<SLUG> BC-NY-GIRLFRIEND-KILLED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTIM IN A STABBING SAW ONLY THE BEST IN HER SCHIZOPHRENIC
FIANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ On a summer night in 1995, there was a
lively backyard party in New Rochelle, with music and hanging
lanterns, and among the guests were Caroline Costello and Michael
Laudor, who whirled around the flagstone patio with the grace of
professional dancers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They looked up at each other and they were clearly, madly in
love with each other,'' recalled Leslie Mignault, the party's
hostess and a friend of the couple.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, two days after Ms. Costello was stabbed to death and one
day after Laudor, her mentally ill fiance, was charged with murder,
Ms. Mignault recalled that summer night to try to explain to a
reporter how Ms. Costello continued a relationship with Laudor,
despite the obstacles presented by his schizophrenia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think she had a choice,'' said Ms. Mignault, with
simple understatement.
</P>
<P>
   That determination to listen to her own heart was consistent
with other shadings in the portrait Ms. Mignault and other grieving
friends drew of Ms. Costello Friday. They said she was an intensely
private and deeply principled person who resisted pressure from her
parents to break up with Laudor, a man whose schizophrenia was
almost outweighed by an even more fundamental shortcoming: He was
not from the Roman Catholic Church in which she had been raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know her family disapproved of her relationship to Michael
because she told me that, and I know that it saddened her,'' Ms.
Mignault said. ``She said she was confident of her relationship to
Michael and that her parents would come around.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Laudor, a tall, bearded man of 35, remained in the
Westchester County Jail awaiting psychiatric examinations and his
next court hearing on July 15. Ms. Costello's parents, who flew in
from Newton, Mass., were waiting for the completion of an autopsy
so they could begin making arrangements for a funeral. Meanwhile,
law-enforcement officials and friends confirmed that Laudor had
told his relatives that he had stopped taking his antipsychotic
medication because it was no longer working for him.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Costello, 37, was slightly built, with light brown hair and
a predilection for demure clothes. About the world, her friends and
Michael, she was upbeat, but about herself she had a tendency to be
deprecating.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had great intellectual abilities, and she was very modest
about them and somewhat insecure about them in the way that many
accomplished women are,'' said Randy Banner, a friend of the
couple.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while her fiance had some impressive achievements despite
his illness _ graduation from Yale Law School and more than $2
million in book and movie contracts _ Ms. Costello was no slacker.
</P>
<P>
   She was born in Portsmouth, Va., outside Norfolk, the site of
the country's largest naval base. Friends say her father, William,
served on naval submarines before he began his current career as a
biostatistician. Her mother, Marilyn, is a registered nurse who was
close to Caroline and her two other daughters.
</P>
<P>
   The family eventually moved to the Boston suburb of Newton,
where Ms. Costello attended public schools, doing so well at Newton
North High School that she was accepted at Yale. She graduated as a
literature major in 1984. Some years afterward, she went to work
for IBM in New Haven, Conn., researching ways to apply computers in
schools. To enhance her specialization, she enrolled in a one-year
master's program at the Harvard School of Education.
</P>
<P>
   It was sometime in 1991, while she was working in New Haven,
that she met Laudor, who was studying law at Yale. He was a witty
and brilliant raconteur, yet deeply spiritual, with a strong
interest in Judaism. He was touched by her generosity and
tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought she was the sweetest person he had ever met and he
found her intensely attractive,'' Ms. Banner said.
</P>
<P>
   It soon became clear to Ms. Costello that Laudor spent a great
deal of energy just attending to daily fundamentals. Staying in a
conversation was sometimes wrenching, given his recurrent
hallucinations.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1994, Ms. Costello took a Manhattan job as associate
director of technology for the Edison Project, an upstart New York
firm trying to prove that it could run public schools better than
public servants could. She was managing the design of a new e-mail
system linking the project's 42 schools.
</P>
<P>
   She and Michael lived together for a time in the Riverdale
section of the Bronx. After Laudor received a $600,000 offer from
Scribner for his life story and a $1.5 million movie deal, they
moved into an apartment in Hastings-on-Hudson with sweeping views
of the Hudson River. Friends whom he had made over the years, like
Ms. Banner and Ms. Mignault, became her friends.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly six months ago, she told Ms. Mignault she wanted to have
a child with Michael, whose father, Charles, had a history of
mental illness as well.
</P>
<P>
   When her body was found on Wednesday in the kitchen of the
couple's apartment, law-enforcement authorities revealed something
only a small circle had known: Ms. Costello was pregnant. To her
friends, it was another indication of her steely commitment to
Michael.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
