<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8454 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-open-HNS &LR;      06-20 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-open-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Stewart slips at 18 
but holds Open lead
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JAYNE CUSTRED &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ Payne Stewart's temper started to rise as his ball
continued to roll back down the 18th green at the Olympic Club on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   What had started out as a 10-foot putt for birdie that would
have extended his two-stroke lead to three in the 1998 U.S. Open
quickly turned into a 25-footer to save par that would come up
short. The 18th had claimed another victim in the second round,
leaving Stewart clinging to a one-shot lead over The Woodlands'
Jeff Maggert and Bob Tway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually thought it would finish up three to four feet below
the hole, and suddenly it's 25,'' Stewart said. ``I commented to
the official walking with us that that pin was unfair. That green
is bordering on ridiculous where that pin is.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his troubles, Stewart's 71 put him at 3-under-par 137.
Maggert and Tway, who both managed to escape the carnage at No. 18,
had rounds of 69 and 70, respectively, to share second place at
138. The only other players under par after two rounds are Lee
Janzen, whose 66 was the best round of the day even with a double
bogey at No. 17; amateur sensation Matt Kuchar (69); and Lee Porter
(67), all at 139.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty players survived the 36-hole cut, which was set at
7-over-par 147.
</P>
<P>
   It was the field against the 18th green Friday. The pin was put
on the back left side of the green, just on the part of the slope
where it was nearly impossible to hold a ball. Anyone who tried to
land an approach shot near the hole got to watch his ball trickle
back down. Anyone who tried to putt close to the pin and missed
experienced the same outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lehman was just one who gave USGA officials ``both barrels''
after his trials at No. 18. Lehman was safely on in two shots,
approximately 35 feet below the hole. From there, he four-putted
for a double-bogey 6, stormed off the course into the scoring area
with his 75 and ripped into the first USGA official he saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who set this up are full of ,'' Lehman said. ``Tell
them that, OK? The 18th green is hard as a rock.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Triplett's' reaction was even more drastic. Already likely
to miss the cut, Triplett had no intention of watching while his
par putt slid below the hole and started back down the green.
Triplett simply put his putter head down on top of the ball,
stopping its progress, and then putted the ball into the cup for
bogey. Of course, he also was slapped with a two-stroke penalty for
interfering with the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just the last frustration of a frustrating day that
wasn't really golf out there,'' said Triplett, whose 79 sent him
packing for home.
</P>
<P>
   David Fay, executive director of the USGA, admitted the decision
to put the pin on the back left of the green might not have been a
good one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not what we hoped would happen,'' Fay said. ``We're not
happy with what happened. We had similar problems there in 1987,
just not as severe. But we didn't want to have the pin on the
bottom of the green for all four rounds. We thought if we put more
water on 18, it would be acceptable. As it turned out, if you were
above the hole or sideways, it was quite difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   While a majority of the second round was lost in the furor at
the 18th hole, there was solid golf played Friday at the Olympic
Club.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart appeared headed for the round of the day, opening with
three consecutive birdies and getting as low as 7-under. But he
lost steam down the stretch, spending too much time in the rough
and picking up bogeys on three of the last five holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the veterans, when they saw me at 6- or 7-under, knew that
it is going to come back,'' Stewart said. ``Everything comes back,
and for this championship, something right around par is going to
be a heck of a golf score.''
</P>
<P>
   Maggert certainly would agree. That's why he was extremely
pleased with his second consecutive 69. Maggert made several bogeys
during the round, which he knew he would, but he also picked up the
birdies when the opportunities were there.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my goals coming in for the week was to try to shoot
each round under par,'' said Maggert, who has finished in the top
four in two of the last three Opens. ``Obviously, that is a tough
goal. But for the first two days, I have managed to do that. So I
feel like I need to shoot under par on the weekend to have a chance
to win. I am certainly playing well enough to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   As is Janzen. He started the day at 3-over but went on a
back-nine run that included birdies on Nos. 11, 15 and 16, which
put him tied for the lead with Stewart at 3-under and headed for a
record round. But a double-bogey 6 on No. 17 after driving into the
deep rough dropped Janzen back to 1-under.
</P>
<P>
   With two rounds to go, almost anyone who survived the cut still
has a chance to win, and Maggert hopes to finally be the last man
standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't come out here to shoot a few good rounds and just
kind of wait to see what happens,'' Maggert said. ``I expect to
play well, and I expect to win. I expect to play well this weekend,
and if I don't, I'll be disappointed. But I like my chances. I feel
good about myself. I'm not here to finish second.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
