<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RILEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROSS-COUNTRY TREK USED TO URGE EARLY CANCER DETECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUSTIN SCHMID  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago, doctors told Jack Riley, 66, he had just six
months to live. No treatment would stop his prostate cancer from
spreading. But Riley's still riding on hope.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's 305 miles into his third Triathlon of Hope, which
started June 16 in San Diego. Riley is running, cycling and
swimming across the United States to raise money for cancer and
preach his early-detection message.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Fox, a Canadian cancer victim, inspired him to organize
the Triathlon of Hope.
</P>
<P>
   Riley's raised more than $200,000 for cancer research since his
first Triathlon of Hope in 1996. But he's not ready to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Though cancer ravages his body, Riley looks healthier than many
people half his age. He's at peace with his fate, but promises to
battle to the end.
</P>
<P>
   Riley, listed in the Guinness Book of World's Records, competed
in 52 triathlons in 52 weeks at age 52. The tenacious ex-fighter
pilot was also a top-10 finisher in Hawaii's grueling Iron Man
Triathlon.
</P>
<P>
   He says this cross-country journey will be the toughest.
</P>
<P>
   Riley, from Alamo, Calif., combats pain in his bones by taking
medication every five hours. He has only one-quarter of the energy
he had during his first Triathlon of Hope in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   His daily mileage has been cut nearly in half, from about 60
miles to 30 miles. He spends most of his time on a bike because
it's easiest on his body.
</P>
<P>
   He still runs into each town carrying his own version of the
Olympic Torch. But this trip isn't about athleticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been there already,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   His real mission is helping wipe out cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors missed his tumor during a screening 10 years ago. When
they detected it five years later, it had spread too far.
</P>
<P>
   Riley says cancer doesn't scare him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to make cancer sorry it ever picked on me!'' he
pledges.
</P>
<P>
   He fights the disease with modern medicine, herbs, a healthy
lifestyle, self-healing and a strong spirit. Riley says the
spiritual element is most important, believing God is his best
defense.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to finish Sept. 16 in New York after swimming from New
Jersey to Ellis Island, where he'll proclaim liberty for all cancer
victims.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the Triathlon of Hope, call 888-700-1850
or visit the Web site at www.oasisofhope.com. &QL; 
 &UR; Justin Schmid can be reached at 444-7474 or at
justin.schmid &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
