<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERGOPIA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLE INDICTED ON CHARGES OF DEFRAUDING LENDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   From all appearances, John Vergopia and his wife, Dixie Summers,
have been living the good life.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the couple bought one of the largest homes in the gated
Scottsdale community of Montana Ranch. They formed several
marketing businesses and showed lenders income tax returns
reporting six-figure incomes. They now sell Arabian horses under
the name of En Vogue International Arabians.
</P>
<P>
   But according to a federal indictment returned against them last
week, the couple have been living a lie.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment claims Vergopia and Summers financed their
$357,000 home by defrauding lenders. It says they also swindled
hundreds of thousands of dollars from unsuspecting customers.
</P>
<P>
   Vergopia and Summers, who refused to comment about their case,
have pleaded innocent and face trial Aug. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale police Detective Paul Arnold said his department
occasionally confronts ``people coming in here from other states
and giving the appearance of being successful business people, when
in fact they're engaged in fraudulent activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold estimated he deals with such cases ``two or three times a
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Maricopa County court records and Scottsdale police records show
that the indictment is just the latest and most serious legal
problem for Vergopia and Summers, both of whom refused interview
requests this week.
</P>
<P>
   Summers has been sued for failure to pay monthly homeowners fees
at Montana Ranch and for failure to pay the lease on a $36,000
Lincoln Town Car. Scottsdale records show that since 1995, police
have been called to the couple's home at least seven times to quell
domestic-violence incidents in which Vergopia reportedly attacked
Summers.
</P>
<P>
   Summers has stalled foreclosure on the house by seeking the
protection of the U.S. Bankruptcy Court.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Mark Aspey said in a court hearing last
week that Vergopia has a string of convictions in New York, New
Jersey and Florida on offenses ranging from assault to disorderly
intoxication to criminal possession of a firearm.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's 12-count indictment charges that, to obtain home
loans, the couple submitted bogus federal tax returns that showed
Summers earned $969,000 from 1993 to 1996, while she reported
income of just $62,000 to the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment charges that Vergopia, claiming to be J. Cuttler,
president of Harvest Group International Ltd., wrote a letter to
lenders, confirming Summers' claims of employment and income.
</P>
<P>
   The case, presented by prosecutor Mark Aspey and FBI agent
Deanne Simpson, also alleges that Vergopia and Summers swindled
$410,000 from customers of their food brokerage businesses.
Vergopia and Summers would collect advance payments from their
customers and then simply pocket the money, according to the
indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Although the indictment offers few details about the scheme, it
charges that the couple swindled a Florida business that won a
civil judgment against Vergopia last year in Maricopa County
Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, the court ruled that Vergopia must pay $414,182 to
DJB Investments Inc. because he failed to deliver on a business
deal to supply Tylenol products at a inexpensive cost. Vergopia
took advance payment of $249,000 but never shipped the goods,
according to court documents. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
