r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKYHARBOR-AZR &LR;      06-20 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKYHARBOR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNCIL POSTPONES PLAN TO ADD GOLDWATER NAME TO SKY HARBOR
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS FISCUS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The name Sky Harbor International Airport lives, at least for
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   After days of receiving angry phone calls from the public _ and
losing support from some council members _ Phoenix Mayor Skip
Rimsza on Friday asked to postpone a final decision on renaming the
airport until Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   In a memo to the council, he instructed City Manager Frank
Fairbanks to set up public hearings during the summer for input on
plans to name the airport after Barry Goldwater.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Rimsza, the Phoenix City Council voted 6-3 this week to
rename the airport to honor Goldwater, the U.S. senator and
presidential nominee who died May 29 at age 89.
</P>
<P>
   But to become final, Tuesday's vote would have to be formally
adopted at the council's July 1 meeting. Some council members _
struck by the intense public outcry against the name change _ said
they talked with the mayor in recent days and asked him to delay
the July 1 vote. Rimsza relented Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the memo, Rimsza wrote that he felt the council ``did exactly
what we're elected to do. Still we have heard the pleas from
people. People who love Barry Goldwater. But people who want us to
hear their ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the public hearings won't necessarily be limited to the
name of the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have a lot of ideas,'' Rimsza said. ``In the
end, people were complaining about process, so I want to clear that
up and let them have an opportunity to vent their ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Many who called City Hall this week asked that the airport name
be left alone, but that other spots in the city _ such as Squaw
Peak or a proposed north Phoenix desert pre serve _ be named for
Goldwater.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the public hearings are still being worked out, but
the sessions could be scheduled for late July and early August.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix Councilman Cody Wil liams voted against renaming the
airport Tuesday because of his concern that people didn't have a
voice in the decision. He said Friday that he approves of the
postpone ment _ if people's concerns will actually be heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is just a facade to create the allusion that the
public has had a chance to address the issue, then we're adding
insult to injury,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His concern is to have all the information available, including
the cost of a name change and how it could affect marketing efforts
to increase the awareness of ``Sky Harbor'' in foreign nations.
</P>
<P>
   News of the delay also was a relief to such residents as Judy
Clarke of Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fit to be tied when I heard they were going to change
the name `Sky Harbor,' '' she said. But she said Friday that she
was ``thrilled at the idea of the public input.''
</P>
<P>
   Clarke said she is not anti-Gold water. She appreciates his work
as a statesman. Her father worked with Goldwater and her parents
voted for him when he ran for president. It's just that ``Sky
Harbor is just too beautiful a name. It's unique in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Doug Lingner made the motion Tuesday to rename the
airport ``Goldwater Sky Harbor International.'' By Friday, he said
he had a change of heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since then we've heard from a lot of other people and it's
apparent to me . . . some sort of community input _ aside from
telephone calls _ is necessary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a feel-good ges ture,'' he said. ``I want them to
have the opportunity to share with us their concerns and wishes . .
. my decision will be based on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rimsza, though, is standing firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I know and feel tells me this is the right thing to
do,'' the mayor wrote to the council. ``I'll never do anything less
than that. That's why I will be voting to name the airport after
Barry Gold water. He deserves the Grand Can yon _ but this will do
just fine.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Chris Fiscus can be reached at 444-8697,
 &UR; or at chris.fiscus &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
