<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTIN MAKES THE CUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The worst of Casey Martin's problems Friday was
that he tripped over a few of his newfound fans, which gives you a
pretty good gauge of how grand a day it was for the disabled
golfer.
</P>
<P>
   While continuing to win friends and influence people, Martin
also managed to make the cut at the U.S. Open on his very first
try. By chasing his opening-round 74 with a 1-over-par 71, the
golfer who has created headlines all week for becoming the first
player in U.S. Open history to use a cart moved one giant step
closer to his ultimate goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to be known more as a golfer than a person with a
disability,'' said Martin, who was born with a rare circulatory
disease in his right leg that makes walking painful. ``Making the
cut in the U.S. Open gives me confidence. I think if I just keep
improving I can be out here and really be a steady fixture.''
</P>
<P>
   His cart ran fine Friday, but it's a wonder Martin didn't run
out of gas emotionally. He continues to be overwhelmed by the
outpouring of support he is receiving from his galleries. Call them
Casey's Crusaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been just a great experience,'' Martin, 26, said.
``The crowd support and just playing in the U.S. Open, period, is a
blast. I am having a great time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bitten by No. 18: Before the 18th green went one-on-one with
Payne Stewart and won, it practiced on former Pepperdine standout
Brent Geiberger.
</P>
<P>
   Some two hours before Stewart stroked an 8-foot birdie putt that
missed the hole by inches and trickled 25 feet down the glassy
slope, Geiberger had stood over virtually the same putt, with the
exact same results.
</P>
<P>
   The difference was, Stewart's 3-putt finish merely trimmed his
lead to one stroke while Geiberger's 3-putt put him on the wrong
side of the cut by one stroke, at plus-8.
</P>
<P>
   Geiberger, who tacked on a 77 to his opening-round 71, had no
way of knowing it at the time, but he would miss the cut by a
matter of inches, which is how close his comeback putt came to
falling.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old called the pin placement ``illegal'' _ an
opinion echoed by Stewart who called it ``bordering on the
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore fades: Jason Gore, another former Pepperdine standout, got
off to a sizzling start. He birdied the par-5 first hole and the
par-4 fourth to get to 5-over-par with a bullet. In his own mind,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I was thinking I could get myself into contention,''
said Gore, who had opened with a 77. ``I was thinking of (shooting)
a 65.''
</P>
<P>
   Bogeys on three of the next five holes served as a rather harsh
reality check on the way to a second-round 76. The good news is the
course in Greensboro, N.C., where the Hart High graduate is headed
for next week's Nike Tour event, is going to seem like a
pitch-and-putt layout next to the Olympic Club's Lake Course.
</P>
<P>
   ``This course just wears on you,'' Gore said. ``It's going to
make every golf course I play from now on seem really easy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
