<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 00:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8465 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHUNG-DEMS-FUNDS-525&AMP;     06-20 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHUNG-DEMS-FUNDS-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY ALARMS WERE SOUNDED OVER CHUNG DONATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: This is a late add to page 1 of the New York Times.)  
(lh) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Not long after Johnny Chung and his checkbook were
welcomed into Democratic fund-raising circles, some senior party
officials worried that he posed a potential problem.
</P>
<P>
   There were suspicions that the struggling California businessman
was using the White House to raise consulting fees from the Chinese
businessmen that he escorted to fund-raising events in Los Angeles
and Washington. As early as March 1995, the Democratic National
Committee's finance director, Richard Sullivan, said, he raised the
possibility that Chung was a conduit for illegal foreign money from
China.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a sense that he might be taking money from them and then
giving it to us, you know,'' Sullivan said in his deposition with
Senate investigators last year. But those concerns apparently did
not prevent the Democrats from accepting a $125,000 check from
Chung, which led to access for him and several Chinese businessmen
to a dinner at the home of the filmmaker Steven Spielberg. Not long
after that check cleared, the Democratic National Committee
chairman, Donald Fowler, said the ``Democratic Party is lucky to
have'' Chung.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, Fowler and other leading Democrats say they feel
betrayed by Chung, who embarrassed them again last month when it
was revealed that he told federal investigators that he had
funneled nearly $100,000 from a Chinese military officer to the
Democrats in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Chung's account represents the first hard evidence of the
``China Plan'' to influence the U.S. presidential election in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats and White House officials repeatedly asked Chung
for money and never said no to any of Chung's contributions leading
up to the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, Chung, a southern California businessman, pleaded
guilty to campaign-related bank and tax fraud charges, and he is to
be sentenced July 20. While cooperating with the Justice
Department's campaign finance inquiry, Chung has described for
federal investigators his view of what Democratic fund-raisers knew
_ and should have known _ about his contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Brian A. Sun, Chung's lawyer, confirmed that Chung had given
detailed briefings about his conversations with Democratic party
officials to investigators, but he refused to divulge any details.
</P>
<P>
   There was no secret among Democratic officials that Chung was
aggressively promoting his fax business. He asked both the party
and the White House to hire his company (both declined). And at
nearly every fund-raising event he attended, Chung had escorted
Chinese businessmen who were anxious to meet the president.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Chung feels stung that the Democrats have blamed him for
the troubles that he brought to the party, Sun said. ``What is
troubling to Mr. Chung is the suggestion that the DNC was a victim
in this,'' he said. ``The DNC's fund-raisers were willing
participants.''
</P>
<P>
   But Peter J. Kadzik, a lawyer for the Democratic committee, said
that any accusations by Chung against party fund-raisers are
``baseless.'' He said there was no reason for party leaders to ever
suspect that Chung's donations came from anyone other than him. He
said Chung, as he awaits sentencing, ``has every reason to point
his finger at others.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-98 0042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980620.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 00:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8467 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHUNG-DEMS-FUNDS-2NDT     06-20 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHUNG-DEMS-FUNDS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: at others.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chung and his company, Automated Intelligent Systems Inc., gave
the Democrats a total of $366,000, all of which has since been
returned because of questions about its origins. And nearly
$100,000 of those contributions, he recently told federal
investigators, originated with Liu Chao Ying, the Chinese military
officer whom he escorted to meet President Clinton at a Brentwood,
Calif., fund-raising dinner in July 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Chung got his first taste of political gift-giving in the summer
of 1994 when he attended a governor's association convention in
Washington and the president's 48th birthday party, a fund-raising
event. He donated $10,000 and brought several associates to the
party, and was given status as a ``DNC trustee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when Johnny realized that if you make a donation, you
get something in return,'' Sun said.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 19, Chung's fax company gave $40,000 to the Democrats.
The following day, Chung and Shi-Zeng Chen, a Haomen beer magnate,
attended a White House Christmas party, and had their pictures
taken with the president and Mrs. Clinton. The photo with Clinton
would be used to sell beer in Beijing in a billboard display.
</P>
<P>
   Just two months later, Chung planned on bringing five Chinese
business executives to Washington. He asked for a meeting with
President Clinton, a meeting with Vice President Gore, lunch at the
White House mess, permission to attend the President's weekly radio
address, and other perks.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the White House tour, the request was rejected by
Sullivan, whom Chung described as his ``primary contact'' at the
Democratic National Convention in his proffer given last summer to
the Senate committee investigating campaign finance abuses. Indeed,
Sullivan referred the matter to Fowler, who helped make
arrangements for Chung and the Chinese delegation to attend the
radio address.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, then the finance director, has said he felt
``uncomfortable'' about Chung because he kept bringing Chinese
businessmen to fund-raising events.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan declined to comment for this article.
</P>
<P>
   Stymied by the Democratic committee, Chung took his request to
the first lady's office, and asked for help in arranging a White
House tour and lunch at the White House mess. He handed over a
check for $50,000 to Mrs. Williams inside the White House, which
the Senate committee said, ``apparently made it possible for Chung
to achieve what had hitherto been denied him: his clients'
attendance at President Clinton's weekly radio address on March 11,
1995.''
</P>
<P>
   The president told aides that he regretted the fact that Chung
was able to get several Chinese businessmen into his radio address.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1995, Scott Pastrick, the party treasurer, traveled to
California to ask Chung for more money. Chung agreed to write the
party a $125,000 check, which bought him and several Chinese
businessmen seats at a fund-raising dinner at Spielberg's home.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, Chung again attended a Democratic
fund-raiser, this one for the Clinton-Gore campaign in California.
Chung, who took 19 guests to the $1,000-a-plate dinner, gave a
check for at least $20,000, but he was later told he needed 20
separate $1,000 checks.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, Chung rounded up checks from his employees and
friends of friends, but he reimbursed them for their contributions.
Although a campaign worker had warned Chung not to do that, Sun
argued that the fund-raisers had to know that Chung had no choice.
``At that time, Johnny doesn't understand the vagaries of campaign
finance law,'' Sun said.
</P>
<P>
   In the next year, Chung would give another $100,000, and be
asked to give much more, Sun said. Speaking of Democratic
fund-raisers, the lawyers said, ``These guys would have been a lot
smarter if they just fessed up and said they just wanted Johnny's
money and got carried away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
