<DOCNO> NYT19980620.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8470 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STADIUM-AZR &LR;      06-20 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STADIUM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIO SALADO FOOTBALL STADIUM COMPLEX PLAN UNVEILED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LISA GONDERINGER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Backers of a new stadium for the Arizona Cardinals unveiled the
largest project in state history Friday, a $2.3 billion mega sports
and convention complex on the Tempe-Mesa line surrounded by hotels,
housing, shops, restaurants, office buildings and parks.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed 900-acre project, called Rio Salado Crossing, could
one day be home to 15,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Private investors would foot about four-fifths of the bill for
the mini-city, including $200 million from the Cardinals. The team
claims that figure, greeted with thunderous applause, is one of the
largest contributions a National Football League team has made to a
new stadium project. The team would contribute $75 million
immediately, and the rest later on.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; An additional $1.694 billion is expected to be ponied up by
private developers involved in the retail, hotel and residential
parts of the project over the next 10 years. Backers say some of
those developers already have signed onto the project, but would
not identify them. In other cases, deals are still being worked
out.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the hefty private investment, the project still will
have to land as much as $489 million in public funds.
</P>
<P>
   Most of that, $320 million, would come from a 20-year
quarter-cent sales tax that must be approved by voters in Mesa and
Tempe. It would go toward public parks and recreation, the
convention center and mass transit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been very careful to make sure public funds would be
used for the public parts of the project,'' said Julie Pace,
chairwoman of the Rio Salado Crossing Association, which has been
working furiously since September to retool the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``People told us loud and clear that they did not want to fund a
football stadium. They wanted something that would give back to the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   An additional $169 million will be collected from sales taxes
generated from businesses within the project, including hotels,
restaurants, shops and concessions inside the stadium. The majority
of those dollars would join the Cardinals' contribution to the $299
million stadium, which is to have a retractable roof.
</P>
<P>
   The Mesa and Tempe city councils must now decide if they want to
form a convention-facilities voting district that would complete
negotiations with developers and put the tax on the November
ballot. Only Tempe and Mesa residents would be subject to the tax.
</P>
<P>
   The plan will die if either city decides not to join the
district, or if either city's voters reject the tax.
</P>
<P>
   Several council members at the unveiling, including Hugh Hallman
and Joe Spracale of Tempe and Bill Jaffa of Mesa, said they were
ready to get the issue on the ballot. But they were quick to say
that doesn't mean they are in favor of the tax.
</P>
<P>
   Others, such as Mesa Councilman John Giles and Tempe Mayor Neil
Giuliano, say they want more concrete financial details before they
will support forming a stadium district.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got pretty pictures, but not a lot of substance,'' Giles
said. Dennis Kavanaugh, also on the Mesa council, said he saw huge
potential in the project, but worried that too many complex
questions would have to be answered too quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a world-class facility, so why rush it?'' said Dave
Spaur, Mesa's economic development director. ``Its not like anyone
is going to take away that land.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pace said it is crucial to get the tax on the November
ballot while the economy is still good, bond rates are favorable
and investors are willing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may not be the case six months from now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The project would stretch for three miles along the south bank
of the dry Salt River bed and include land in Mesa, Tempe, and
unincorporated county islands.
</P>
<P>
   Its centerpiece is a futuristic-looking Arizona Exposition and
Convention Center, which, its advocates say, would catapult the
state into the top tier in competing for large conventions. It
would be the 16th largest center in the country, with 1 million
square feet of space, and would be attached to the state's largest
hotel, with 1,250 rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Valley is really losing out when it comes to landing the
most significant conventions,'' Pace said. ``In the last five
years, Phoenix has only hosted one of the top 200 conventions in
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The 67,000-seat football stadium is part of the same building.
When not in use, the field can be rolled away from the building and
the floor can be turned into extra convention space.
</P>
<P>
   Pace said other cities, such as Indianapolis and St. Louis, have
been successful in similar projects that combine stadiums and
convention centers.
</P>
<P>
   The state-of-the-art stadium would have one end &UR; zone in Tempe
and the other in Mesa, as well as two huge glass doors _ 150 feet
high and 240 feet wide _ on the northern end that would give fans a
panoramic view of Squaw Peak, Camelback Mountain and Mummy
Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Just south of the stadium would be a sizable retail and
entertainment district, that could include big-name tenants such as
the All-Star Cafe and the PGA Tour Shop. It would include the NFL
Experience, an interactive football theme park.
</P>
<P>
   There are also plans, later in the development, to add almost
3,000 more hotel rooms in resort and smaller suite hotels. A
whopping 2 million square feet of office space and more than 6,000
condominiums, apartments and single-family homes are also in the
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Backers envision 15,000 people living within Rio Salado Crossing
and 8,000 to 10,000 working there.
</P>
<P>
   Pace said she thinks one of the biggest selling points is that
two-thirds of the project is devoted to open space, including four
new parks linked by 10 miles of trails, 12 acres of lakes and
waterways and three 18-hole public golf courses.
</P>
<P>
   The park system, which will link Scottsdale's Indian Bend Wash
and Tempe's Rio Salado greenbelts, will include a rock climbing
wall, urban fishing, paddle boats, water taxis, a skateboard park
and a 1,500-seat amphitheater.
</P>
<P>
   If the tax passes, ground could be broken on the first phase as
early as November 1999. That construction would include the
convention center, stadium and hotel complex; 2,000 condo and
apartment units; 350,000 square feet of retail space; and the first
park and golf course, to be located on the western end. It would be
ready to go by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Other phases, including single-family homes and other hotels,
could take as long as 10 years to come online.
</P>
<P>
   The project has changed drastically since the East Valley
Partnership started looking at whether a new Cardinals stadium was
feasible two years ago. The team has long contended that Sun Devil
Stadium is inadequate, too hot for fans and puts them at a
competitive disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership quickly learned they would have to add other
elements, such as a convention center, to the mix to make it
profitable and to sell it to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Pace said the size of the Cardinals' contribution and the fact
they only want to be a tenant rather than a major owner, should
help ease public bitterness about funding sports projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so much more,'' she said. ``It will leave an economic
development mark on the Valley for decades.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Lisa Gonderinger can be reached at 444-7967 or at
lisa.gonderinger &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL; 
 &UR; republic writer Bob Petrie contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
