<HEADLINE>
COURSE BITES STEWART LATE, HOLDS LEAD TO 1 SHOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Payne Stewart's pleasure cruise at the U.S. Open
officially came to a screeching halt yesterday in the same place it
began _ on the closing holes of the Olympic Club.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who took control of the leader board with birdies on
the final three holes in Thursday's opening round, frittered away
three strokes to the field over the final five holes yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, a lead that once stood at five strokes dwindled to
one heading into the weekend rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who fashioned a second-round 71 to remain 3 under par
for the tournament, stands a stroke ahead of Bob Tway and Texas A&AMP;M
graduate Jeff Maggert (2 under). Three others are at 1 under: Lee
Janzen, Lee Porter and U.S. Amateur champ Matt Kuchar.
</P>
<P>
   None of the other 156 starters managed to crack even-par through
two rounds at the 6,797-yard, par-70 layout, where the average
score for yesterday's second round was 74.4. The cut fell at 7
over, allowing 60 players _ the Open minimum _ to play this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart had things going early. He took birdies on the first
three holes, reaching 7 under. But he backslid with bogeys at Nos.
14, 17 and 18, opening the door to a variety of pursuers heading
into the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 25 pursuers remain within seven strokes, including
past major-championship winners Nick Price (1 over), Scott Simpson
(3 over), Tom Lehman (3 over) and John Daly (4 over). The group
also includes David Duval (3 over), Colin Montgomerie (4 over) and
Phil Mickelson (4 over).
</P>
<P>
   Among the notables to survive the cut were disabled golfer Casey
Martin (5 over), Fort Worth resident Mark Brooks (6 over), Tiger
Woods (6 over) and Jack Nicklaus (7 over).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a nip-and-tuck finish,'' Stewart said. ``It
looked like I was going to run away for a while, but that just
doesn't happen in a U.S. Open. I knew I was going to give some
back. You just hope you don't give back too many.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, a former SMU standout who won the 1991 Open, gave back
one he was not counting on at No. 18. After knocking his approach
shot to eight feet, Stewart watched in amazement as his birdie putt
made a hard left turn just before the cup and rolled 20 feet
downhill.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he joined several players in criticizing the U.S.
Golf Association's pin placement at No. 18, where Daly had a
40-foot birdie putt die an inch from the cup but roll backward four
feet before stopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that pin was unfair. When you have balls roll up, then
roll back away without stopping, that's bordering on ridiculous,''
Stewart said. ``I don't know if you would call it an illegal pin,
but I know I wasn't the only player who spoke to the USGA's walking
marshal about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he was not. The pin placement drew enough complaints
that USGA executive director David Fay all but issued a post-round
apology, saying that officials ``miscalculated'' the severity of
the slope at the 347-yard par-4 that elicited an average score of
4.22 in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, we expected it to be the most difficult spot on the
green,'' Fay said. ``But it didn't turn out the way we'd hoped.
We're not happy with what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Janzen, the 1993 Open champ, shrugged off the challenging pin at
No. 18 more easily than he shrugged off the double bogey at No. 17
that dropped him out of a tie with Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come to the U.S. Open expecting nothing to be fair,'' said
Janzen, whose 66 marked the lowest score of the second round. ``If
you hit it in the rough, you can't get it to the green. If you hit
the green, it's hard to two-putt. ... It's a test of wills. You
find out who overcomes adversity the best and who has the most
patience.''
</P>
<P>
   After dropping his seventh birdie putt of the round at No. 16 to
grab a share of the lead, that appeared to be Janzen. But he gave
back two strokes with a double bogey at No. 17 after a drive into
the rough.
</P>
<P>
   Among the front-runners, Maggert and Kuchar were the only
players who did not lose ground at No. 17, a par-4 that played to a
scoring average of 4.68 strokes per player and is rapidly emerging
as the probable pivotal hole of the weekend rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Maggert, at this juncture, remains the only player in the field
to break par in both rounds at Olympic.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal coming in was to shoot each round under par,'' said
Maggert, who slept on the lead heading into the final round of the
1997 Open but finished fourth. ``Obviously, that is a tough goal.
But if I can do that, I am going to be right there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
