<HEADER>
A8472 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-astroslede-HNS &LR;      06-20 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-astros </SLUG>
 lede-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros keep 
Reds reeling
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Despite allowing five hits in the first inning Friday night, Sean
Bergman knew he was making good pitches.
</P>
<P>
   He just needed to hear it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty sure they were good pitches, but when you hear it
from your catcher, it makes a difference,'' said Bergman, who
pitched eight strong innings in the Astros' 4-2 victory over the
Cincinnati Reds at the Astrodome. ``I came in after the first
inning, and Brad (Ausmus) told me to keep making good pitches, that
they had been hitting good pitches, and not get discouraged, and
try to stay aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   The pep talk worked.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman settled down after the Reds' two-run first inning,
limiting Cincinnati to four hits and no runs over the next seven
innings en route to his sixth victory of the season. Carl Everett
went 2-for-3 with two runs batted in, and Ricky Gutierrez added
three hits as the Astros extended their lead in the National League
Central to three games over the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got five hits off Bergman, and only one of them was hit
hard,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said. ``That's tough to deal
with. In the first inning, it might be a little easier because you
know your team has a long way to come back, but still he survived
that. That's something a lot of pitchers have trouble with when
they face first-inning difficulty. Once he got rolling, he was
hitting his spots and changing speeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati, which has been held to two or fewer runs in 11 of
its last 14 games, received consecutive one-out singles from Mike
Frank, Barry Larkin, Willie Greene and Dmitri Young in the first
inning. Bret Boone added an RBI single in the inning as Bergman dug
himself into an early hole. From that point, with the exception of
a threat in the fifth, the Reds didn't come close to scoring again
as they suffered their sixth straight loss and 14th in their last
17 games.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman (6-3) allowed two runs and nine hits in eight innings.
Billy Wagner pitched a 1-2-3 ninth for his 17th save.
</P>
<P>
   Everett ignited the Astros' comeback with his seventh home run
of the season, a solo shot to right field in the second inning that
sliced the Reds' lead to 2-1. He added an RBI double during the
Astros' three-run fourth inning and has driven in 15 runs in his
last 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so timely, because if you play Carl all year, he's going
to have times when he struggles, just like Jeff Bagwell has, like
Derek Bell has, and everybody has and will,'' Dierker said. ``For
him to have his hottest streak of the year when (center fielder)
Richard Hidalgo is out of action is a blessing for us. I hope he
can continue, because Richard is not that close to coming back. He
has really filled that void and then some.''
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo suffered a separated shoulder on May 30 at Colorado, and
Everett has started the last 19 games in his place.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first year I've ever started this early, and I'm
getting those consistent at-bats. That will help anyone,'' said
Everett, who is batting .615 (8-for-13) during the Astros' current
homestand. ``Everybody on this team wants to do well and help the
team. This is not a team of egos. This is a team that chips in and
tries to do the best it can.''
</P>
<P>
   Reds starter Scott Winchester, who pitched six shutout innings
against the Astros five days earlier, had no such luck as the
Astros took command of the game in the fourth inning. Jeff Bagwell
led off the inning with a double and advanced to third on a
groundout by Moises Alou. Everett then doubled to pick up his 36th
RBI of the season and knot the score at 2.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros tagged Winchester for two more runs in the inning.
Ricky Gutierrez lined a 2-2 pitch into the left-center-field gap to
score Everett with the go-ahead run, and Ausmus followed with an
infield hit down the third-base line. Craig Biggio provided the
final blow with a two-out chopper over third base, his second hit
of the game, scoring Gutierrez for a 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Winchester (3-4) allowed four runs and nine hits in five
innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds' only other significant scoring threat came in the
fifth, when they put runners at second and third with two outs
before Bergman coaxed Eddie Taubensee into an inning-ending flyout
to center field.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman retired the final nine batters he faced, making him a
popular man with the Astros' bullpen. His eight-inning effort
enabled Dierker to give his beleaguered relief corps a rest, not a
small thing with three of the Astros' next four games scheduled for
afternoon starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was pretty significant in terms of what has happened in
the last three or four games with the way the guys in the bullpen
have been used,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Bolstered by some early encouragement, it was the least Bergman
could do.
</P>
</TEXT>
