<HEADLINE>
SELLERS CLAIMS THREE OF FOUR ALL-STAR RACES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ Before fans even had a chance to get
comfortable in their seats, the suspense was gone. Shane Sellers
saw to it right away that last night's NTRA All-Star Jockey
Championships had all the drama of a Tiger Woods tap-in, or a
September pennant race with the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers won the first two races of the four-race event at Lone
Star Park at Grand Prairie to open a commanding lead, and then for
good measure added another victory in the final race.
</P>
<P>
   That meant the 32-year-old Louisiana native _ practically a
young whippersnapper amid the Hall of Famers _ finished the
competition with an unbeatable 36-point total and took bragging
rights back to Kentucky along with the $25,000 first prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those situations where the horses ran for me,''
Sellers said. ``I've always been a firm believer that when you get
to be a certain caliber of rider, the only thing that separates you
is (the horse) between your legs.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Krone won the other race and finished second with 18
points. Jerry Bailey recorded two seconds and wound up third with
12 points.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's winner, Gary Stevens, was hampered by a weak draw
and scored only three points.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers won aboard Shareef Dancer (2nd), Miami Flyer (4th) and
Mocha Express (7th). Krone took the 6th race with Illusive Ghost.
</P>
<P>
   But for this night, at least, the horses were secondary,
especially once the astounding payoffs were posted for Lone Star's
new All-Star wager, where fans could wager on the jockeys over the
four-race series rather than the horses. Given the mounts they
received, the Sellers-Krone-Bailey trifecta was entirely
predictable, and yet it paid a whopping $670.60 for a $2 wager. The
exacta paid $150.80.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers, one of the leading riders in Kentucky, hadn't had much
luck at Lone Star before last night.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he rode Skip Away to a disappointing third-place
finish in the inaugural Texas Mile. He returned to Lone Star two
months later for the first All-Star jockey competition, and
finished 10th among the dozen riders.
</P>
<P>
   But Sellers has won more than 3,000 races in his career,
including some big ones. He is best-known for riding Skip Away to
an upset victory over Cigar in the 1996 Jockey Club Gold Cup, and
for winning last fall's Breeders' Cup Juvenile Fillies on Countess
Diana.
</P>
<P>
   And he has an All-Star championship to put on his resume.
Sellers dedicated the victory to fallen friend Robby Albarado, who
went down in a spill three days ago at Churchill Downs in
Louisville, Ky., and sustained a fractured skull. Albarado
underwent surgery to have a titanium plate placed over the
fracture, but is expected to miss only a few weeks of riding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat Day is my idol,'' said Sellers, who wore Albarado's
monogrammed undershirt beneath his riding silks, ``but Robby is one
of my best friends. I didn't tell anybody, but I dedicated this
championship for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
