<SLUG> BC-CARDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL CARDINALS LEAVE WITHOUT NEW STADIUM? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Cardinals say they are committed to Arizona, but it's
unclear whether that commitment extends beyond this fall, when the
fate of a proposed stadium is determined.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are an integral part of the proposed Rio Salado
Crossing, a $1.5 billion development project that includes a $299
million, retractable-roof stadium that is in turn part of a
convention center. The stadium would seat 67,000 for most games but
could be expanded to 78,400 with the addition of bleachers in its
north end.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has assured project backers that a new facility would
earn the Valley at least one Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bidwill, Cardinals vice president and general counsel,
said the Cardinals aren't thinking about plans beyond this
November. That's when voters in Mesa and Tempe could be asked to
consider a quarter-cent sales tax that would help fund portions of
the project other than the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've put an attractive plan together, and that plan should
run its course,'' said Bidwill, a son of Cardinals owner Bill
Bidwill. ``We've said all along we're committed to the Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   But for how long? And if the proposal is defeated, will the
Cardinals look to move to another city? Bidwill declined to answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to focus on November,'' he said. ``That's what we're
interested in doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The stadium portion of the project will be funded in part by the
Cardinals, who will contribute $75 million toward construction,
provided the team's lease agreement is comparable to those of other
NFL teams.
</P>
<P>
   The team also has agreed to pay $50 million over 25 years to
cover game-day operating costs. In addition, the team will invest
$75 mil lion in other parts of the development, including retail
shops and hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bidwill has been the Cardinals' point person on the
stadium issue, while his father has stepped into the background.
Bill Bidwill did not attend Friday's meeting of the East Valley
Partnership, where the plans were announced.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bidwill pointed out that in the past three years 13 of
15 referendums on sports facilities throughout the country have
been approved by voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``And many of them had far less contributions than the team has
committed to today,'' Bidwill said. ``We're excited about that
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals believe Sun Devil Stadium is antiquated by NFL
standards. Among the complaints are that the heat makes it
uncomfortable for fans early in the season, and restroom and
concession facilities are inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   A new stadium also will mean more money to the Cardinals through
various sources, including additional ticket revenue, luxury-box
sales, advertising and sponsorships.
</P>
<P>
   Naming rights alone could be sold for $40 million to $50 million
over a 20- to 25-year period, and most teams receive a hefty chunk
of that money.
</P>
<P>
   A new stadium and a favorable lease also dramatically increase
the value of a team. The Cardinals, valued at $187 million last
year, would be worth well over $200 million with a new stadium,
experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Bidwill said the Cardinals need a new facility ``to remain
competitive, to have the ability to keep our premier players and
attract new marquee, premier players.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-98 0058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980620.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8476 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LIVERY-SLAYING-625     06-20 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LIVERY-SLAYING-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM A PROMISING PATH TO A CHARGE OF MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As he left his Queens home on Tuesday night, Tae Wook
Yoon walked by a letter in the living room accepting him into a
military academy, and his dream of becoming a law-enforcement agent
still seemed a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   But hours later, after a losing night at the pool tables with
friends, the police said, Yoon did something antithetical to that
dream: putting a gun to the neck of a scared livery-cab driver, and
then, with the jerk of a finger, ending the man's life.
</P>
<P>
   The bullet that killed the driver, Hyong Kyu Kim, also traveled
through Yoon's arm, sending him to North Shore University Hospital
in Manhasset, N.Y., where he was arrested. He later told the police
that he and his three friends had decided to rob a cabdriver in
Bayside, Queens, to pick up some cash for pool games, said
investigators speaking on condition of anonymity. They added that
he said the gun went off accidentally, the mistake of a novice.
</P>
<P>
   Yoon, 16, and two friends now face charges of murder and
attempted robbery. One of the friends, Samuel Chung, 17, a student
at Bayside High School, was arrested Thursday morning, and the
other, Eric Chi, 16, a student at Stuyvesant High School in
Manhattan, was taken to the 111th Precinct station house in Bayside
Friday afternoon by his lawyer, the investigators said. A fourth
suspect, a 15-year-old who attends Valley Forge Military Academy in
Pennsylvania, had not been arrested, and the Queens district
attorney's office was negotiating with his lawyer, the
investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Yoon's father, Won Yoon, said Friday that he was heartbroken
that instead of helping his son prepare for his entrance into
Valley Forge, he was now searching for a lawyer to help keep him
out of prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a bad dream,'' said the elder Yoon, who recently
opened a Korean restaurant in Flushing, where the family lives. He
added that he believed that his son's friends were responsible for
the crime. ``He is a good kid, a bright kid, active in sports. He
wanted to be an FBI agent, that's why he was going to Valley
Forge,'' the father said. ``But he started hanging out with these
bad friends and started getting into fights. He said he couldn't
control himself.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``My wife and I are so sorry that this happened to
this man.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends and family members said Yoon's change from a bright
young boy to a murder suspect happened gradually. Yoon never missed
Sunday services at the local Baptist church and was a star athlete
at school, winning a trophy for his abilities on the track. He was
a friend to the neighbors who had watched him grow up on Georgia
Avenue, friends and family members said.
</P>
<P>
   He had been an excellent student at the Bronx High School for
Science, but he began cutting classes about a year ago and started
hanging out with several other youths he met at two pool halls in
Queens, according to family members, friends and school records.
</P>
<P>
   Yoon emulated some of his new friends in sporting a bright
yellow streak in his hair, a common emblem of the gang called
Korean Power, the police and friends said.
</P>
<P>
   Yoon told his parents that many of his problems were related to
the school and that he did not fit in there. They transferred him
to Francis Lewis High School in Flushing in February. But the
problems continued, and he was put on a list of chronic truants,
school officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was shy, and said he was getting picked on because he was a
new face,'' Won Yoon said. ``He said he just didn't want to go to
school.''
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager's friends had troubles similar to his own,
according to school records. Chung was failing every class, while
Chi was suspected of being a gang member.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jacob Burke, 17, a friend of Yoon's, said he asked Yoon a few
weeks ago whether he was involved in the Korean Power gang. ``He
said that he'd thought about it, but was not a member yet,'' Burke
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   He said he also asked about Yoon's friends, who were ``just
aggressive, thinking they were big and bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke added, ``When he told me that his group was getting into a
lot of fights with other Korean kids, I told him that it just
wasn't worth the pain and agony.''
</P>
<P>
   The police said Yoon hatched the robbery plot with his friends
late Tuesday night. As Wednesday morning approached, Yoon phoned
Twin ABC Call Taxi in Flushing and asked that a car pick him up at
a pool hall. Kim arrived and drove Yoon to 47th Avenue and 206th
Street in Bayside. Yoon pulled out a gun and demanded money, the
district attorney's office said.
</P>
<P>
   A shot rang out as Yoon's friends left their own car in the
shadows and began to approach the idling livery cab, the police
said. They added that all four suspects fled as Kim, a recent
immigrant who was trying to make enough money to bring his wife
from Korea, lay dying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
