<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARROS' HOMER BEATS ROCKIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Eric Karros knows breaking even just isn't going to do
for the Dodgers. It isn't going to help catch the San Diego Padres
and it certainly won't let manager Bill Russell keep his job.
</P>
<P>
   So for the second night in a row, Karros made the difference,
hitting a 10th-inning homer Friday night to give the Dodgers a 4-3
victory over the Colorado Rockies in front of 48,120 at Coors
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Karros could see things slipping away when the Colorado Rockies
tied the game with two runs in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   But as he did Thursday with five RBI that included a three-run
homer, Karros took control. With three regulars sidelined, Gary
Sheffield ejected and Raul Mondesi still wobbly playing with a
sprained left ankle, Karros surprisingly got a fastball from Jerry
DiPoto (2-3).
</P>
<P>
   He drove it 422 feet and hobbled around the bases on a left knee
he says is getting better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last few days I've had more mobility with the knee,''
Karros told broadcaster Rick Monday on the Dodgers post-game show.
``I don't know if it is a coincidence or not, but I feel much
better at the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   No Dodger felt very good after closer Scott Radinsky allowed a
two-run pinch single by Greg Colbrunn in the eighth that tied the
score 3-3 and ruined seven strong innings by starter Darren
Dreifort.
</P>
<P>
   The runs belonged to Greg McMichael, who came in to start the
eighth, but the pressure has been on Russell and Radinsky after a
shaky month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have anyone else to put out there,'' Russell said.
``But he is still throwing hard and with good movement. He's just
having trouble finding the strike zone. He'll keep going out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't seem so bad after Karros' homer. Antonio Osuna (3-0)
struck out three in the 10th, including fastball-loving Vinny
Castilla to end the game. Osuna threw a fist in the air and
motioned Castilla back to the Rockies dugout.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies, now 11-22 at home, were forced to put reigning NL
MVP Larry Walker on the disabled list with pain in his surgically
repaired right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna's move was a little trashy, but the Dodgers know what it
is like to be down.
</P>
<P>
   Still tinkering with their makeshift lineup, the Dodgers
re-acquired 1B/OF Matt Luke from Cleveland, which released him, and
designated outfielder Thomas Howard for assignment. The move was
designed to give Karros some relief for his knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This season is a long process,'' executive vice president Fred
Claire said. ``I don't know if any team has been through what we've
been through and it isn't even July. You hope to get to the point
where you are four games over, then six and eight and able to put
everything else aside.''
</P>
<P>
   For the third consecutive game, Russell used a lineup without
slumping third baseman Bobby Bonilla and injured second baseman
Eric Young. The Dodgers also were playing without catcher Charles
Johnson, who missed the first of two games to attend his
grandmother's funeral in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort was coming off a 4-2 loss to the Rockies last Saturday
and didn't start Friday's game much better.
</P>
<P>
   He walked Neifi Perez to lead off the bottom of the first and,
one batter later, hit Dante Bichette with a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   An RBI single by Ellis Burks gave the Rockies a 1-0 lead. They
then loaded the bases when Todd Helton walked, but Dreifort pitched
out of the jam when third baseman Paul Konerko made a back-handed
stop and touched the bag to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Holding the Rockies to just one run seemed to help Dreifort
refocus.
</P>
<P>
   For the next five innings, he retired 14 of 15 hitters. Helton
was the only one to reach when he singled with one out in the
third, but he was erased on a double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the second straight game I had trouble at the
beginning,'' Dreifort said. ``When I got to the dugout after the
first, they got me to relax and refocus. It seemed to help. Plus
the defense was great.''
</P>
<P>
   By the sixth, the Dodgers led 3-1. Roger Cedeno, who ran the
Dodgers out of a first-inning rally trying to take third on a
grounder to short, singled with one out in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Vizcaino took a called third strike, but Sheffield drilled
Astacio's first pitch into the left-field stands.
</P>
<P>
   It was Sheffield's 11th homer and fifth as a Dodger.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers added their third run in the sixth after stringing
together four consecutive hits with one out.
</P>
<P>
   Konerko was first, singling to right. After starting the trip 2
for 11, Konerko went 2 for 3 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Prince, playing in place of Johnson, followed with another
single to right and Castro loaded the bases by grounding a single
between short and third.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort came in batting just .160, but he singled to left to
score Konerko and give the Dodgers a 3-1 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
