<P>
   NATIONAL _ GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `w' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ In a significant test of
strength, the coalition supporting bipartisan legislation to
overhaul the campaign finance law won a series of House votes on
Friday and drew an unexpectedly large number of Republicans to its
side. On one key test, 65 Republicans voted to preserve the
legislation sponsored by Reps. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., and
Martin Meehan, D-Mass. The bill is one of a dozen proposals up for
consideration in a free-for-all over the campaign finance laws. By
Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CHUNG-DEMS-FUNDS (Washington) _ Not long after Johnny Chung and
his checkbook were welcomed into Democratic fund-raising circles,
some senior party officials worried that he posed a potential
problem. As early as March 1995, the Democratic National
Committee's finance director, Richard Sullivan, said, he raised the
possibility that Chung was a conduit for illegal foreign money from
China. By Don Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI-CORRUPT (Miami) _ Bribery. Kickbacks. Voter fraud.
Cover-up. Even as law-enforcement officials promise more arrests,
the city of Miami is now engulfed in a series of high-profile
investigations that have uncovered a wave of such pervasive public
corruption it is now often mentioned in the same breath as New York
during its Tammany Hall days. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   SPOCK-DIET-HEALTH (Undated) _ The late Dr. Benjamin Spock,
arguably the most influential pediatrician of all time, has left
children and their parents with a surprising and rather demanding
legacy: advice that they stick to a vegetarian diet devoid of all
dairy products after the age of 2. In the seventh edition of his
world-famous book, ``Baby and Child Care,'' issued last month by
Pocket Books just weeks after his death at age 94, he recommends an
approach to childhood nutrition that many experts, including his
co-author, Dr. Steven J. Parker, consider too extreme and likely to
result in nutritional deficiencies. By Jane Brody.
</P>
<P>
   PRESBY-GUNS (Undated) Striking an unusually personal note in the
national debate on gun control, the top policy-making body of the
Presbyterian Church (USA) has passed a resolution calling on the
denomination's 2.6 million members to ``work toward removing
handguns and assault weapons'' from their homes and communities.
Presbyterian officials and other church leaders said the assembly's
resolution takes a new tack in asking directly for individual
action by church members, rather than seeking governmental
legislation. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DEAF-MEXICANS (New York) _ The 49 deaf Mexican men and women
whose ordeal as virtual slaves in a quiet Queens County
neighborhood shocked New York and attracted national attention will
be allowed to stay in the United States, federal officials said on
Friday. By Mirta Ojito. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-GUIDE (Washington) _ In an abrupt change of plans,
Clinton administration officials said on Friday that they would
restrict the initial distribution of a new consumer guide on the
Medicare program because they feared that millions of elderly
people would be utterly confused by its description of new health
insurance options. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   BRILL-ARTICLE (Undated) _ If Steven Brill had simply written an
opinion column for his new magazine, condemning the news media for
their conduct in the coverage of the Monica Lewinsky investigation,
Washington might have been able to ignore it. If all he had done
was to get Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel, to admit leaking
information to reporters, the storm might have passed after a brief
downpour of headlines. But what Brill did this week in the
inaugural issue of his media review, Brill's Content, was far more
brazen and ultimately subversive of the insular culture of the
nation's big newspapers and networks. By David Firestone. (With
photo.)
</P>
<P>
   MANZANAR-NATIONAL-SITE (Lone Pine, Calif.) _ During World War
II, this lonely stretch of scrub off Highway 395 was the largest
outpost between Los Angeles and Reno. It had a Bank of America
branch and a hospital of 250 beds, plus an orphanage, a hog farm
and chicken ranch. But Manzanar was no ordinary town. Behind its
armed guards and barbed wire fences it housed 10,000
Japanese-Americans who were brought here against their will in the
mass hysteria that followed the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor. By
Todd S. Purdum. (With photo and map.)
</P>
<P>
   VIAGRA-INSURANCE (Undated) _ Some of the nation's biggest health
insurers have decided not to pay for Viagra, the new male impotence
drug in their prescription drug plans. They said that providing the
recommended 6 to 12 pills per month would add hundreds of millions
of dollars to their annual costs. By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   THERAPEUTIC-RIDING (Undated) _ A growing number of physical and
occupational therapists are using horses in treatment, contending
that the physical rigors of riding strengthen the limbs and muscles
of people with cerebral palsy, multiple sclerosis, paraplegia and
other disabilities. And some proponents of therapeutic riding go
even further, asserting that the emotional bonding and mental
discipline involved can help children with autism and patients with
addictions and a range of emotional and behavioral problems. By
Barbara Stewart. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-COCA-HERBICIDE (Bogota, Colombia) _ The Colombian
government, bowing to demands from anti-narcotics officials in
Washington, has agreed to test a granular herbicide to kill coca
crops, despite public warnings from the chemical's American
manufacturer against its use in Colombia. By Diana Jean Schemo.
(With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   KASHMIR-WEDDING-DEAD (New Delhi, India) _ In one of the worst
attacks on Hindu civilians in nine years of war in Kashmir, 25 men
taking part in wedding parties were killed on Friday by gunmen
armed with automatic weapons. By John F. Burns. (With map.)
</P>
<P>
   CYPRUS-CONFLICT (Istanbul, Turkey) _ Greece and Turkey are at
odds again over the divided island of Cyprus, with Greek planes
landing on the island and Turkish planes screeching overhead in
retaliation. The latest quarrel reflected the fact that although
the Cypriot dispute is ostensibly between the Republic of Cyprus
and the ethnically Turkish enclave in the north, the greater
conflict is between their patron states, Greece and Turkey. By
Stephen Kinzer. (With map.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS DAY
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `f' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOCH-TRIAL-VERDICT (Topeka, Kan.) _ A court fight in one of the
longest-running, nastiest, and most bizarre family business
disputes ended on Friday as a federal jury here halted the efforts
of William Koch, one of the nation's richest men, to win $2 billion
from two brothers who, Koch contends, cheated him a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   BERKSHIRE-GENERAL (Undated) _ Warren Buffett's company,
Berkshire Hathaway, acquires General Re, one of the world's leaders
in providing insurance to insurance companies, for $22 billion. By
Joseph B. Treaster. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   MCDONALDS-OVERHAUL (New York) _ All 13,500 McDonald's outlets in
North America are expected to be overhauled by the end of next year
at a total cost of up to $380 million, the company said. The
process has begun slowly, with only about 600 kitchens remodeled in
the last year. But the company believes the initiative will help
reverse its sagging share of the U.S. market. By Dana Canedy. (With
photo and graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   KOCH-TRIAL-VERDICT (Topeka, Kan.) _ One of the longest and
nastiest family disputes ended Friday, sort of, as a working-class
jury blocked efforts by William Koch, one of the United States'
richest men, to get $2 billion from two of his brothers whom he
accused of cheating in a business deal over a decade ago. By Leslie
Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   WORLDCOM-MCI (Frankfurt, Germany) _ After more than a month of
negotiations, European antitrust regulators on Friday tentatively
approved WorldCom Inc.'s $37 billion takeover of MCI Communications
Corp. after the merging companies agreed to concessions in the sale
of MCI's Internet holdings, industry executives involved in the
negotiations said. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stock prices fell again Friday as Wall
Street closed out a volatile week just the way it began: with waves
of large-scale selling. Shares tumbled across the board, hitting
blue-chip issues the hardest, in an extremely heavy trading session
that saw the Dow Jones industrial average drop 100.14 points, or
1.14 percent, to close at 8,712.87. By David Barboza.
</P>
