<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ OVERPOWERS ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Juan Gonzalez is chasing a major-league record that
has stood for 68 years, but more important than the end result is
what he does along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez increased his major league-leading RBI total to 86 with
a three-run double and a two-run homer Friday night, leading the
Texas Rangers to a 7-3 win over the Angels before 38,866 at Edison
Field.
</P>
<P>
   With the win, the Rangers moved to within one-half game of the
Angels in the AL West, with a chance to regain first place this
afternoon when the teams meet again.
</P>
<P>
   With 86 RBI in 72 games, Gonzalez is on a pace to finish with
194 RBI. Hack Wilson set the record with 190 in 1930. Friday night
marked the fifth time this season Gonzalez has had five RBI in a
game.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not Gonzalez can continue his record march remains to
be seen, but he came up big when the Rangers needed it Friday.
Gonzalez came to the plate to face Chuck Finley with the bases
loaded, two out and the game tied at 2 in the top of the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Finley got ahead in the count 1-2 before Gonzalez ripped a line
drive into the right-center field gap, scoring all three. It broke
Gonzalez's first notable RBI drought of the season _ going into
Friday's game, Gonzalez had only one RBI in his previous seven
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw him two splitters in the dirt that he swung at and
missed,'' Finley said. ``I thought there was no way he'd be looking
for a fastball off the plate. I thought there was no way he could
get it, and if he did, it would be a ground ball to second. But
he's so big and strong, it went all the way to the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing you do is you tend to second-guess yourself.
But I won't do that. I made a good enough pitch to get eight other
guys in the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez got the opportunity to hurt Finley only because Angels
first baseman Cecil Fielder had booted a ground ball for the second
time in the game. His error in the fourth inning led to an unearned
run for the Rangers, but the one on Luis Alicea's grounder in the
seventh proved more costly.
</P>
<P>
   That gave the Rangers runners on first and second with one out,
but Finley struck out Roberto Kelly for out No. 2. Finley then
walked Rusty Greer, loading the bases for Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Fielder had not made any errors in his 40 previous starts going
into Friday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't the first time and it ain't going to be the last,''
Fielder said of his errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy's got as good of hands as any first baseman in the
game,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said. ``Tonight was just one
of those nights.''
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth inning, Gonzalez hit a 400-foot line drive over the
fence in left-center off Shigetoshi Hasegawa for his 22nd homer and
a 7-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I was patient,'' Gonzalez said of his big night.
``When I'm patient, I do well. I have a lot of concentration,
especially with men on base. It's important. It's my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers starter Rick Helling (10-3) tied teammate Aaron Sele for
the league league in victories by going seven-plus innings and
allowing three runs and nine hits, including Jim Edmonds' 14th
homer of the year. Helling struck out five and walked none.
</P>
<P>
   Finley (7-4) got the loss, his second in less than a week to
Helling and the Rangers. Helling beat Finley 4-2 last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Finley could not be blamed for this one, however. He went 62/3
innings, allowing five runs and six hits. But because of Fielder's
errors, only one run was earned.
</P>
</TEXT>
