u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHUNG-DEMS-FUNDS-1STL     06-20 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHUNG-DEMS-FUNDS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-600(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRAT CITES EARLY SUSPICION OVER DONATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs for additions and refinements; changes throughout)  (lh) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Not long after Johnny Chung and his checkbook were
welcomed into Democratic fund-raising circles, some senior party
officials worried that he posed a potential problem.
</P>
<P>
   There were suspicions that Chung, a struggling California
businessman, was using the White House to raise consulting fees
from the Chinese business executives whom he escorted to
fund-raising events in Los Angeles and Washington. The Democratic
National Committee's finance director, Richard Sullivan, said that
as early as March 1995 he raised the possibility that Chung was a
conduit for illegal Chinese money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a sense that he might be taking money from them and then
giving it to us, you know,'' Sullivan said in his deposition with
Senate investigators last year.
</P>
<P>
   But those concerns apparently did not prevent the Democrats from
accepting a $125,000 check from Chung, which led to access for him
and several Chinese businessmen to a dinner at the home of
filmmaker Steven Spielberg. Not long after that check cleared, the
Democratic National Committee chairman, Donald Fowler, said the
``Democratic Party is lucky to have'' Chung.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, Fowler and other leading Democrats say they feel
betrayed by Chung, who embarrassed them again last month when it
was revealed that he told federal investigators that he had
funneled nearly $100,000 from a Chinese military officer to the
Democrats in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Chung's account represents the first hard evidence of what
Republicans said was a plan by China to influence the U.S.
presidential election in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats and White House officials repeatedly asked Chung
for money and never said no to any of Chung's contributions leading
up to the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, Chung pleaded guilty to campaign-related bank and
tax fraud charges. He is to be sentenced July 20. While cooperating
with the Justice Department's campaign finance inquiry, Chung has
described for federal investigators his view of what Democratic
fund-raisers knew _ and should have known _ about his
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Brian A. Sun, Chung's lawyer, confirmed that Chung had given
detailed briefings about his conversations with Democratic Party
officials to investigators, but he refused to divulge any details.
</P>
<P>
   There was no secret among Democratic officials that Chung was
aggressively promoting his fax business, Automated Intelligent
Systems Inc. He asked both the party and the White House to hire
his company. (Both declined.) And at nearly every fund-raising
event he attended, Chung had escorted Chinese business people who
were anxious to meet the president.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Chung feels stung that the Democrats have blamed him for
the troubles that he brought to the party, Sun said. ``What is
troubling to Mr. Chung is the suggestion that the DNC was a victim
in this,'' he said. ``The DNC's fund-raisers were willing
participants.''
</P>
<P>
   But Peter Kadzik, a lawyer for the Democratic committee, said
that any accusations by Chung against party fund-raisers are
``baseless.'' He said there was no reason for party leaders to ever
suspect that Chung's donations came from anyone other than him. He
said Chung, as he awaits sentencing, ``has every reason to point
his finger at others.''
</P>
<P>
   Chung and his company gave the Democrats a total of $366,000,
all of which has been returned because of questions about its
origins. And nearly $100,000 of that money, he recently told
federal investigators, originated with Liu Chao Ying, the Chinese
military officer whom he escorted to meet President Clinton at a
Los Angeles fund-raising dinner in July 1996.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   His associates recall a Los Angeles fund-raiser on Sept. 21,
1995, when two party fund-raisers asked Chung for $70,000 before
they permitted him to bring three guests, including a Chinese beer
company executive, to meet Clinton at a private reception.
</P>
<P>
   Chung agreed to give the money, and he and his guests were
permitted to meet with Clinton. But two months later, Chung still
had not donated the money he had pledged. Ari Swiller, a party
official, asked Fowler to call Chung and ask for the money,
according to an internal Democratic committee memorandum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell him if he does not complete his commitment, ASAP, bad
things will happen,'' Swiller wrote to Fowler in a memo Nov. 10,
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a tongue-in-cheek comment between the chairman and
me,'' Swiller said. ``In no way did I mean any threat to come upon
Johnny.''
</P>
<P>
   Chung got his first taste of political gift-giving in the summer
of 1994 when he attended the president's 48th birthday party, a
fund-raising event. He donated $10,000 and brought several
associates to the party, and was given status as a ``DNC trustee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when Johnny realized that if you make a donation, you
get something in return,'' Sun said.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1995, Chung planned on bringing five Chinese business
executives to Washington. He asked for a meeting with Clinton, a
meeting with Vice President Gore, lunch at the White House mess,
permission to attend the president's weekly radio address, and
other perks.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a White House tour, the request was rejected by
Sullivan, whom Chung described as his ``primary contact'' at the
Democratic National Convention in his proffer given last summer to
the Senate committee investigating campaign finance abuses. Indeed,
Sullivan referred the matter to Fowler, who helped make
arrangements for Chung and the Chinese delegation to attend the
radio address.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, then the finance director, has said in the Senate
deposition that he felt ``uncomfortable'' about Chung because he
kept bringing Chinese businessmen to fund-raising events.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan declined to comment for this article.
</P>
<P>
   Stymied by the Democratic committee, Chung took his request to
the first lady's office. He handed over a check for $50,000 to the
First Lady's then chief of staff, Margaret Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The president told aides that he regretted that Chung was able
to get several Chinese businessmen into his radio address.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1995, Scott Pastrick, the party treasurer, asked Chung
for more money. Chung agreed to write the party a $125,000 check,
which paid for seats at a fund-raising dinner at Spielberg's home.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, Chung again attended a Democratic
fund-raiser, this one for the Clinton-Gore campaign in California.
Chung, who took 19 guests to the $1,000-a-plate dinner, gave a
check for at least $20,000, but he was later told he needed 20
separate $1,000 checks.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, Chung rounded up checks from his employees and
friends, but he reimbursed them for their contributions. Although a
campaign worker had warned Chung not to do that, Sun argued that
the fund-raisers had to know that Chung had no choice. ``At that
time, Johnny doesn't understand the vagaries of campaign finance
law,'' Sun said.
</P>
<P>
   In the next year, Chung would give another $100,000, and be
asked to give much more, Sun said. Speaking of Democratic
fund-raisers, Chung's lawyer said, ``These guys would have been a
lot smarter if they just fessed up and said they just wanted
Johnny's money and got carried away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
