<SLUG> BC-BKW-LIBERTY-SPARKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBERTY LOSES TO SPARKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JAY PRIVMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Liberty can not wait to get home, not after opening its
Women's National Basketball Association season with four losses in
five games. Its trip to nowhere ended in Inglewood, Calif., Friday
night, with a 78-75 loss to Los Angeles at the Great Western
Forum. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Leslie scored 19 points and set a WNBA record with 21
rebounds in leading the Sparks. Haixia Zheng had 19 for Los Angeles
(2-2). The Liberty was led by Sophia Witherspoon, who had 18
points. Rebecca Lobo and Vickie Johnson had 17 each, and Kym
Hampton had 15. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty was playing for the second straight night, having
defeated Sacramento by 64-48 on Thursday. It had lost its first
three games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   After trailing by 12 points at halftime, the Liberty rallied to
tie the game at 55-55 with 9 minutes 30 seconds remaining in the
game. The Liberty closed to within 2, at 55-53, with 10:04
remaining when Witherspoon drove the lane to score, was fouled and
sank the subsequent free throw. And then Lobo's 8-foot shot tied
the game.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sparks then scored seven consecutive points, to go up by
62-55, and led the rest of the way. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty was a victim of poor shooting during crunch time.
The team made less than 40 percent of its shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty made just four of its first 18 shots and went
8-for-30 at halftime. Witherspoon (1-for-7), Hampton (1-for-5) and
Lobo (1-for-4) all shot poorly. The Liberty missed all five of its
3-point attempts. And the Liberty had just two offensive rebounds
in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Theresa Weatherspoon landed hard when fouled with 15.3 seconds
remaining in the game, and though she stayed in to shoot her free
throws, she was limping noticeably. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty returns to Madison Square Garden for its home opener
Sunday against Utah. The team will also play at the Garden on
Tuesday against Cleveland and on Friday against Sacramento.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   also play at the Garden on Tuesday against Cleveland and on
Friday against Sacramento.
</P>
</TEXT>
