<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 02:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8497 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      06-20 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON OF OLD STOPS M'S FIVE-GAME SKID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A couple of innings into Randy Johnson's latest start
of a tortuous season Friday night at the Kingdome, Oakland
outfielder Jack Voigt asked teammate and former Mariner Mike
Blowers for a read on the Big Unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike made a comment: `He's on a mission,''' Voigt said. ``I
fully agreed.''
</P>
<P>
   So did 33,212 fans who couldn't have been quite sure what they
were going to get, as well as a clubhouse full of Mariners. What
materialized was a 9-1 Seattle victory born of Johnson's eight-hit,
12-strikeout performance over eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   While there is plainly some fan skepticism over Johnson's
motivation this year, it was never in evidence. When he took the
mound, he was greeted without a boo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was awesome,'' said catcher John Marzano. ``Randy was
Randy.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy as Randy, 1998, means you reach into a vast grab bag. On
this night, he had the mid-90s fastball and the blistering slider
and he pitched inside just enough to make it all the more
effective.
</P>
<P>
   The game might have meant more to Mariner management than it did
to the Mariners. The club has insisted it won't trade Johnson (6-6)
in this fractious, on-again, off-again season, which might be mere
lip service. At least, after a personal three-game losing streak in
which Johnson had yielded 14 earned runs, the brass knows it still
has something marketable.
</P>
<P>
   Marzano, backup to Dan Wilson, caught him for the second time as
a Mariner. It seems Johnson threw in the bullpen twice since his
7-3 loss to the A's last Saturday, caught both times by Marzano,
and subsequently, Johnson asked to have Marzano stay with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that has success,'' Lou Piniella, the Mariner
manager, said dryly, ``has a chance of continuing.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella and pitching coach Stan Williams also worked earlier
this week with Johnson on a mechanical refinement, trying to get
him to be less upright on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk to Randy about that,'' Piniella said. Nobody did, because
Johnson isn't entertaining reporters these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pitched inside real well,'' Piniella said. ``That's one of
the things we talked about. It made his slider more effective.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners made economic use of seven hits, the most damaging
a first-pitch grand slam by David Segui off Oakland starter Blake
Stein in the second inning. To that point, the M's were 7-for-53
(.132) with the bases loaded in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys write that B.S.,'' Segui scoffed. ``We don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Ken Griffey Jr. parked his 28th homer to stay within
shouting distance of St. Louis' Mark McGwire (33), and Alex
Rodriguez had his 25th, each to the opposite field.
</P>
<P>
   But what made almost as much difference as Johnson was the fact
that for a night, the M's discovered a club that kicked the ball
around as much as they do.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland shortstop Miguel Tejada gifted the Mariners a six-pack
of runs all by himself as the M's took a 7-0 lead after two
innings. A three-run first should have been one run, but Tejada
muffed a double-play throw from Stein and the M's tacked on two
more.
</P>
<P>
   An inning later, Tejada's leaping relay throw on another
double-play attempt, this one on Rodriguez, went low for an error
and sustained the inning. Griffey and Jay Buhner walked, and Segui
mashed one to straightaway center field, 429 feet away, to break it
open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget it,'' Tejada shrugged philosophically, referring to a
night that would grow to three errors. ``The game is over, right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Blowers, who had two stints with the Mariners, had any
success against Johnson, but he probably won't brag about it. The
third baseman from Spanaway dunked a soft double down the
right-field line, and had two singles that didn't escape the
infield.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Voigt, who struck out three times against
Johnson. He had one nine-pitch at-bat, resulting in a called third
strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``After he threw me the third or fourth fastball, I just
decided, anything that was spinning, I was going to take,'' Voigt
said. ``I didn't think he could locate the slider, and he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen him enough to know that tonight, he was on.''
</P>
<P>
   Marzano's second-ever time catching Johnson was less eventful
than the first. Last Aug. 3 in Milwaukee, it was Johnson,
frustrated with himself in a day-long struggle that resulted in a
6-5 victory, who made a barehand catch of a Marzano throw back to
the mound, resulting in a finger problem that later affected him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was intense, really focused,'' Marzano said. ``If he can do
that, he can dominate any team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
