<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 09:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8544 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     06-20 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE WORLD NEEDS A PUBLIC AND SWEATY GESTURE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LYON, France _ There cannot be many more grungy acts in the
world than putting on a soggy jersey just removed from somebody
else's sweaty body.
</P>
<P>
   However, in the interests of world peace, that is exactly what
the players from the United States will propose at the conclusion
of their historic game with Iran on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Right out in public: ``Here, feller, here's my shirt. It's a
little heavy right now. I've been wearing it for the last 90
minutes. Nice game. See you down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the glorious tradition of soccer, with players seeking
each other out on the field and exchanging shirts. Exactly the
right gesture between two nations that have not been on speaking
terms for, oh, a couple of decades.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one thing wrong with this picture: Shirt-swapping
is against the official rules of the world soccer body, but we all
know that rules are made to be broken or, at the very least, to be
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a great picture _ the surfer-boy blonds and
African-Americans and buzz-cut Yanks walking off the field in
Iranian game shirts, and the Iranians walking off the field in the
red, white and blue uniforms of the Great Satan itself.
</P>
<P>
   This is the post-game plan formulated by the Yanks, ever since
that capricious, windy evening in Marseilles last fall, when the
United States and Iran were drawn into the same group.
</P>
<P>
   A cosmic joke, perhaps, but one that has taken on importance in
recent days. Did you ever think it would come down to this, nearly
20 years after the hostage crisis in Iran? The sport of soccer,
which causes the eyes of many Americans to go utterly blank, is
suddenly a vital instrument of diplomacy. Then again, remember what
a few games of table tennis did for relationships between the
United States and China.
</P>
<P>
   It is surely no coincidence that President Clinton and Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright have issued open gestures of
rapprochement to Iran. What better time than when the whole world
is watching?
</P>
<P>
   The players insist that this is merely a game, that they have no
political motivation against Iran. They do have considerable soccer
motivation, however, since they need a victory over Iran to have
any chance to advance into the second round of this World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   After a wimpy and shoddy performance against Germany, in which
they lost, 111-53, in basketball numerology, the Yanks have no
reason to be overconfident, or even confident, against Iran. The
Iranians can run all day and kick ankles just like anybody else in
the world. People back home should know this. Expect nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the potential humiliation for the world's most
powerful nation (except on the soccer field), there is room for
some positive posturing that could nudge citizens and leaders into
a more civil dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Americans back home should turn on ABC early. With any luck, the
network will not be selling beer or soft drinks during the pregame
ceremony, which is always so touching in the stadium. Normally, the
two teams march on the field, side by side, and the captains
exchange banners. Sunday will be a little different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch this space,'' advised Keith Cooper, an official with
FIFA, the world soccer body, who noted that Sunday just happens to
be Fair Play Day.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said that some extraordinary ceremony is planned for the
two teams before the game. An oriental bow? A Levantine-style kiss
on the lips? A European smooch on both cheeks? A hearty Western
handshake? Cooper would not say, but he did say it would be
friendly and brief.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may sound a little naive,'' Cooper said, ``but we plan to
treat this as just like the other 63 games.''
</P>
<P>
   Right. Which is why the U.S. president and the secretary of
state are standing on 10-foot step ladders to wave the olive branch
to Iran.
</P>
<P>
   FIFA's pregame gesture will be fine, but the real gestures will
come after the lads are finished planting cleats in each other's
thighs, as normal. When the final whistle blows, will the Iranians
accept a sweaty shirt from the Yanks?
</P>
<P>
   ``We plan to shake hands and offer our shirts,'' said U.S. coach
Steve Sampson.
</P>
<P>
   It is against the rules, Cooper noted, adding, ``We ask them not
to exchange shirts on the field, partially as a matter of
decorum.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexi Lalas questions that legalism. ``What is the point of
that?'' he said. ``Everyone knows we fight for 90 minutes, and
exchanging jerseys is about fair play. I want to give the people
the idea that we are not enemies. We are here to play soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Cooper said the players just might expose
undershirts hawking one sponsor or another, and FIFA cannot have
that kind of commercialism, can it? For another thing, ``We like to
have them off the field as soon as possible for security reasons,''
Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   At the World Cup, the players are encouraged to swap shirts in
the tunnel under the stands. That just will not fly Sunday night.
The world needs to see them meet on the churned-up pitch, pulling
off their own sodden shirts and replacing them with jerseys
drenched with the sweat of an opponent. Then let the two nations
find more hygienic ways of patching things up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-98 0910EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
