<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 09:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8547 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-20 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NOW AND THEN, US VS. THEM  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hitler showed up at one boxer's bon voyage party and President
Roosevelt told the other boxer, ``Joe, we're depending on those
muscles for America.'' Their bout was promoted as the undercard for
World War II. At the least, it would be the Fight of the Century.
</P>
<P>
   And so, on June 22, 1938, at Yankee Stadium, Joe Louis, the
world heavyweight champion, defended his title against Max
Schmeling. It was a rematch. Schmeling had won the first fight.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty years later _ even with Muhammad Ali's refusal to be
drafted and the Mexico City Olympics intervening _ that second
Louis-Schmeling fight seems somehow out of a sporting past too
quaint to comprehend. Sunday, as the United States soccer team
plays Iran in the first round of the World Cup, most fans are hard
put to dredge up more than a passion just for soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Athletes representing Nike versus Reebok, OK, but representing
ideologies? How could our fathers and grandfathers buy such hype?
Louis was the first African-American heavyweight since Jack Johnson
who was allowed to get close to that symbol of ultimate manhood,
the heavyweight crown. He was beautiful to watch; he had fast hands
that threw short punches in furious combinations. But it was his
willingness to act the mumbling, nonthreatening Negro who never
openly chased white women or gloated over fallen white men that got
him fights with white contenders.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Brown Bomber (also called the Sepia Slugger, the
Dark Destroyer and the Tan Tornado) beat Max Baer in 1935, he was a
symbol for African-Americans. From his strength, according to the
writer Richard Wright, ``they took strength, and in that moment all
fear, all obstacles were wiped out, drowned.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis believed his press. He was unbeatable, the ``bushmaster,''
according to the premier sportswriter Grantland Rice, with ``the
instinctive speed of the wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis brought golf clubs to camp while training for his first
fight against Schmeling, in 1936. A former world heavyweight
champion, Schmeling had been disowned by the Third Reich after
losing to Baer, who was Jewish. But after Schmeling pounded Louis
for 12 rounds before dropping him, Goebbels declared the fight a
``splendid patriotic achievement.'' Schmeling sailed home
triumphant and Louis slipped offstage to plot his return.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hitler flexed his muscles in the so-called Nazi
Olympics of 1936, a spectacle of pageantry that became the standard
for all the Games to come. American groups, including the Amateur
Athletic Union, had tried to stop U.S. participation, based on
clear violations of the Olympic charter _ non-Aryans had been
excluded from German teams. But Avery Brundage, the U.S. Olympic
chief, called his critics Communists and prevailed in a close vote.
</P>
<P>
   These were the Berlin Games in which Jesse Owens won four gold
medals and was credited with ``embarrassing'' Hitler _ even while
the Nazis dismissed the African-Americans as ``the black
auxilliaries.'' Owens returned to America to run against horses for
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the quintessential example,'' said Harry Edwards, the
Berkeley sociologist who instigated the 1968 Black Power Olympic
protest, ``of how America has historically utilized black athletes,
black celebrities, in ways that were conducive to its broader
political interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards was talking about Louis, too. Schmeling deserved the
next title shot against Jim Braddock, but Louis got it because
American boxing did not want the championship, and all the money it
generated, to leave the country. Political groups were recruited;
better a Negro champion than a Nazi champion.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-nine years ago, June 22, 1937, Louis became the first
black heavyweight champion since Jack Johnson lost the title in
1915. One year later, after three title defenses, he met Schmeling
again. As often happens, the ``steam up'' _ with uniformed American
Nazis marching for Max and gospel choirs singing for Joe and
endless socio-pugilistic pontification _ was better than the fight.
A breathless crowd of 70,000 paid a million dollars to watch Louis
hammer Schmeling helpless in the first and only round.
</P>
<P>
   Louis, who had been, according to Paul Gallico, ``a primitive
puncher just emerging from the pit,'' was now, in the words of
Jimmy Cannon, ``a credit to his race, the human race.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis did more for others, as affirmation and inspiration, than
he was able to do for himself in later life. The cost of living a
double life _ Louis chased all women and repressed a lively
personality and a racial consciousness _ included drug addiction
and madness. Sometimes sitting in a wheelchair, he greeted
customers to a Las Vegas casino. He died in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Schmeling, who served in the German paratroopers during the war,
became a wealthy businessman. It would be reported, years later,
that he was privately anti-Nazi and had hidden the children of a
Jewish friend. He is still alive.
</P>
<P>
   Each new generation is supposed to make its own lessons from the
past. So maybe we can learn about Joe from the Chinese kids who
rooted for Michael, and the soccer fans who watched Germany
overwhelm the United States last week and will watch the United
States against Iran on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-98 0912EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980620.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 09:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8548 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-20 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE JOKE'S ON HIM  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Have you heard the one about John McCain?
</P>
<P>
   The famously noble politician got up at a Republican fund-raiser
last week and made a now-infamously ignoble joke.
</P>
<P>
   He is so revered by the press that his disgusting jape was
largely nudged under the rug. ``It's like a return to the Kennedy
era,'' said one magazine editor. ``He makes a gaffe, and we look
the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of Washington is the story of why smart people do dumb
things. And why pols can swing fitfully between doing the right
thing and doing the wrong thing.
</P>
<P>
   McCain made it through five years of torture in North Vietnam.
The Arizona senator has also been brave in Washington, inciting the
wrath of his party and powerful lobbies with quixotic battles for
the best causes: campaign finance reform and making Big Tobacco
kick its habit of marketing to kids.
</P>
<P>
   In a capital where politicians follow more than lead, McCain has
been an edifying exception. Even though his independent streak and
quick temper have made him Republican enemies, his idealism and
easy way with the press got him on the short list for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   So how does such a lofty figure sink to the basement?
</P>
<P>
   The joke that he thought was funny was about Chelsea Clinton,
Hillary Rodham Clinton and Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the bad boy,'' he said in a phone interview. ``It was
stupid and cruel and insensitive. I've apologized. I can't take it
back. I could give you a whole bunch of excuses, but there are no
excuses. I was wrong, but do you want me crucified? How many days
does it need to be a story?''
</P>
<P>
   He said the senator who spoke just before he did to the
Republican fat cats made a tasteless joke about Viagra. ``So I got
up and said, `You think that was a tasteless joke? Listen to this
one.' The minute it came out of my mouth, I thought, `Oh no, this
is a terrible mistake.'''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, defensively, ``I will always maintain a sense of
humor. Life is too short not to.''
</P>
<P>
   Life is also too short for making the president's daughter the
target of a junky, misogynistic crack masquerading as humor.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he wrote a letter of abject apology to the
president. That's good politics. But where's the letter to Janet
Reno? He says he doesn't think that such a letter is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Because the president and McCain have been working together on
the campaign finance and tobacco issues, the White House response
was muted. ``It takes a severe lapse in synapses to make a joke
about personal things like that,'' says Clinton spokesman Mike
McCurry, who has occasionally lost control of his own synapses.
``Most prominent people at one time or another have a close
encounter with the distasteful.''
</P>
<P>
   It is downright weird that McCain would be the one to break the
taboo against cheap shots at the lovely and self-possessed Chelsea.
He said he thought he'd heard the joke on Jay Leno. But Leno, not
one to shrink from the tasteless, protests: ``I've never, ever done
a Chelsea joke, nor would I. Political humor is like the Mafia _
everything's open game as long as you don't go after the
families.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Imus was befuddled by the blunder of one of his favorite
guests. ``It's horrible, yecchhh! This guy is a genuine American
hero. I don't know why they do it. Some idiotic effort to be one of
the guys. Like me at the correspondents' dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm flummoxed. After so many politicians have humiliated
themselves or ruined their careers with stupid ethnic and sex
jokes, from Earl Butz ``joke'' about blacks to Bob Kerrey's
``joke'' about lesbians to Al D'Amato's ``joke'' about Judge Lance
Ito _ why do they keep doing it?
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't stop,'' says Alan Dundes, a folklorist and expert
in the anthropology of humor at Berkeley. ``It's part of the male
arsenal of weapons to make your way in the world. If McCain is
worried about being too liberal for his colleagues, this is one way
of indicating that he's one of the Republican boys _ attacking the
Democratic president by attacking his women. Since ancient times,
you get at your male opponent by violating his women. If the
women's honor is lost, the man's honor is lost. McCain was in the
military. He knows you conquer enemies by feminizing the men and
putting down the women.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain will survive. But he may have learned a lesson about the
politics of virtue. The holier they come, the harder they fall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-98 0914EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980620.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 09:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8549 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-20 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: FIGHTING CITIZEN ABUSE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Richard Emery filed the lawsuit that led to the
transformation of city government several years ago. The Board of
Estimate, controlled to a great extent by Democratic Party bosses,
was abolished and the powers of the mayor and the City Council were
enhanced.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Emery said he believes the changes have
worked reasonably well. ``We're seeing our first big budget
battle,'' he said. ``It's over a corollary issue (Yankee Stadium)
but it's a legitimate budget battle, and that's healthy. There's a
genuine balance of power in the city.''
</P>
<P>
   But as a veteran fighter for civil liberties, Emery is always
concerned about the misuse of the tremendous power of government,
those chilling moments when government officials, behind the
protective curtain of the law, trample the rights of the innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Those moments occur more frequently than most of us realize. And
it is with that in mind that Emery is putting together a new law
firm. It will be called Emery, Celli, Brinckerhoff &AMP; Abady and its
chief mission will be to serve as a counterforce to the abusive
practices of government and other large institutions. The intent,
Emery said, is to move aggressively on cases of false arrest,
police brutality, the illegal stifling of dissent and other matters
that amount to what he calls ``citizen abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Emery has long been drawn to those kinds of cases. Soon after
graduating from Columbia Law School in 1970 he founded the
Institutional Legal Services Project in the state of Washington,
where he pushed litigation that led to an overhaul of the state's
backward mental commitment law and improvements in notoriously poor
prison conditions.
</P>
<P>
   In the late '70s, as a staff attorney for the New York Civil
Liberties Union, he successfully represented a man who was beaten
and humiliated by the police in a gay bar. In the 1980s he won the
release from prison of Bobby McLaughlin, a Brooklyn man who had
been sentenced to 15 years to life for a murder he didn't commit.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, because of a class-action suit filed by Emery, a
policy of routinely strip-searching suspects accused of minor
offenses in Manhattan and Queens was ended. More than 53,000 people
accused of infractions as minor as driving without a license had
been forced to undergo the humiliating searches.
</P>
<P>
   Emery and his partners in the new firm currently represent a
number of clients who are in legal fights with the Giuliani
administration. They include newsstand operators, many victims of
alleged police abuse, an activist group called Housing Works that
has claimed its criticism of the Mayor led to the illegal
cancellation of its contract with the city, and Public Advocate
Mark Green, who has been stymied in his effort to get data on cops
who were never disciplined despite having excessive-force
complaints substantiated by the Civilian Complaint Review Board.
</P>
<P>
   Emery said, ``We want to have a firm where the people in this
city can come and know they are going to get the best advice and
the best representation with respect to whether their rights are
being violated, whether it's by the city, state or federal
governments, or other major institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the firm is not interested in personal-injury lawsuits.
The primary goal is to curb the abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   It is, of course, ironic that the man primarily responsible for
the most recent increase in the power of the mayoralty is
establishing a law firm to represent the people being steamrolled
by that power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudy Giuliani is the first mayor since the new charter to
really use all of his powers, and even overuse his powers,'' Emery
said. ``As a lawyer and a very bright, hard-working guy, he has
pushed the envelope.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the mayor has been particularly tough on dissenters,
attacking First Amendment rights in a way that is ``unprecedented
in this city.''
</P>
<P>
   But the courts have been there to defend those rights, he said,
adding: ``It's not easy. We're constantly navigating the shoals of
the court system, trying to find the right theories, the best
theories for holding public officials accountable. Government
policy should not be undermined where it has validity and is being
implemented in a careful, thoughtful, humane way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regrettably, that happens less than all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
