<HEADER>
A8575 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COP-SUICIDE-REVIEW-NY     06-20 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COP-SUICIDE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPERADOES SEEKING A BAFFLING ENDGAME: SUICIDE BY COP 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By ALAN FEUER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It happens dozens of times each year during jittery hostage
dramas and routine traffic stops: desperate people lure police
officers into shooting them in a phenomenon known in
law-enforcement circles as suicide by cop.
</P>
<P>
   There are no hard statistics showing the frequency of such
incidents, but experts believe that up to 10 percent of the roughly
600 fatal police shootings that occur in an average year are
provoked by people actively seeking to die.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those killed are like Moshe Pergament, a 19-year-old
college student and problem gambler who was shot by police last
November when he aimed a toy handgun at officers who pulled him
over for driving erratically on New York's Long Island Expressway.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are former inmates who would rather die in a
firefight than return to jail. Others are like Juan Rodriguez, a
46-year-old cancer patient who was shot and wounded in Jersey City,
N.J., in May after pulling a gun on two police officers eating in a
pizza shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would you go and point a gun at a policeman?'' asked
Michael Johnston, a Jersey City police officer involved in another
suicide-by-cop incident this year. ``You have to figure they're
going to shoot you.''
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be the point, law-enforcement experts say. Suicide
by cop is usually not a capricious act of mania or rage but rather
a calculated attempt to force police to act as executioners, said
Clinton Van Zandt, a former chief negotiator for the FBI. ``Many
times they are not `ordinary' crimes gone bad,'' he said. ``They
are the carefully planned suicides of people who want to be killed
by the police.''
</P>
<P>
   Law-enforcement officials have been aware of suicide-by-cop
cases for years, but researchers are just beginning to make sense
of the baffling mix of despair, self-hatred, violence and rage that
seems to fuel such acts. This research has taken on added
importance recently in light of the rash of school shootings around
the nation in which troubled children have opened fire on their
classmates and teachers _ in part, some experts say, to draw a
lethal response from the police.
</P>
<P>
   The term suicide by cop was coined in 1983 by Karl Harris, a
former California police officer with a Ph.D. in psychology who
worked at a suicide hot line in Los Angeles after leaving the
force. ``As a cop, I knew of a number of cases where it appeared
that people had actually forced police officers to shoot them,''
Harris said. ``In the suicide business I saw all the different ways
people attempted suicide, and it occurred to me that maybe some
people were actually forcing cops to shoot them because they wanted
to die.''
</P>
<P>
   In nearly a third of such cases, the victims actually leave
suicide notes, apologizing to the police for having purposely drawn
their fire, Van Zandt said. Just as often, he added, grand jury
inquests discover that the victims had previously announced to
their friends or loved ones their intention to draw gunfire
intentionally. But in the most confounding cases, researchers must
rely on exhaustive psychological studies to determine suicidal
motives, leaving definitive answers unknown.
</P>
<P>
   The few notable studies, including ones conducted by researchers
at the Harvard Medical School and in British Columbia, indicate
that the typical person who commits suicide by cop is a white man
in his mid-20s with a history of alcohol and drug abuse. Much like
traditional suicide victims, such people suffer from depression and
are haunted by feelings of dependence and hopelessness. Their
actions are often set off by the deterioration of an important
personal relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``A break-up or a divorce with no belief that there can be a
reconciliation is often the significant contributing factor,'' said
Sgt. John Yarbrough, an officer in the Los Angeles County Sheriff's
homicide bureau who analyzed police shootings for a recent study on
suicide by cop. ``They are helpless to change their situation and
they often suffer the frustration of, `I can't get it back, it's
over.'''
</P>
<P>
   If the typical psychological profile of someone who commits
suicide by cop seems nearly identical to that of a regular suicide
victim, researchers are still struggling to determine why police
are chosen as the weapon of choice rather than guns, nooses or
pills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most common theory is that if you're shot by an officer,
you're the victim and the officer is the perpetrator,'' said Dr.
Deirdre Anglin, an associate professor of emergency medicine at the
University of Southern California and co-author of a study on
suicide by cop to be published this summer. ``Suicide is still
socially taboo. This way, you're not actually killing yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Anglin said there were other, simpler motives, including
cowardice, religious prohibitions against suicide, concern over
insurance policies and a physical inability to commit the act
oneself.
</P>
<P>
   For Van Zandt, however, the rationale behind suicide by cop is
as simple _ and deadly _ as a loaded gun. ``What it all comes down
to is that people know the police have weapons,'' he said. ``If you
drive your car into a bridge abutment, you may not die. But
provoking a cop _ there's probably good reason to believe that's
going to kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   The effect on police officers in cases of suicide by cop is
often neglected, experts say. ``There are feelings of
powerlessness, feelings of being manipulated,'' said Bill Geller,
author of ``Deadly Force: What We Know'' (Police Executive Research
Forum, 1991). Geller added that most officers involved in
suicide-by-cop incidents _ like most of those who kill in the line
of duty _ retire prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston, the Jersey City police officer who shot a
suicide-by-cop victim in January, said he has managed to remain on
daily patrols only because he now understands that he was provoked.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this kind of thing happens to you, you're basically the
victim,'' he said. ``The only way to go on is thinking that you did
your best _ that in end, it wasn't your decision. He forced you to
do what you did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-98 1133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
