<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOLF CHANNEL: TV FOR DUFFERS SITTING ON THEIR DUFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
(editors: text that should be italicized is marked with (BEGIN
ITALICS HERE) and (END ITALICS HERE) 
(duplication warning: also sent with `a' code) 
 (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Golf is big. Really big. Huge. How big? Golf is 24-hour
cable-TV-channel big, that's how big.
</P>
<P>
   To put the very existence of the three-year-old Golf Channel
into perspective, consider that there is no Football Channel, no
Basketball Channel, no Baseball Channel. Nor, in the department of
numbing pursuits, is there a Watching Paint Dry Channel, a Navel
Lint Channel or a Middle East Peace Process Channel.
</P>
<P>
   True, there is C-SPAN, but the point is that the Golf Channel
says something uniquely profound about our culture. Just what is
anybody's guess, but this much is clear: It has to do with loud
slacks.
</P>
<P>
   And money. The Orlando-based network says it expects to defy its
early skeptics and make a profit for the first time this year,
thanks to an upscale, mostly male audience drawn from the more than
17 million households worldwide that it says now get the Golf
Channel via their cable systems or satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Here, on the occasion of the U.S. Open, the first day of summer
AND Father's Day, are gleanings from a single day's programming.
</P>
<P>
   _ By TOM KUNTZ
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Sunday, May 19, 7:08 a.m. An infomercial
extols a golf club with ``a whole new way of addressing the ball.''
That phrase conjures up Ralph Kramden tutoring Ed Norton in golf on
``The Honeymooners,'' with Norton saying, ``Helloooo, ball!'' This
pitch, however, is for the Wonderputter, the ``Wonder from Down
Under,'' a device whereby you putt not sideways to the hole but
facing it, stroking with an underhand, pushing motion. The ad
features Australians who sound like Crocodile Dundee:(END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Steve Word, host: So tell me, guys, how did you develop the
Wonderputter, the putter from Down Under?
</P>
<P>
   Terry Adcock, Australian pro: Well, it happened quite
innocently, actually, Steve. Paul comes to me for regular lessons,
and the last lesson was on putting. And I showed him the regular
putting method and he said, ``Do people actually putt this way?''
And I said, ``Yeah, sure.'' He said, ``Well, it feels very
uncomfortable.'' And I said: ``Well, if you can come up with
another way, you do that. And if you do, give me a call.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Cleeve, inventor: And I did. I came up with the
Wonderputter!
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)7:38 a.m. An update from ``Golf Central,''
which tries not to miss many golf news tidbits. It seems a caddy
was mugged:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Kris Tschetter played Saturday (at the McDonald's-LPGA
tournament in Delaware) without her normal caddy . . . who's in a
Wilmington hospital recovering from a Friday night attack in
downtown Wilmington. He was stopped for directions, but several
youths beat him up. He suffered several cracked teeth, a broken arm
and a separated shoulder. He was also robbed of $160. . . . Up next
on Central, more than a couple of good shots for Fred (Couples) at
the Nelson. Oh, was he hot!
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)7:39 a.m. A toothpaste commercial just for
golfers:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Like this golf ball, your teeth are filled with microscopic
crevices. Arm &AMP; Hammer gets in these crevices to clean plaque away
better.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)11:30 a.m. Coverage of the Benson &AMP; Hedges
International Open in Thames, England, provided by the BBC. The
British commentators make clear that while golf is not a physical
contact sport, you sometimes have to play with pain:(END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Commentator No. 1: Lee Westwood had an eye infection and thought
of pulling out in the third round, but decided to play, and (scores
of) 77, 76 are not really indicative of Lee Westwood's golfing
game.
</P>
<P>
   Commentator No. 2: I think he got a fly in his eye and,
endeavoring to get it out with a towel, (he) had a dirty towel and
got some mud or something in his eye, just slightly scratched the
retina a little bit or something like that. Anyway it was all
inflamed. It looked rather nasty.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)11:38 a.m. Speaking in hushed tones, the BBC
commentators discern subtle signs of golf athleticism as Retief
Goosen, a South African, approaches a putt:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Commentator No. 1: He seems to be taking it a lot easier on the
golf course today. You know, he's inclined sometimes to walk quite
quickly and get quite excited, but that was a very leisurely walk
across the green, now, wasn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Commentator No. 2: (In sage agreement) Gaining in confidence,
inner confidence. . . .
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)12:40 p.m. Just what golf needs: more
unusual hatwear. Another commercial featuring Australians pitches
Crocodile Dundee-type hats:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Now available from the Outback, an innovative all-weather sports
cap. Made from unique, sun-protective fabric, Outback Shade sports
caps provide an alternative to conventional headwear. . . . Even a
loaded golf bag won't damage these cappies!
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)1 p.m. ``Golf Channel Classics,'' featuring
1964 World Match play in England. Tony Lema, the 1964 British Open
champ, explains to an interviewer that his strategy on the course
will be to play golf:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Interviewer: What would you say would be the premium here in
your game?
</P>
<P>
   Lema: Well, always to win you have to be putting pretty good.
But I would say that the premium here at Wentworth would be on
positioning the ball off the tee and onto the green. Very careful
driving and very careful positioning of the ball at all times.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)5 p.m. On ``Golf Talk Live,'' Peter Kessler,
the host, poses a real toughie to Arnold Palmer, a Golf Channel
co-founder and his boss. Kessler is curious to know whether the
golf legend and multimillionaire ever regrets leaving his job as a
paint salesman:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Kessler: Do you regret that you left the world of paint poorer
for your decision to go pro (in 1954)?
</P>
<P>
   Palmer: Oh, no. (Chuckling.) I could never say that I regret it.
I certainly took a long look at it. . . . It was a turning point,
Peter, and it was a good decision as far as I'm concerned.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) 6:45 p.m. Inclusion and diversity a la
Tiger Woods is a big theme as the Golf Channel goes on location for
the grand opening of the sprawling new World Golf Village and the
World Golf Hall of Fame in St. Augustine, Fla. A rock video
features kids with golf irons playing air guitar:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)'Cause I love to swing today
</P>
<P>
   I love to play
</P>
<P>
   WE LOVE IT!
</P>
<P>
   I love to play . . .
</P>
<P>
   WE LOVE IT! WE LOVE IT!
</P>
<P>
   WE REALLY LOVE IT!(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)7:25 p.m. Rich Lerner, a Golf Channel
reporter, asks the evening's headline act, Smokey Robinson, whether
his hit ``You've Really Got a Hold on Me'' could be golf's theme
song: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Robinson: The first verse is perfect for that because: (BEGIN
ITALICS HERE)I don't like you, but I love you /Seems like I'm
always thinking of you /Though you treat me badly, I love you madly
/ You've really got a hold on me.(END ITALICS HERE) That's
dedicated to golf.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner: That works perfectly. You gonna throw out all the great
classics tonight?
</P>
<P>
   Robinson: Oh, yeah, man, we play everything.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner: (Breaking into song) We're goin' to a go-go. . . .
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)But Smokey cuts in, as if to remind Lerner
that World Golf Village is a long way from Motown:(END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Robinson: Rich, Rich, Rich, you were doing so great on the
interview, man.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner: No singing?
</P>
<P>
   Robinson: Sorry.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner: It sounded so good in the shower this morning. . . .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
