<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AM-NYT-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
 (jt)  
 FOR Sunday Papers: 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, June 21:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Coded `i')
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-SAUDI-BOMB (Washington) _ Update on the government's
investigation of a 1996 terrorist bombing that killed 19 American
airmen in Saudi Arabia. By Philip Shenon and David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-NUCLEAR (Jerusalem) _ The nuclear tests by India and
Pakistan have left Israel alone in the world as a country that is
widely believed to have nuclear weapons but that has not
acknowledged it does. For now, Israel is apparently happy to leave
it that way. By Serge Schmemann.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-AUSTRIA (Vienna) _ Speaking to a group of Austrian
officials and dignitaries that included former President Kurt
Waldheim, Pope John Paul II said Saturday that European Christians
had a moral obligation to fully reconcile with the Jews. By
Alessandra Stannley.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-NAZI-GOLD (Washington) _ The ongoing controversy over
Switzerland's role in aiding Nazi Germany have now prompted the
State Department to broaden the debate by raising questions about
the role that other neutral countries played in aiding the Third
Reich.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Beijing) _ The prospects for China's entry into the
World Trade Organization any time soon are nil, the top American
trade negotiator said here Saturday evening after two days of talks
with Chinese officials, casting ice water on any lingering hopes
that a trade breakthrough might be announced during President
Clinton's state visit next week. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-OPERA (Shanghai) _ Rebuffing international pressure to
compromise, local authorities instead chose Saturday to escalate
their dispute with the director of a classic Chinese opera that is
scheduled to open in New York City as the centerpiece of next
month's Lincoln Center Festival. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ The Japanese government pledged before a
meeting of the Group of Seven industrialized nations that it would
revive its economy and repair its banking system, but it fell short
of saying anything new or specific. By Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-MARK (Frankfurt) _ The 50th anniversary of the German
mark. By Edmund Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-ELECTION (Bogota) _ Curtain-raiser for presidential
election runoff on Sunday. By Diana-Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Coded 'a')
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL-AID-EDUC (Undated) _ The financial aid season just
ended was the most competitive in memory. Several trends converged,
creating what some experts lament as a near free-for-all in a field
that was until recently relatively well-ordered. By Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   VOICE-TECH (Undated) _ Later this year, many callers wanting
flight information from United Airlines will speak not to a person
but to a computer that acts like one. It will ask when and where
the caller wants to travel, look up flight schedules and converse
using synthesized speech. United's system is only one example of a
wave of new computer technologies that understand spoken language
and are poised to sweep through the American economy. By John
Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER-JOBS (Gaffney, S.C.) _ For the youth of South Carolina,
the benefits of America's lowest unemployment rate in three decades
are unmistakable in South Carolina. Heavy doses of foreign
investment have helped drive the statewide jobless rate down to 2.5
percent this spring from 4.4 percent a year earlier. But the
experience of South Carolina's young job seekers is not replicated
everywhere. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   BROTHERS-BENNETT (Washington) _ The Bennett who defends the
president has a close and complicated relationship with the Bennett
who thinks the president should be ashamed. Each says he respects
his brother's right to make a living. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTION-THEME-EDUC (Albuquerque, N.M.) _ Around the nation,
candidates for state and local office this year are talking far
more about education than any other theme. Nowhere is that better
demonstrated than here in New Mexico's First District, where a race
to fill the seat of Rep. Steve Schiff, a Republican who died in
March, at times more resembles a contest for a seat on the local
school board than for Congress. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   NY-BILINGUAL-EDUC (New York) _ New York City Schools Chancellor
Rudy Crew is preparing to step into a political vortex in the fall
with a plan to overhaul bilingual education in New York City.
Senior school administrators say the effort will improve schooling
for immigrant children in their native languages, not abolish it.
By Randal C. Archibold.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCT-FLAWS (Washington) _ A bill to set nationwide standards
for damages from flawed products from toasters to heart valves has
eluded a coalition of Republicans and manufacturers for years. But
a new agreement with the White House may mean its time has come,
perhaps this summer. By Neil Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH-POLICE (Pittsburgh) _ Pittsburgh's police force has
the highest percentage of women of any big-city force in the
nation, the result of years of litigation. But there are signs the
force's leadership is going back to old ways. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   MAYORS-CONFERENCE (Reno, Nev) _ Under mounting pressure from the
Clinton administration and mayors around the country, federal
lawmakers have reversed their decision to have the Housing
Department's chief investigator examine housing programs in three
cities led by black mayors. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CENTENNIAL (New York) _ Celebrating the centennial of the
union of the five boroughs. By David Gonzales.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout
of the first edition of The New York Times _ has moved.
</P>
