<TEXT>
<P>
   Threats and Defiance In a Balkan Stalemate
</P>
<P>
   NATO began the week with a show of force to warn Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic, to stop using his military against
the ethnic Albanian majority in Serbia's restive province of
Kosovo. More than 80 NATO jets ranged through the skies bordering
Serbia to drive home the point that the West was serious about
heading off Kosovo's ethnic bloodshed, which could spread through
the region.
</P>
<P>
   But the effect the message was having was not very clear. For
one thing, America's allies in NATO want United Nations
authorization for any use of force, and Russia threatens to veto
such a step.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic met in Moscow on Tuesday with Russian President Boris
Yeltsin and promised concessions over Kosovo. He did not, however,
agree to a key Western demand: withdrawing Serbian security forces
from the province. And he was defiant, declaring, ``In the latest
actions, it was declared by the security forces there were no
civilian victims at all.''
</P>
<P>
   An Atom's-Eye View of AIDS
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have obtained an atom-level picture, reconstructed by
computer from X-ray data, of the first contact made between an AIDS
virus and the human cell it infects. The picture portrays the
daunting strength of the virus' several defenses against the immune
system. It also defines points of vulnerability against which new
drugs and vaccines might be designed.
</P>
<P>
   The images were a result of an eight-year joint effort by
research teams at Columbia University and the Dana-Farber Cancer
Institute in Boston. They focus on the probe protein that studs the
virus' surface like the spikelets of a mine. The probe protein is
also the basis of an AIDS vaccine about to be tested in the United
States and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   _ By NICHOLAS WADE
</P>
<P>
   Cashing Out
</P>
<P>
   Gus Levy, a late chairman of Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co., once described
the firm's secret of success as ``long-term greedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street's top private investment bank subordinated the
individual deal maker to a team-oriented partnership. Delayed
riches came to those who pledged lifetime allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Goldman's 190 partners have decided that their philosophy
has proven so successful, and that the competitive landscape has
changed so much in the late 1990's, that the time has come to cash
out.
</P>
<P>
   They will dissolve their partnership in favor of selling shares
to the public, and reaping the very considerable value, as much as
$30 billion, that the firm expects the public to place on the
Goldman franchise. The question is whether Levy's magic formula
will lose the long-term ingredient.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOSEPH KAHN
</P>
<P>
   A Signal to Tehran?
</P>
<P>
   Six months after Iranian President Mohammad Khatami extended a
small olive branch to the United States, the Clinton administration
responded with the offer of a ``road map'' to normalized relations
between the two countries. The offer came in a speech by Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright almost two decades after Iran's Islamic
revolution took U.S. diplomats hostage and made a breakup with
Washington inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly why the administration decided to make the gesture now
was not disclosed. But the United States, stunned by nuclear bomb
tests in India and then Pakistan, and losing its foothold on Iraqi
sanctions, may have noticed that it has no leverage in Iran,
another potential nuclear nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranians were neither overjoyed nor grateful. Their
officials responded with the opinion that they would like to see
some deeds to go with the words. In her speech, Albright said
nothing new about U.S. efforts to isolate Iran economically.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARBARA CROSSETTE &QR;
</P>
<P>
   An Au Pair Goes Home
</P>
<P>
   The highest court in Massachusetts freed the au pair Louise
Woodward to return to her native England, and she was off like a
shot the next day, lingering not an extra minute in the country
where her name had become synonymous with the deepest fears of
working parents.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Woodward, 20, was convicted last fall of murdering Matthew
Eappen, the 8-month-old baby boy in her care, but Judge Hiller
Zobel then converted the verdict to a manslaughter conviction and
sentenced her to time already served _ 279 days. Tuesday, the
Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court upheld that decision, while
emphasizing that Ms. Woodward had not been acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CAREY GOLDBERG
</P>
<P>
   A Downsizer Is Downsized
</P>
<P>
   When Albert Dunlap was ousted as Sunbeam Corp.'s chief
executive, the decision drew cheers in the streets from factory
workers at a plant in Cleveland that the company had planned to
close, an executive recruiter said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many of Dunlap's former employees and associates
unapologetically celebrated the embarrassingly public way in which
he was thrown into the ranks of the unemployed, when the Sunbeam
board said he hadn't lived up to his reputation as a turnaround
artist. He had also become known as Chain Saw Al for the way he
downsized thousands of workers while earning tens of millions of
dollars for himself.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DANA CANEDY
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bill Who? Diana Who?
</P>
<P>
   Sports Illustrated on Thursday proclaimed him the ``most
familiar face on the planet earth,'' ahead of Bill Clinton and the
late Princess of Wales. Fortune detailed his impact on the global
economy two weeks ago. Taking all revenue surrounding his image
into account, the magazine came up with $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and Michael Jordan still plays basketball fairly well.
</P>
<P>
   Incomparable icon or merely incredible athlete, Jordan led the
Chicago Bulls to their third straight championship and sixth in the
last eight seasons on Sunday with an astounding finish in the
season's final game.
</P>
<P>
   In 37.1 seconds befitting his legend, the league's greatest
player scored a breathtaking layup, stole the ball from Karl Malone
on the defensive end and finished the Utah Jazz with a pretty jump
shot from 17 feet away with 5.2 seconds remaining. ``I can't see
him topping this, but then again, it is Michael Jordan,'' his
coach, Phil Jackson, said.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MIKE WISE
</P>
<P>
   A New Face at the U.N.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Holbrooke, architect of the Dayton accords on Bosnia,
has been nominated as the U.S. representative to the United
Nations, replacing Bill Richardson, who will be secretary of
energy.
</P>
<P>
   Given Holbrooke's reputation for independence and media
management, his appointment was big news for those who like to
speculate on the intricacies of power-sharing in the specialized
world of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   There were immediate suggestions that Holbrooke might pull the
spotlight off Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and disrupt a
relatively harmonious foreign-policy team. But the two have vowed
to make their new relationship work, and one official took a
pragmatic view of the appointment's meaning: ``With so many balls
in the air, we needed another pair of competent hands.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEVEN ERLANGER
</P>
<P>
   Judgment in Hollywood
</P>
<P>
   The assignment was daunting: pick the 100 best American movies.
Ever.
</P>
<P>
   With such a wealth of cinematic riches over the century, where
could the American Film Institute turn?
</P>
<P>
   Such a task couldn't possibly be entrusted just to stuffy film
historians and critics.
</P>
<P>
   No, the institute also sought out common folk like, say, Bill
Clinton and Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Top honors, of course, went to ``Citizen Kane.'' Even those
who've never seen the Orson Welles classic are used to it being
called the best, so they might well have voted for it anyway. And,
continuing to round up the usual suspects, No. 2 was perhaps the
most-quoted movie ever, ``Casablanca.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Yankee Doodle Dandy'' an ignominious 100th? And not a
single film from Ernst Lubitsch or Preston Sturges?
</P>
<P>
   A moment of silence, please, or perhaps darkness, for the giants
left on the century's cutting-room floor.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Poesy at the Bout &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The outlook wasn't prose-y for the literary crowd &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who jammed the hall to hear _ of all things! _ poems read aloud &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By poets using metaphor to knock each other out &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Taos, New Mexico's, world championship poetry bout.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The champ, a native son, Jimmy Santiago Baca, &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Declaimed his work in cadences designed to stir and rock a &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Crowd that oohed and aahed at onomatopoeic iambs &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And booed with murderous intent at less-than-perfect rhy-ambs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His foe, Sherman Alexie, pursued the winner's purse &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With lyric tales of Indian life in arch, impassioned verse. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Denying 'twas a contest _ ``It's poetry we love'' _
</P>
<P>
   The poets punched and counterpunched with fist in wordsmith's
glove. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ten rounds of reading left the two men bloodied but unbowed &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And things stood even as they spoke their last before the crowd &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The tension rose unbearably _ well, 'twas bearable, perhaps, &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though supporters of each fighter looked as though they might
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The whole idea, of course, was to enlarge the poet's house. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Poetry wins, not poets, was the stated theme in Taos. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And it was true for most on hand, but not in Baca's camp &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For though J.S.B.'s verse lives on, Alexie is the champ.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BRUCE WEBER
</P>
