<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMES-EXPRESS-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (jt)
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top Times Express stories planned for Sunday, June
21. The NYT News Service Supervisor is Jack Topchik, 212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-EXCLUSIVE-SAUDI-BOMB (Washington) _ Update on the
government's investigation of a 1996 terrorist bombing that killed
19 American airmen in Saudi Arabia. By Philip Shenon and David
Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-POPE-AUSTRIA (Vienna) _ Speaking to a group of Austrian
officials and dignitaries that included former President Kurt
Waldheim, Pope John Paul II said Saturday that European Christians
had a moral obligation to fully reconcile with the Jews. By
Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-CHINA-TRADE (Beijing) _ The prospects for China's entry into
the World Trade Organization any time soon are nil, the top
American trade negotiator said here Saturday evening after two days
of talks with Chinese officials, casting ice water on any lingering
hopes that a trade breakthrough might be announced during President
Clinton's state visit next week. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ The Japanese government pledged before
a meeting of the Group of Seven industrialized nations that it
would revive its economy and repair its banking system, but it fell
short of saying anything new or specific. By Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-GERMANY-MARK (Frankfurt) _ The 50th anniversary of the
German mark. By Edmund Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-FINANCIAL-AID-EDUC (Undated) _ The financial aid season just
ended was the most competitive in memory. Several trends converged,
creating what some experts lament as a near free-for-all in a field
that was until recently relatively well-ordered. By Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-VOICE-TECH (Undated) _ Later this year, many callers wanting
flight information from United Airlines will speak not to a person
but to a computer that acts like one. It will ask when and where
the caller wants to travel, look up flight schedules and converse
using synthesized speech. United's system is only one example of a
wave of new computer technologies that understand spoken language
and are poised to sweep through the American economy. By John
Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-SUMMER-JOBS (Gaffney, S.C.) _ For the youth of South
Carolina, the benefits of America's lowest unemployment rate in
three decades are unmistakable in South Carolina. Heavy doses of
foreign investment have helped drive the statewide jobless rate
down to 2.5 percent this spring from 4.4 percent a year earlier.
But the experience of South Carolina's young job seekers is not
replicated everywhere. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-ELECTION-THEME-EDUC (Albuquerque, N.M.) _ Around the nation,
candidates for state and local office this year are talking far
more about education than any other theme. Nowhere is that better
demonstrated than here in New Mexico's First District, where a race
to fill the seat of Rep. Steve Schiff, a Republican who died in
March, at times more resembles a contest for a seat on the local
school board than for Congress. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-MAYORS-CONFERENCE (Reno, Nev) _ Under mounting pressure from
the Clinton administration and mayors around the country, federal
lawmakers have reversed their decision to have the Housing
Department's chief investigator examine housing programs in three
cities led by black mayors. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-CHINA-ENTOURAGE-REVIEW (Washington) _ The presidential
entourage and its paraphernalia fill four passenger planes and
several large C-141 military transports. The White House is taking
60 tons of communications gear and as many as 10 armored
limousines. By John N. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-AFRICA-PHONES-REVIEW (Johannesburg) _ After relatively rich
South Africa, which African country has the highest percentage of
cellular phones among telephone users? Ghana? The Ivory Coast?
Kenya? Nigeria? None of the above. The correct answer is the
desperately poor, badly shot-up Democratic Republic of the Congo,
where the regular telephone system _ where it exists at all _ is so
decrepit that cellular is often the only option. By Donald G.
McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-COP-SUICIDE-REVIEW (Undated) _ It happens dozens of times
each year during jittery hostage dramas and routine traffic stops:
desperate people lure police officers into shooting them in a
phenomenon known in law-enforcement circles as suicide by cop.
There are no hard statistics showing the frequency of such
incidents, but experts believe that up to 10 percent of the roughly
600 fatal police shootings that occur in an average year are
provoked by people actively seeking to die. By Alan Feuer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
