<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-JOBS-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR TEENS, JOB HUNTING THIS SUMMER IS EASY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927. A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAFFNEY, S.C. _ Unaware of just how much muscle she had, Sharai
Correll took a job as a waitress recently at the local Cracker
Barrel restaurant, the kind of steady, air-conditioned summer work
that generations of teen-agers with limited options would have far
preferred to, say, scrounging for lawns to cut.
</P>
<P>
   But one day of orientation was enough for Ms. Correll, an
18-year old premed student. She quit abruptly and took a job as a
sales clerk at Fila, a shoe and sportswear retailer that is one of
the employers at the 68-store Carolina Factory Shops complex in
this town of 25,875 competing almost desperately for summer help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working here is a lot easier than working at Cracker Barrel,''
said Ms. Correll, who also briefly entertained offers from the
Dress Barn and the Gap and was ambitious enough to take a second
job working mostly weekends at the Upstate Carolina Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five jobs in two days!'' she exclaimed, still amazed at the
leverage she and friends command this year in the market for summer
work, where many students have long had to settle for unappealing
or low-paying jobs _ if they got on any payroll at all. For anyone
with even an ounce of gumption, Ms. Correll said, ``I can't believe
you can't find a job.''
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of America's lowest unemployment rate in three
decades are unmistakable in South Carolina. Heavy doses of foreign
investment have helped drive the statewide jobless rate down to 2.5
percent this spring from 4.4 percent a year earlier, according to
figures from the U.S. Department of Labor.
</P>
<P>
   The experience of South Carolina's young job seekers is not
replicated everywhere. In New York City, for example, finding a
summer job remains a challenge. Yet, even in the city, economists
say a decline in unemployment should open up more jobs for young
people.
</P>
<P>
   And in many places around the country, tight job markets mean
youth unemployment is at its lowest point in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Here, summer work is likely to come at pay well above the $5.15
minimum wage. Young workers typically enjoy hefty discounts on
purchases, often can demand enough flexibility to allow the
occasional long weekend at the beach and may even collect a bonus
of $200 or more for lasting the whole summer.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a recent swing through the northwestern and central
parts of the state found a litany of employer grief about the
inability to attract needed workers, in many cases with adverse
effects on business.
</P>
<P>
   For example, even though vacation season for regular workers is
not yet in full stride, it already takes longer for customers in
Columbia, the state capital, to get through the checkout line at
some supermarkets. The jobless rate has dived to an unheard of 1.4
percent, and even lifeguard jobs, among the most coveted, go
begging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could use about four kids right now,'' said John Ferguson,
the manager of a Piggly Wiggly grocery store in an affluent section
of Columbia. ``My level of service is not what I want it to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Another, more far-reaching result of surging demand for summer
workers is that young blacks here are increasingly being drawn into
the labor market.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the unemployment rate for 16- to 19-year-old blacks
remains sky high, at 29.4 percent in May, compared with 14.2
percent for young people of all races. Still, joblessness among
black teen-agers is down _ from 33.9 percent a year ago. And the
shift is a significant development in South Carolina, where the
population is 30.1 percent black, about two and a half times the
national figure.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jamie Devine, 18, who is black, is working this summer as a loan
administrator at Carolina First, a regional bank, doing tasks such
as calculating loan payoffs for people taking out new mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want a job, you can get a job,'' said Devine, who is
putting in a full week for more than $8 an hour after working part
time at the bank during the year while attending Benedict College
in Columbia. ``It teaches you discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Boineau, a vice president who oversees Carolina First's
paid internship program, told of one black teen-ager from the
College of Charleston who was hired as a teller this summer but
quit to take an even better job two days after starting work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so disappointed,'' Ms. Boineau said. ``It gets harder
and harder to get good people.''
</P>
<P>
   Even rural areas of South Carolina, which once offered little
but arduous farm work, provide a choice of appealing jobs this
summer. In Joanna, a speck of a place midway between Greenville and
Columbia, Brooke Bradley, 16, happily tends a video store _ much of
the time watching movies _ for $5.25 an hour after changing her
mind about a job offer from Pizza Hut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just called them back and canceled it,'' she said. ``This is
more steady.''
</P>
<P>
   Some employers have been unable to find extra summer hands at
all, among them the Phoenix, an elegant Greenville inn. ``If six
qualified college kids walked in right now, they'd have a job,''
said Walter Gallman, the banquet manager, citing his need for
waiters, bellmen and front desk people who, he said, could average
$300 a week for 25 or 30 hours of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible. I've never seen a summer like this _ there's
help wanted everywhere,'' said Douglas Woodward, research director
at the University of South Carolina's Darla Moore School of
Business. ``Any 16-year-old who wants a job can find one in this
state right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Acute demand for young workers has not pushed wages up
drastically this summer; employers are still trying to compete on
working conditions and perquisites. But at a job fair in Greenville
sponsored by the Urban League of the Upstate, recruiters for United
Parcel Service said that the $8.50 to $9.50 an hour they could
offer under the company's national pay scales had become relatively
less attractive as competitors' pay creeped higher.
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, ``we were leaps and bounds above'' the
competition, said Jim Mahaffey, one of the recruiters. ``There's
not a whole lot we can do except go out and beat the bushes.''
</P>
<P>
   Even students who want jobs but do not want to give up their
summer at the beach are bargaining from a strong position.
</P>
<P>
   The Myrtle Beach Pavilion, a huge resort complex of rides and
attractions, which employs as many as 1,600 people at the season's
peak, still needs to find 300 more workers, said Scott Radwick, who
is in charge of hiring for the resort's owner, Burroughs &AMP; Chapin.
</P>
<P>
   With housing scarce, increases in hourly pay of 10 or 15 cents
this season may not do the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every employer around here is resigned to the fact that it's
going to be a tough hiring season,'' Radwick said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
