<DOCNO> NYT19980620.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 12:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8596 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BENNETT-BROTHERS-ART-     06-20 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BENNETT-BROTHERS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ISSUE TESTS BENNETT BROTHERS' TIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ William Bennett, the conservative author, was in no
hurry to tell his brother, Robert Bennett, President Clinton's
personal lawyer, about his new book project. The working title is
``The Death of Outrage: Bill Clinton and the Assault on American
Ideals,'' which the Free Press is rushing into print this fall.
</P>
<P>
   So how did the Bennett who works for that same Bill Clinton
react when he heard about this latest endeavor? The Bennett who
thinks the president should be ashamed said, ``I haven't told
him.''
</P>
<P>
   No? ``He's been away,'' Bill Bennett said recently. Then he
stopped, exhaled, tried again. ``Oh, and he's going to want to take
me aside and be my big brother and say, `Be smart, be decent, be
responsible,' and I'll tell him, `I'll be all those things.' It'll
probably be a big headache for him. Or for his client, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Bennetts finally had that conversation a couple of days
later, it went pretty much as expected. ``He has his own life and
has to do what he thinks is right for him,'' Bob Bennett said,
sounding only slightly pained. ``I did say I hoped he would be fair
to the president. I urged him to do that.'' Will the book undermine
their brotherly bond? ``If he's unfair it might,'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   Each brother says he respects the other's right to make a
living. For Bill Bennett, a former education secretary in the
Reagan administration, drug czar in the Bush administration and
author of the best-seller ``The Book of Virtues'' (Simon &AMP;
Schuster, 1993), now ensconced at the conservative advocacy group
Empower America, this means excoriating Clinton on a regular basis.
For Bob Bennett, it means defending him.
</P>
<P>
   The close but awfully complicated relationship between these two
prominent men, brothers who sometimes seem to agree on little more
than the appeal of a good steak, is a matter of intense interest in
Washington, where hard-core conservatives and members of Clinton's
inner circle mostly meet on television.
</P>
<P>
   After Paula Jones' sexual harassment suit against the president
was dismissed this spring, pending an appeal, both brothers said
they were looking forward to a period of more relaxed fraternizing.
But just when their regular lunches at the Palm were threatening to
turn into a volley of old stories about their ``Grandma Szalay,''
the younger Bennett has reinvigorated the discussion.
</P>
<P>
   The book has ``nothing to do with him,'' the author says of the
lawyer, in a clear case of what Clinton might call
compartmentalizing.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of dinner table produced these two outsized, and
outwardly very different, men? ``I don't think they had one,'' in
any ordinary, please-pass-the-peas and how-was-your-day sense, said
Ellen Bennett, Bob's wife. Their mother married several times, Mrs.
Bennett said, and ``it was a pretty dysfunctional family.''
</P>
<P>
   Though on opposite sides of a wide cultural and political
divide, they are ``not dissimilar in any important ways,'' she
said. Essentially, they are two tough guys with a sentimental
streak, a memory for slights and great loyalty to one another. They
stay close, they say, by making only the most glancing references
to the president and avoiding certain topics altogether.
</P>
<P>
   They do dare to criticize one another on occasion. ``I know what
he's thinking,'' said Bill Bennett, 54. ``I'll be sitting there
watching TV and saying, `Don't say it. Don't say it.'''
</P>
<P>
   As his brother, Bob, 58, puts it, ``When you've had that
success, people don't say, `Cool it. You're getting too big for
your britches,' and I'll do that for him. I say, `You're not the
nation's priest, for God's sake.'''
</P>
<P>
   Both Bennetts are passionate about their very different work.
And both are clearly still sweet on their wives. Bill has two sons,
who are 9 and 14, Bob has three grown daughters. Each is close to
his family in ways that dramatically exceed the probabilities for
boys raised by a mother and grandmother who at best count were
married a total of nine times.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bennett brags unself-consciously about his wife, Elayne
Bennett, who runs Best Friends, a program that encourages sexual
abstinence among inner-city girls. And Mrs. Bennett likes telling
about their courtship, laughing about the time he was angry and she
made up with an offering of food _ another passion the brothers
share.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rang the bell with a pot roast,'' she said. ``He came to the
door, still with the storm clouds over his head. Then I just lifted
the lid _ and ahh, it was OK''
</P>
<P>
   Ellen, Bob Bennett's wife of 27 years, a photographer and former
teacher whom he calls ``the finest person I've ever met,'' makes
some pretty extravagant claims: ``He has never not made time for
his family. The children have always felt more important than the
client. He's never worked weekends.'' And she said he possesses
that rare quality so appealing in a husband: ``Everything,'' she
said, ``is negotiable.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in his law office, Bob Bennett is at once
charming and efficient, and suggests that the differences between
the two brothers are mostly occupational. ``I'm an advocate,'' he
said. ``I represent people who are in trouble, and Bill is an
advocate for a position.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, Bob Bennett said, he became an advocate because of
his younger brother. After their parents divorced, when Bill was 3
and Bob was 7, a subsequent stepfather who drank and had a temper
forced the older brother into the role of protector. While Bill,
who was shy, withdrew into books, Bob learned to box.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a defender always, defending him, defending my
mother,'' Bob Bennett said. ``I'd come home from school and Bill
would give me a list of who picked on him. I was supposed to say,
`Hey, did you do this to my brother?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Bam,'' he said, and demonstrated a right hook. ``It sounds so
stupid now. I'm glad to have turned out as I did and not as a Mafia
hit man.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of old friends from the Flatbush neighborhood of
Brooklyn, where the Bennetts grew up, attending both public and
Roman Catholic schools, say the image of Bob as a brawler is one he
has greatly exaggerated over the years. Despite an unsettled life
at home, both boys excelled under the stern influence of the nuns,
their mother, Nancy Walsh Bennett, and their Hungarian grandmother,
Irene Szalay, a force of nature who offered such words to live by
as, ``A gentleman is a gentleman, even in hell,'' and ``There's
always time to do the right thing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bob was the top debater at Brooklyn Prep, and Bill was known as
something of an intellectual even then, tackling ``The Iliad'' and
``The Odyssey'' as a sixth-grader. Even then, too, friends remember
Bill as a child who was deeply interested in moral issues and such
theological debates as how unfair it would be if pets were not
allowed into heaven, official Catholic teaching notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Then and now, Bob Bennett seemed less interested in these
matters. And politically, he has never been comfortable declaring
himself, though he has represented Democrats and Republicans,
including former Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger.
</P>
<P>
   He does suggest that he does not necessarily share the politics
of his best-known client. ``If Clinton were George Bush, I'd be
doing the same thing I am now,'' he said, smiling. ``Obviously, the
issues would be different.''
</P>
<P>
   These days Bob Bennett is working on fending off Ms. Jones'
appeal of her case and fighting efforts by the independent counsel
to get top Clinton aides to testify about the president's
relationship with Monica Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett mentioned that he once represented a bookie, and saw a
certain morality even in him. ``That bookie would not give up the
book. He'd have gone to the gas chamber instead. We all choose how
we're going to be moral.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Bob Bennett says, the chief difference between the
brothers is more philosophical than ideological. ``I see the world
as a very complicated place,'' he said, and rubbed his eyes. ``I
wish the world was more like what my brother wants it to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, ``We're breaks for each other,'' Bob Bennett said,
getting a little maudlin. ``As long as the other is alive, we don't
have to worry that our family would ever want for anything if
anything ever happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite enormous material success, he clearly sees their blood
bond as a hedge against hard times. ``We're there for each other on
the important things.''
</P>
<P>
   In his own downtown office, Bill Bennett is initially more
cautious than his brother, and still shows signs of the shy child
he was, mostly avoiding eye contact.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, he said, he has had more reason to worry about his big
brother than vice versa. ``The Clintons bother me and what happens
to people around them worries me,'' Bill Bennett said. ``It's risky
business.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bennetts' politics seem to have shifted since Bob talked
Bill out of joining the anti-war Students for a Democratic Society
in college. But the cultural differences between the two are
reflected in their families. Ellen, Bob's wife, who was dressed
casually for an interview in her kitchen, said their daughters were
``pretty liberal'' and still trying to convert Uncle Bill.
</P>
<P>
   Elayne, Bill's wife, who has a warm, Southern sensibility and a
more formal bearing, served pear tart and tea and said: ''Our boys
wear a tie to school every day, Catholic school. We're afraid of
popular culture. We restrict television and monitor rock music. I
never saw `Seinfeld,' and I don't want my kids to watch `The
Simpsons.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bennett sees himself as a ``public advocate, a public
philosopher on some of the things out there that I believe matter
in the long run,'' he said, adding, ``I do not see myself as Mr.
Virtue.''
</P>
<P>
   He refers to his role in relation to his brother's: ``As a
parallel to Bob, who likes to defend people in trouble, I like to
defend principles that are in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   He has spent many months saying Clinton should resign if he had
an affair with Ms. Lewinsky. But only a few weeks ago, he said, he
decided to write a book about how the whole mess had lowered
America's moral standards, after reading a newspaper article about
a group of Republicans in Naperville, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were apparently sitting around saying, `What does this
matter to me?' I said, `This is ridiculous!' These are Republicans,
who should know better, taking on this pseudo-intellectual,
European, learned nonsense and it made me mad. There should be
outrage!''
</P>
<P>
   He says he is writing the book to counter the cynicism and moral
slippage that are sure to take root if the defense of Clinton's
reported bad behavior goes unanswered. Both brothers said their
relationship would survive this, too. But there are strains over
the Clintons and other matters. Bill once took offense, for
example, when Bob called him ``Mr. Virtue'' on television.
</P>
<P>
   And close as they are, there have always been topics considered
off-limits. One night years ago, when Bill Bennett was 32 and still
unmarried, the telephone rang, and it was his brother. He remembers
the conversation like this: ``He said, `Is there anything you want
to ask me about sex?' He was worried that he had not done his duty
as an older brother. It was very sweet, very guilty, very Bob. I
told him, `Thanks, I'm fine.'''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Bill Bennett asks an interviewer about his brother, looking
for an answer to what some people consider the ultimate personal
question: ``Does Bob believe in God?'' Well, he is not practicing,
Bill is told, but beyond that, he did not say. Suddenly, Bill
Bennett is beaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe,'' he said, `I'll call and ask him if he has any
questions about God.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
