<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980620.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 13:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8603 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCIAL-AID-EDUC-AR     06-20 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCIAL-AID-EDUC-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: financial aid.''. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And in an explicit offer of negotiation, Harvard added, ``We
expect that some of our admitted students will have particularly
attractive offers from the institutions with new aid programs, and
those students should not assume that we will not respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Keck said it was Harvard's letter that prompted her appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's financial aid office was open 12 hours a day six days
a week in April for families to discuss their packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spoke to an unprecedented number of parents this year,''
said William Fitzsimmons, Harvard's dean of admissions.
``Competition had been getting tougher, and this year's
announcement by other institutions did nothing to abate the
competitiveness. But I think from the student's point of view, it
is a good thing. This is America. This is a market.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, say those educators worried by the trend, the changes
at Harvard and Princeton mean that middle-income families whose
children are the cream of their schools can negotiate better aid
packages at elite colleges. But the tactics are having a cascading
effect. Beyond the top colleges, there is an abandonment of the
principle of so-called ``need-blind'' admission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Need-blind'' means accepting students regardless of their
ability to pay and providing a mix of grants, loans and campus
jobs. Many institutions that a decade ago operated by such rules
say they no longer can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago we stated publicly that while we had been
need-blind in the past, we could no longer afford to do it,'' said
Michael Fraher, financial aid director at Vassar College.
</P>
<P>
   Vassar, like Carleton, Smith, Oberlin and others, have become
somewhat ``need-sensitive'' in their admissions procedures in
recent years. That means that, particularly toward the bottom of
the list of those admitted, such institutions do not promise to
meet 100 percent of applicants' needs.
</P>
<P>
   Students from lower-income groups, including members of
minorities, who are not at the top of their classes, may be
rejected because of their inability to afford the tuition, while
students of similar qualification but higher income will get in.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we look at the bottom 10 to 20 percent of the students,''
Fraher said, ``we have to ask ourselves whether we really want to
commit $18,000 of Vassar scholarship money to a certain student
when we can attract two other, perhaps better students, by granting
each half that amount.''
</P>
<P>
   The other trend that has made it difficult for less-endowed
colleges to maintain need-blind policies is the increased use of
so-called merit aid, meaning the offering of scholarships to top
students whether or not their families need the money. The authors
of ``The Student Aid Game'' say that merit aid grew at a 13 percent
annual rate (after adjusting for inflation) in the 1980s and has
apparently accelerated since. Need-based aid, as a portion of all
aid, fell by one-eighth in the 1980s, although it increased
annually by 10 percent during that period.
</P>
<P>
   Through such aid, second-tier institutions seek to lure students
who might otherwise choose a more expensive or more exclusive
school.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is also visible at some state institutions. This past
season, some state legislatures, including those of Kentucky,
Florida and Louisiana, which control state university budgets,
moved toward merit aid in an effort to keep the most promising
students in their states.
</P>
<P>
   The move toward greater use of merit scholarships, particularly
at a time of record stock portfolios, has some scholars asserting
that colleges are backing away from traditional responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``College endowments are at historically unprecedented heights,
so the number of need-blind institutions should be increasing
rather than decreasing,'' said Jerome Karabel, professor of
sociology at the University of California at Berkeley, who is
studying the question. ``Institutions of higher education need to
ask themselves whether they are moving in the wrong direction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
