<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-AUSTRIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE SAYS EUROPEAN CHRISTIANS MUST RECONCILE WITH JEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ Speaking to a group of Austrian officials and
dignitaries that included former President Kurt Waldheim, Pope John
Paul II said Saturday that European Christians had a moral
obligation to fully reconcile with the Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot forget that the history of Europe is tightly
entwined with the history of the people from whence came our Lord,
Jesus,'' the pope said. ``Unspeakable suffering was inflicted on
the Jewish people in Europe, and we cannot affirm that all the
roots of this injustice have been eradicated. Reconciliation with
the Jews is one of the most fundamental duties of Christians in
Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   As he did with all the other guests who filed past him in the
receiving line at the presidential residence in the old Hapsburg
Imperial Palace, the pope shook Waldheim's hand and said a few
words.
</P>
<P>
   Historians and researchers have accused Waldheim, 79, of
complicity in war crimes in the Balkans while he served as an
officer in the German army during World War II. He is not a pariah
in his native country, but his name is on a State Department list
of people who cannot enter the United States because of grave
charges against them. Waldheim has denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   This is the pope's third visit to Austria, and it was not his
first encounter with Waldheim, who served one term as U.N.
secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
   During John Paul's last visit, in 1988, he was criticized for
meeting several times with Waldheim, then president, who had been
closely linked to the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Since that visit the pope has reached out to Jewish
organizations. He took a historic step toward reconciliation this
year by apologizing for the Catholic Church's silence during the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-98 1320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
