<DOCNO> NYT19980620.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8611 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-ECON-600&AMP;ADD-NY     06-20 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECON-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN PROMISES TO FIX ITS ECONOMY, BUT OFFERS NO SPECIFICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Japanese government pledged before a meeting of the
Group of Seven industrialized nations Saturday that it would revive
its economy and repair its banking system, but it fell short of
saying anything new or specific.
</P>
<P>
   The failure to provide any new commitment to economic
restructuring seemed a step backward from the expectations that had
been raised just a few days earlier. When the United States joined
with Japan on Wednesday to intervene in foreign exchange markets to
prop up the yen, President Clinton and other officials strongly
hinted that Japan was ready to take new steps to bolster its
economy, but Saturday those steps seemed more elusive than ever.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Japanese government insisted that it had made no
promises of further restructuring in exchange for American support
for its currency.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask if there are secret agreements between the United
States and Japan: There are none,'' Eisuke Sakakibara, deputy
finance minister for international affairs, said at the conclusion
of the G-7 meeting of deputy finance ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Financial markets throughout the world surged in the last few
days in part on the expectation that the yen's long slide had ended
and that Japan would undertake new policies to improve its economy.
It is not clear how the markets will react in the coming week to
the lack of any clear new steps to emerge this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. deputy treasury secretary, Lawrence Summers, who is in
Tokyo to attend the meeting and hold talks with officials here,
called his discussions with Japanese officials ``very useful'' and
said that they were aware of the urgency of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is going to be most important going forward is the steps
that Japan takes to take advantage of this window of opportunity,''
said Summers at a news conference Saturday. ``There is a clear
recognition of the need to move rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   But he would not say whether Japan had outlined new economic
measures or how confident he was that it would respond decisively.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting of G-7 officials, expanded to include
representatives of 10 Asian countries, the International Monetary
Fund, the World Bank and the Asian Development Bank, was intended
to put pressure on Japan to take further steps and to reassure the
financial markets that there was a new determination on Japan's
part to address its problems. But the vagueness of the simple
statement issued by the meeting's participants Saturday suggested
that it would not be easy to keep up the momentum for cooperation
if Japan does not move fast to mend its economy.
</P>
<P>
   In the statement, the United States and other countries agreed
to ``monitor developments'' and cooperate ``as appropriate'' in the
foreign exchange markets, but there was no mention of any effort to
reverse the decline of the yen, which has fallen by 42 percent
since its peak in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``We issued a statement expressing our seriousness and urgency
of the matter,'' Sakakibara said. ``I think they believe our
seriousness.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem is that Japan has repeatedly promised before to
tackle its economic and banking troubles. And while it is pushing
through with a grand scheme, called the ``big bang,'' to
restructure the financial industry, it has backtracked on some of
its previous pledges to liberalize its markets and to create a more
open financial environment.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is also preparing a proposal, called the ``total plan,''
to eliminate the huge bad debts that threaten the nation's banking
system. But this was in the works well before the American-Japanese
intervention.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It is not clear whether Clinton and other Americans were
expecting Japan to announce a major new effort to bolster the
economy. But Japanese officials seemed puzzled by what Clinton and
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin were thinking when they suggested
that bold new actions by Japan were in the works to justify a
higher value for the yen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very much afraid that he doesn't understand what's going
on in Japan,'' a senior Finance Ministry official said of Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   Summers emphasized that Japan needed to increase transparency in
the way its financial industry operates and to tackle the bad
loans. Japan also needs to work out a mechanism to deal with
troubled financial institutions, some of which are on a lifeline
from the Bank of Japan, the nation's central bank.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is just about to start carrying out a $120 billion fiscal
stimulus package that includes at least $58 billion in real
spending and $30 billion in temporary income tax cuts. It has also
set aside nearly $220 billion to bail out the nation's banks, which
are burdened by more than $600 billion in bad or doubtful debt.
</P>
<P>
   Already, economists say that Japan is likely to see growth in
the third quarter this year. But regulators, officials and
economists abroad are still concerned that Japan is not moving fast
or far enough to alter radically the nature of its financial system
and the overall economy. So they fear that once the public money
runs out, Japan's economy may slump again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-98 1330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
