<SLUG> BC-ELECTION-THEME-EDUC-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.M.)  
 EDUCATION IS WATCHWORD IN CLOSELY CONTESTED HOUSE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. _ Ask Phil Maloof for his most important
legislative proposal if he is sent to Congress in a special
election on Tuesday, and he has a ready reply: ``We need more
computers in the classroom for kids.''
</P>
<P>
   His Republican rival, Heather Wilson, was so eager to highlight
her bonafides on education that she did not mention that she was a
Rhodes Scholar and an arms negotiator in the Bush administration.
Instead, she noted with pride that she had been one of five
finalists to be superintendent of the Albuquerque public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Around the nation, candidates for state and local office this
year are talking far more about education than any other theme.
Nowhere is that better demonstrated than here in New Mexico's 1st
Congressional District, where a race to succeed Rep. Steven Schiff,
a Republican who died in March, sometimes resembles a contest for a
seat on the local school board more than an election to the U.S.
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Wilson has tried to skewer Maloof, a Democratic member of
the state Senate, with television commercials that accuse him of
skipping sessions of the chamber's higher education committee.
Everywhere he goes, Maloof touts his endorsement from principals of
seven schools in his Senate district. His commercials attack Mrs.
Wilson for not voting in the last three school board elections
here.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the focus on education, the closely contested campaign
here in the foothills of the Sandia Mountains _ the only full-scale
congressional election before November _ offers an important
preview of what awaits voters (and even the candidates) as the
midterm election year unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   Attack commercials are alive and well. For all their pledges to
stay on the high ground and to condemn their opponents' efforts at
``character assassination,'' Maloof and Mrs. Wilson have not been
timid about flinging oratorical mud. In fact, both sides agree that
the campaign in this usually placid state is the nastiest they have
seen here in years.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by this race, it is also clear that Democrats still
intend to demonize Speaker Newt Gingrich, as they did successfully
in the 1996 elections. In a new Maloof commercial, the announcer
warns that Mrs. Wilson would abolish the Department of Education.
``Tell Heather Wilson to stop siding with Newt Gingrich,'' he says
as side-by-side photographs of Gingrich and Mrs. Wilson pop on the
screen. (Republicans, by contrast, have not featured Clinton, who
is fairly popular in this state.)
</P>
<P>
   The commercials of the 37-year-old Mrs. Wilson, a former head of
the state Department of Children, Youth and Families, portray the
31-year-old Maloof as an empty suit. ``I just don't think he
understands the issues,'' the announcer intones. ``Phil's just too
young.''
</P>
<P>
   One explanation for the intense personal attacks may be another
reality of the 1998 campaign: With the hardy economy, the campaigns
here are having a particularly hard time engaging uninterested
voters. As a result, both the Maloof and Wilson campaigns are
running particularly aggressive telephone and literature drives to
get people to the polls Tuesday. Except for an organization
advocating term limits, which is running advertisements backing
Maloof, outside interest groups are preserving their advertising
budgets for the regular House races.
</P>
<P>
   While this race offers important clues for November, it is
crucial in its own right, which helps explain why Hillary Rodham
Clinton and Tipper Gore, as well as House Minority Leader Richard
Gephardt and Rep. Patrick Kennedy of Rhode Island are coming here
this weekend to campaign for Maloof. House Majority Leader Dick
Armey is scheduled to campaign here for Mrs. Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   If Maloof manages to wrest the seat from Republicans, then
Democrats would have to pick up only 10 seats in November to retake
the House. Officials on both sides agree that whoever wins the
election Tuesday to complete Schiff's term will be the favorite
when the candidates face off again in November. (Earlier this month
the two candidates won their parties' primaries for the general
election.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The winner has all the momentum going into the fall,'' said
Steve Grossman, national chairman of the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   The latest polls show the race dead even in the district, which
is split roughly between Republicans and Democrats. But polls show
that the Green Party candidate, Robert Anderson, is gaining ground
and could siphon votes from Maloof. Another Green Party contender
contributed to a Democrat's loss in a special House election in an
adjoining district last year.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Wilson is still trying to recover from a 60-second
Maloof commercial that says she ``abused her position of power''
when she was in the Cabinet by trying to remove a confidential case
file with potentially embarrassing information about her husband,
Jay Hone.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Wilson asserted that the advertisement was ``full of
lies.'' Her aides concede, however, that it has been the single
most damaging development in the campaign. ``We lost eight points
overnight,'' said Steve Bell, Mrs. Wilson's chief strategist. ``It
was like a torpedo amid ships.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their deep ideological differences, Mrs. Wilson and
Maloof could not be more opposite in terms of their personal
styles, backgrounds and personalities. Maloof is from one of New
Mexico's wealthiest and most prominent families, which made its
fortune in the hotel, casino, liquor and banking industries. His
father, George Maloof, was so prominent that there is a bronze
statute of him in downtown Albuquerque, with the inscription,
``philanthropist/humanitarian.''
</P>
<P>
   Maloof has dipped into the family fortune to lend at least $1.2
million to his campaign, and is expected to spend closer to $2
million; Mrs. Wilson has raised nearly $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Maloof's biggest weakness is that he lacks a deep command of
many issues, is prone to misstatements and often comes off as
uncomfortable, even frightened, at campaign forums, particularly
when he ventures beyond the same stock Democratic talking points
that he repeats again and again. At debates, while he appears
earnest, he sometimes relies on thick briefing books. The missteps
are so frequent that the National Republican Congressional
Committee has enough material to regularly put out a flyer titled,
``Mal-OOPS!''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At their last televised debate, on Thursday night, Maloof was
asked whether he would support programs to protect the Mexican gray
wolf and spotted owl, even if they cost jobs. Instead of answering
the question, Maloof noted that he was supported by environmental
groups and favored the Endangered Species Act, and added, ``I enjoy
camping _ it's something I really enjoy.'' Then he quickly tried to
change the subject to education, only to be admonished by the
moderator.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Wilson has sought to make Maloof's wealth an issue, a
strategy Lt. Gov. Gray Davis of California used in defeating a
multimillionaire rival, Al Checchi, in that state's Democratic
primary for governor this month. Her slogan, ``You just can't buy
the experience Heather Wilson has,'' is an adaptation of the Davis
slogan, ``Experience money can't buy.''
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview, Maloof was at a loss to explain the
differences between his race and that of Checchi. ``I don't know
what hurt him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Wilson, a former Air Force captain who was on the National
Security Council staff in the Bush administration, is far more
articulate. But she has never run for elective office before and
lacks Maloof's deep roots in the community.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Wilson moved to the state less than seven years ago, and
her accent sounds more like she is from her native New Hampshire
than from the Southwest. She was the hand-picked choice of Sen.
Pete Domenici, the state's senior senator.
</P>
<P>
   For all her smoothness on the stump, her own pollsters have
found that voters are put off by Mrs. Wilson's officious and
sometimes stiff manner and her preference for eye-glazing policy
discussions. Determined to make herself likable, Mrs. Wilson tries
to smile her way through campaign appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, who has taken a leave as Domenici's chief of staff to run
the Wilson campaign in the final weeks, likens Mrs. Wilson to Sen.
Richard Lugar, R-Ind., who is highly respected but also one of the
more colorless lawmakers in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Asked in an interview why she has hit so hard on what she
describes as Maloof's unpreparedness, Mrs. Wilson said: ``There are
a lot of people in Congress and in public life, average people of
average intelligence. Or even below average intelligence. I don't
think that's it, really. There's something else. Maybe it's
confidence or experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly in the final days of the campaign, officials on
both sides said their own polls showed that education had shot up
as by far the most critical issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the polling shows that the undecided vote is the female
vote,'' said Tom Hujar, Maloof's chief consultant, ``so both
candidates are going very heavily in terms of their appeals toward
women. So education is in the forefront.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-98 1358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980620.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8636 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLOMBIA-ELECTION-2TA     06-20 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-ELECTION-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS COLOMBIA PICKS NEW CHIEF, REBELS VOICE THEIR VIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia _ For months now, the campaign posters and
rallies of Horacio Serpa of the Liberal Party have championed him
as the presidential candidate best able to negotiate an end to the
civil conflict that has virtually dismembered this Andean nation,
leaving some 31,000 dead.
</P>
<P>
   Serpa's campaign has promised that this former interior
minister, who is from the working-class oil port of
Barrancabermeja, could draw on his ties to the political left to
find the elusive path to peace.
</P>
<P>
   The only risk to this election strategy, political analysts
warned, was it might make Serpa appear overly friendly toward the
rebels and undermine his credibility with the military and business
elite.
</P>
<P>
   But in these final days of campaigning for the election of a
successor to President Ernesto Samper on Sunday, the two main rebel
groups issued stinging criticisms of Serpa.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest group, the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia,
known by its Spanish acronym FARC, blamed him for the breakdown in
peace talks with the government six years ago, and accused him of
waving the banner of peace solely for electoral gain.
</P>
<P>
   In a move worthy of his nickname, ``Sure Shot,'' Manuel
Marulanda, the rebel leader who had not been photographed publicly
in 10 years, held talks at his secret hideout with a representative
of Serpa's Conservative Party rival, Andres Pastrana, and allowed a
picture of the meeting to be published in newspapers here.
</P>
<P>
   The surprising turnaround in the two candidates' stands as peace
negotiators is only the latest in a series of strange twists in the
election that will end the presidency of Samper, who has spent most
of his turbulent term fending off accusations that Cali drug
dealers financed his election. In the first round of the election,
on May 31, Serpa won 34.64 percent of the votes and Pastrana 34.32
percent.
</P>
<P>
   If the bywords of the candidates have been ``peace'' and
``change,'' the word political analysts here frequently resort to
is ``paradoxical.''
</P>
<P>
   While the country is reeling in almost every sense after four
years of Samper _ economically, socially and politically _ the
leading candidate in voter surveys has been Samper's staunchest
defender and hand-picked successor, Serpa.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter of resignation as Samper's interior minister last
year, Serpa wrote, ``You, president, have set an example of
equanimity, dignity and patriotism, and under your leadership the
government will overcome with fortune the enormous challenges it
has been presented.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Serpa said in a pre-election debate that he would
not rule out extraditing his former boss to the United States
should Washington seek this. By contrast, Pastrana, whom voters
might have thought more likely to surrender the unpopular president
to the American authorities, rejected extradition for Samper.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana, 44, who is favored by the business community here, is
the son of former President Misael Pastrana. A former mayor of
Bogota himself, he could, in theory, make the most convincing case
for offering Colombia a fresh start, since he has been out of
government for the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   His television campaign advertisements list the violence,
corruption and other troubles of Colombia over the last four years
with Samper's face gradually fading into that of Serpa.
</P>
<P>
   But Pastrana lacks the charisma of Serpa, 55, who has managed to
put the Conservatives on the defensive by predicting that he will
privatize state industries. Pastrana has been reduced to pledging
his opposition to privatization.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana has produced a more detailed peace proposal than Serpa.
As part of a settlement, he has proposed ending the use of
herbicides to kill drug crops, calling instead for an
internationally backed plan to offer coca-growing peasants
alternative ways to earn a living.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana lacks the media backing and the government support
enjoyed by Serpa. The government ombudsman's recent review of
election campaign coverage showed television stations giving
substantially more air time to Serpa. The television stations
depend on the government for their operating licenses, while the
licenses of news shows are periodically subject to being revoked by
government officials.
</P>
<P>
   Noemi Sanin, an independent presidential candidate whose
unexpectedly strong showing in the first round of voting has turned
her into an arbiter of political morality, has also denounced the
Samper government for doling out free publicity to Serpa on the
government-run television station and for publicly supporting his
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sanin, whose 2.6 million votes could provide the winning
margin for Pastrana, has declined to throw her support behind
either of the candidates. Doing so, she said in an interview on
Friday, would subvert the principles of her political movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The essence of political behavior in our campaign,'' she said,
``was what? To desist with the vote that is directed, manipulated.
Instead, vote your conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Castro, a 59-year-old egg wholesaler, said he supported
Serpa because ``he knows our country's problems.'' Asked if Serpa
was not responsible for some of them, Castro gathered up a handful
of coins. He picked out a silver-colored coin to represent Samper,
as the chief who was responsible for his government's actions, and
a brass one to represent Serpa.
</P>
<P>
   ``See, they're not even the same color,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The most pressing issue, along with the economic troubles, has
been negotiating an end to the conflict that the military here has
been unable to win in the last 30 years. Both candidates have said
that, if elected, they will personally take charge of negotiations
with the guerrillas, and both said last week they would agree to a
guerrilla demand for the withdrawal of government security forces
from five municipalities as a requirement for negotiations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But it was Samper's agreement to pull back troops from the five
municipalities, a move that the rebels had been seeking
unsuccessfully for three years, that prompted the rebels' public
attack on Serpa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, with electoral ends to win votes and guarantee the
triumph of Dr. Serpa,'' Samper ``offers to evacuate,'' said a
communique from the rebels, which also criticized Serpa's record as
a peacemaker over the last 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   As chief peace negotiator under former President Cesar Gaviria,
the rebels say, Serpa closed peace talks in Mexico, ushering in the
``total war'' offensive against the guerrillas. As interior
minister under Samper, he saw the creation of armed citizen's
defense groups known as convivirs, which the guerrillas and human
rights groups both contended were mechanisms to legalize
paramilitary death squads. A Colombian court has now ruled the
defense groups illegal.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Serpa said he would name Alvaro Uribe Velez, the
former governor of Antioquia who spearheaded the creation of
defense groups around Medellin, as his defense minister, apparently
in an effort to establish his credentials among the military and
conservative landowners.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a rhetoric of peace, but in practice there's been an
increase in terror while he's been in government,'' said Carlos
Franco, a former guerrilla of the Marxist April 19 Movement, known
as the M-19, who has joined other political figures to support
Pastrana. ``I think all this led the FARC to conclude that Serpa's
chances of negotiating peace were low.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
