<HEADLINE>
U.S. RETREATS ON INQUIRIES INTO URBAN HOUSING OFFICES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., La., Calif., Mo., Nev.)   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RENO, Nev. _ Under mounting pressure from the Clinton
administration and mayors around the country, federal lawmakers
have reversed their decision to have the Department of Housing and
Urban Development's chief investigator examine housing programs in
three cities led by black mayors.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Baltimore, New Orleans and San Francisco two
months ago as targets of a House subcommittee's ``Urban Fraud
Initiative'' infuriated the mayors of those cities _ Kurt Schmoke,
Marc Morial and Willie Brown, respectively _ as well as mayors from
scores of other places, many of whom are meeting here for a few
days at the U.S. Conference of Mayors annual convention.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the mayors charged that racism played a role in the
selection of the cities.
</P>
<P>
   Mayors attending the convention were so angered by the proposed
investigation that they planned to approve a resolution Saturday,
calling for the suspension of any investigation until objective
criteria are developed to select cities in need of examination for
fraud and mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
   But the thrust of such a resolution was made moot in Washington
on Thursday, when the chairman of the housing subcommittee of the
House Appropriation Committee, Rep. Jerry Lewis, R-Calif., agreed
that the initial selections by Inspector General Susan Gaffney of
the Department of Housing and Urban Development should be set
aside. He also agreed that after new criteria were established,
those cities or others, and perhaps more than three, would be
selected for investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was not immediately available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo, who is attending the convention
in Reno, hailed Lewis' decision. An early critic of the initial
plan, he said, `'If cities are selected fairly, then that's fine
with me. I'm all for enforcement and weeding out waste, fraud and
abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   The housing investigation was one of several significant issues
under discussion in Reno on Saturday among mayors from cities in
more than 40 states who are attending the four-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to President Clinton (by satellite) on Friday and
Cuomo on Saturday, the convention schedule also includes speeches
from Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater, Labor Secretary Alexis
Herman and Attorney General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Cochran, the executive director of the mayors' conference,
said all their remarks are intended to elaborate upon the
administration's recent report, State of the Cities 1998, which
warned that many urban centers, despite their best financial
condition in decades, are facing mounting problems of education,
housing and joblessness.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the convention, Cochran said, was for mayors to
share ideas that are working so others may test them in their
cities.
</P>
<P>
   As the first Cabinet officer to follow Clinton addressing the
mayors, Cuomo on Saturday expressed the continuing need to satisfy
the growing demand for adequate housing for the poorest of
Americans, a pitch that is reflected in the housing department's
1999 budget request. He has asked Congress for $1.8 billion in new
program spending, which includes $585 million for 100,000 new
housing vouchers and $400 million for job creation in cities. In
each of the last five years, the department's budget has remained
flat, at around $24 billion.
</P>
<P>
   While many of the mayors heartily supported his request, some
were still upset over the pending investigation of housing programs
for reasons, they said, they do not entirely understand.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel Cleaver of Kansas City, Mo., president of the National
Conference of Black Mayors, a separate group from the one meeting
here, has been a vocal critic of Ms. Gaffney and Lewis for the
selections of cities led by black mayors. He said he called Ms.
Reno on Thursday and asked for a private meeting after she arrived
here to discuss what he called ``a rogue investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver conceded that he was unaware Lewis had initiated a
change in policy. Yet even that did not satisfy him. ``At the very
minimum,'' he said, ``a statement ought to be issued by the
inspector general, if not, by Lewis, stating there never has been
any information that suggested these targeted cities had fraud or
corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
