<DOCNO> NYT19980620.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8679 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAN-SOCCER-COX &UR;      06-20 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-SOCCER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FREEDOMS AND NATIONAL ASPIRATIONS MAKE SOCCER DUAL IMPORTANT TO
IRANIANS
</HEADLINE>
     &HT;     For Sunday, June 21 
 &HT;     EDS Note time element. This story should run Sunday 
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ Iranians would love to see their national team
whip the United States in Sunday's World Cup soccer match in
France, but not because many still chant ``Death to America'' at
weekly prayers.
</P>
<P>
   Iran is at a crossroads. Its 60 million people are testing the
limits of new personal freedoms and emerging from years of war and
world isolation.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the soccer team has become the symbol of reform and
progress. That the team shares the same fields in France with the
major powers promises Iranians a brighter future, not just more
fights against the same old ``Satans.''
</P>
<P>
   So, when Sunday's game starts in Lyon, France, at 11:30 p.m.
Tehran time (mid-afternoon Eastern time), almost all Iranians will
be watching, but at home.
</P>
<P>
   There are no bars, let alone sports bars, in the Islamic
Republic of Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Community centers had planned to show the game on big screens,
but those plans were scrapped out of what many see as government
concern that a win or tie could spark highly un-religious street
celebrations in the early morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people have a thirst for happiness. For 20 years, there
has been much mourning,'' said newspaper editor Mashallah Shams.
``If someone just goes out and dances in the street right now, they
will say he is crazy and stop him. But, if 20 million people start
dancing, no one can stop them.''
</P>
<P>
   There is the usual soccer fanaticism _ a fan recently scoured
the downtown strip of sports stores buying up 1,000 Iranian jerseys
for friends in the United States. Some universities postponed exams
and people have delayed summer vacations until after the World Cup
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But the love of Iranian soccer is better illustrated by impish
nine-year-old Samayeh Hemati. Under the required head scarf and
black cape, there's a soccer fan in blue jeans and sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   She plays with the boys in the street and saves a picture of her
favorite Iranian forward.
</P>
<P>
   Women might be the country's biggest fans, though they cannot
play on organized teams. When the team qualified for the tournament
in December, men and women danced side-by-side in the streets. The
ruling religious Mullahs were nervous, but did not dare try to stop
them.
</P>
<P>
   It had been 20 years since Iran made it to the World Cup. Since
then, Iranians replaced a brutal, American-backed, dictator with a
popular, but stern, Islamic revolution. They stormed the U.S.
Embassy in 1979, holding 52 Americans captive for 444 days. Later,
the Iranians saw one of their airliners shot down by a U.S. Navy
missile.
</P>
<P>
   Iranians saw their cities bombed and hundreds of thousands of
men and children killed in the eight year war against Iraq. They
are just now restoring relations with many neighbors and flirting
with the United States, long called ``the Great Satan.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year they surprised the world by electing President
Mohammad Khatami, who promised to loosen the strict religious codes
if he can hold off the more powerful religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   When the team qualified for the World Cup in December, thousands
of women forced their way into the 100,000 seat male-only stadium
to honor the team. People danced in the street and soccer started
to mean change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big revolution. (The government) couldn't do
anything,'' said Iranian Alan Petrosian, a wealthy 21-year-old
eating in a ritzy Tehran hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Near the shrine of the late Ayatollah Khomeini, where
working-class families picnic, soccer means progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you chant for the team, the better they play and the
more Iran participates in the world,'' said car mechanic Ahmad
Heydari, 28.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some politicians have hyped the ``Great Satan'' angle and
political overtones swirl around the game.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has taped a goodwill message with the hope it
will be viewed on TV by Iranians during the game and a Swiss
referee has been chosen to make sure things are neutral.
</P>
<P>
   But even some of the conservative clerics, usually strongly
anti-American, want to keep politics out of soccer.
</P>
<P>
   On the burning question of whether the players should make the
customary exchange of uniforms after the game, cleric Sayed Jalal
Ahmad Panahi said they should, as long as it is something done in
every game and the gesture is not ``misused'' to ``lessen Iran's
stance.''
</P>
<P>
   Symptomatic of the country's identity crisis, Iranians have been
flipping channels between the World Cup action and the dramatic
broadcasts of the popular, reformist, mayor of Tehran. He is
defending himself against religious conservatives who have put him
on trial.
</P>
<P>
   Even today is not just saved for soccer. Sunday is a work day
here and the hard-line Iranian parliament is holding an impeachment
hearing for one of Khatami's most important cabinet members.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's newspapers focused on that battle as well as the game
against the U.S., but it was clear that the soccer team is
identified with reform.
</P>
<P>
   An editorial cartoon portrayed famous hard-line politicians,
still stunned by Khatami's surprise election, lecturing the soccer
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't underestimate your opponents!'' the hard-liners warned
the team.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For use by clients of The New York Times News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-98 1434EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
