<HEADLINE>
THE STARS ARE ALIGNED FOR GREENE TO DAZZLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Maurice Greene felt he was ready to break the
world record for the 100-meter dash. His coaches said he was ready.
His opponents said he was ready.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, the world champion gets a big chance. The
occasion is right _ the U.S. outdoor track and field championships.
The heat and humidity provides good sprinting weather because his
muscles can get loose. The opposition is expected to include such
world-class sprinters as Dennis Mitchell, Tim Montgomery and Brian
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   And Greene, like many other Americans, was not enamored with the
frequent breast-beating of Donovan Bailey, the Canadian who set the
record of 9.84 seconds in the 1996 Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, the 23-year-old Greene moved toward his goal. In
the quarterfinals, he ran impressively and won in 9.84 seconds,
helped by a following wind too strong to allow record recognition.
In the semifinals 2 hours 20 minutes later, although he did not
look overly sharp, he still won cleanly in 9.96 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first round,'' he said, ``I was thinking too much about
the record instead of running my race and letting the record come
to me. If I'm just thinking about my technique and run my own race,
I will be OK If I don't, I'll be in trouble. So in that respect,
the semifinal was good.''
</P>
<P>
   Very good, according to two victims in that race. One was
30-year-old Kevin Little, a high-level sprinter for a decade. The
other was 19-year-old Ja'Warren Hooker, a Washington freshman and
one of America's sprint proteges.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll bring out the best in you,'' Little said. ``You have to
be ready to run every time you race him.''
</P>
<P>
   At least Little knew what to expect. Hooker, who had never run
against Greene before, faced him in the quarterfinals and
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``His first 50 meters is pretty controlled,'' Hooker said. ``But
in the last 50, he explodes. The first time I ran against him here,
I was next to him and I was with him for 50. Then he really took
off.''
</P>
<P>
   John Smith, who coaches Greene, could have warned Hooker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maurice is a world champion when he puts his mind to it,''
Smith said. ``He usually comes up with results. He has a passion
for whatever he does and always lays it on the line. In the fall of
1996, Greene went to Los Angeles from Kansas City, Kan., with
basically nothing. But he has a serious commitment. He's a very
serious man. I enjoy working with him. I like working with people
who have a purpose in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith also coaches the sprinters at UCLA, so Art Venegas, UCLA's
throwing coach, sees Greene on the practice field daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competitively,'' Venegas said, ``Maurice Greene is a freak of
nature. I'm a track fan as well as a coach, and I like him. He
seems to rise to the challenges in front of him. Indoors, Jon
Drummond was in better shape, but Maurice found a way to get the
world record in the 60 meters. He's got pure, unadulterated
competitiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   With all that, a world record was still a big order.
</P>
<P>
   ``World records are looked at as something almost impossible,''
Smith said. ``He looks at them as something he can do, and I like
that. He's interested in being the fastest 100-meter guy. I don't
try to control what's natural. I just try to manage it.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Greene.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have world championships or Olympic Games this
year,'' Greene said, ``so the world record is the most important
thing. It was in the U.S. for so long, it's time for it to come
back.''
</P>
<P>
   SPIKE MARKS
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's winners included John Godina in the men's discus
throw (220 feet 1 inch), Marc Davis in the men's 5,000 meters (13
minutes 40.62 seconds) and Lynn Jennings in the women's 10,000
meters (34:09.86). For the 37-year-old Jennings, it was the seventh
title in 12 years in this event and her 38th national title
overall. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
