<SLUG> BC-CHINA-OPERA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA HINDERS OPERA PERFORMANCE IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ Rebuffing international pressure to
compromise, Chinese authorities instead chose to escalate their
dispute with the director of a classic Chinese opera that is
scheduled to open in New York City next month as the centerpiece of
the Lincoln Center Festival.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute, which seems to be about power as much as about art,
now threatens to scuttle the Shanghai Kunqu Opera Company's
project, ``The Peony Pavilion,'' originally expected to open on
July 7.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Shanghai officials accused the opera's director,
Chen Shi-Zheng, of making his production ``feudal, absurd and
pornographic in a way that is unacceptable to Chinese viewers and
artists.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen countered that his interpretation of the opera, with
innovative and vivid staging, actually comes closer to the original
spirit intended when it was written by Tang Xianzu in 1598. Lincoln
Center hired Chen to direct ``The Peony Pavilion,'' in part,
because of his ambition to breathe new life into a genre that has
deteriorated in recent decades.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities, insisting that the world see a version that
Chinese officials are used to, have required extensive revisions to
the opera's script. Last week, they blocked shipment of the
production's sets, props and costumes, now all stuck at Shanghai
International Airport. They defended that move by saying the items
will be needed as the opera is revised.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute is emerging just days before the arrival of
President Clinton to China, a visit that officials from both
countries are touting as a symbol of cooperation. Yet diplomats
from the United States and France, where ``The Peony Pavilion'' is
also scheduled to be performed this year, have pleaded with
Shanghai leaders to intervene and solve the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Burghardt, U.S. consul general in Shanghai, said he had
urged the Shanghai authorities to allow the production's shipment
to proceed to New York on Sunday, and expressed the hope that the
dispute could be resolved in time for the opening on July 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the dress rehearsal, and I thought it was terrific,''
Burghardt said. ``This is a very important example of U.S.-China
cultural cooperation. The Kunqu company was in dire financial
straits before Lincoln Center came along.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen, saying he was distressed by the thought that the
production might be foiled, stressed that he was willing to make
minor adjustments to his production in order to compromise with the
authorities. But he is not willing to completely restage the show,
as the officials are now demanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We signed a contract last year, approved by the Bureau of
Culture, that says I am artistic director and can stage the opera
according to my artistic vision,'' Chen said. ``These people don't
understand the meaning of a contract.''
</P>
<P>
   In principle, the Shanghai Bureau of Culture might have little
say over a production to be staged in the United States, and funded
by the Lincoln Center Festival.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, Communist Party bureaucrats have wielded decisive
control over artistic matters for years and are reluctant to give
it up. Many movie directors, authors and actors in China know about
interference by officials at the Ministry of Culture, still a
redoubt of ultraconservative officials.
</P>
<P>
   Chen, a native of China who moved to the United States in 1987,
said he was warned by friends that the typical method of staging a
show in China includes inviting political leaders to a rehearsal
and making whatever changes they ask for, large or small, even if
the politicians understand nothing of opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say I have no right to adapt it,'' Chen said. ``To me,
the point is to offer another artistic vision. They may not like
it; that is their right. But should they prevent us from performing
it at all?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
