u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-IN-WAITING-N     06-20 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-IN-WAITING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 METS IN MINORS WAIT, WAIT AND WAIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bill Pulsipher is frustrated. Jay Payton is back to
playing center field. And Paul Wilson is just trying to get back to
live games.
</P>
<P>
   Pulsipher, Payton and Wilson are arguably the three
highest-profile minor leaguers in the Mets organization. And each
is headed in a different direction.
</P>
<P>
   Pulsipher's current mood stems from the holding pattern he is in
at Class AAA Norfolk. The 24-year-old left-hander is 7-5 with a
3.96 earned run average for the Tides, but he has lost his last two
starts. He knows there is no room for him in the Mets' rotation
right now. But that does not alleviate any of the thoughts going
through his head.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Pulsipher has no chance for a call-up. The day after
trading for Hideo Nomo on June 4, Mets General Manager Steve
Phillips called Pulsipher to tell him that he would not rule out
promoting Pulsipher in a bullpen role. But that apparently did not
assuage Pulsipher's fears, because he and Phillips met in Norfolk
last week to talk again.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't much of a change, and he is continually
frustrated by that,'' Jim Duquette, the Mets' director of player
personnel, said Saturday. ``Bill has these in and out phases. Some
days he can handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   The others are the tough ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had a pretty good season,'' Duquette said. ``The majority
of his starts have been quality starts, which is what you'd expect
from him. He's had shaky defense behind him a couple of times, or
you see an outing where he has one bad inning and is then able to
settle down.''
</P>
<P>
   In 14 starts, Pulsipher has allowed 50 runs, 38 earned, and 91
hits in 86 1/3 innings. He has walked 41 and struck out 58. Lately,
his name has come up in trade rumors, but until a deal is made or
until the Mets beckon (and Mark Mimbs is the hottest left-hander in
Norfolk right now), Pulsipher will just have to wait.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, he is not known for his patience. ``All we can
do is try to maintain the positives with him,'' Duquette said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have no such problems with Payton, who returned last
Monday from an 18-day stay on the disabled list because of a pulled
right hamstring. Duquette said Payton is not playing first base
anymore. It is either left field, center field or designated
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as he stays healthy, we'll look at him in center
field,'' Duquette said. ``He's got pretty good speed. He's also
been hitting at the top of the order. So if he gets called up
again, he could be a lead-off center fielder.''
</P>
<P>
   First, though, Payton needs to strengthen his hamstrings. While
he was on the disabled list, an examination showed that his
hamstrings were significantly weaker than his quadriceps. And even
though Payton was put on a strengthening program immediately, he
felt something in the right hamstring earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We backed him off,'' Duquette said. ``We're basically being
real conservative with him.''
</P>
<P>
   That is because, at 25, Payton is the brightest offensive
prospect in the organization. After undergoing numerous elbow
surgeries that limited him to 71 minor-league games two seasons ago
and none last year, Payton is batting .255 with four home runs and
14 runs batted in, in 46 games with the Tides. He has 10 doubles,
three triples and 11 stolen bases. He has already been called up to
the Mets briefly this season, although he never actually appeared
in a game.
</P>
<P>
   And it is not a stretch to think Payton could be playing a
little center field for the Mets, maybe even by the end of this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Jay, and how much time he had off, you never know when
he's going to click with the bat,'' Duquette said. ``It's so
potent. And you can't put a ceiling on that. It wouldn't surprise
any of us if he got back to the big leagues. But we don't want to
put any pressure on him.''
</P>
<P>
   The most pleasant surprise of Payton's season thus far has been
his ability to play the outfield and make the throws. ``When we
mapped it out before the season, we looked at him thinking he would
play first base the entire year and maybe we could get him out to
the outfield,'' Duquette said. ``He has exceeded our
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   With Wilson, it is difficult to know what the expectations are
anymore. Since undergoing surgery on his right shoulder on Nov. 12,
1996, the big right-hander has pitched in just five games, all last
season, and all in the low-level minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   This year, after being set back by shoulder and elbow stiffness,
Wilson has finally progressed to the point where he can throw
batting practice, which he was scheduled to do for Todd Hundley
again Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we still expect him to be at Class AAA this year,''
Duquette said. ``He'll do live batting practice one or two more
times, then pitch in a simulated game. If everything goes as
expected, he could be pitching in game situations in a couple more
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   As Duquette said, the Mets are being extremely cautious with the
former No. 1 pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still sometimes feels not abnormal pain, but some stiffness
in the elbow, which is why we're being real cautious. But we still
have two and a half months. I don't think it's unrealistic to
expect he'll be at Class AAA at some point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
