<HEADER>
A8775 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-CHEMISTRY     06-20 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-CHEMISTRY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS CONTEND THAT SUCCESS RESTS WITH `CHEMISTRY'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ John Wetteland is offered a pregame cup of
coffee by fellow reliever Al Levine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes please, thank you Al,'' he replies.
</P>
<P>
   Please? Thank you? In the same sentence?
</P>
<P>
   What's up? Is Wetteland an honors graduate of the Emily Post
School of Etiquette?
</P>
<P>
   Nah. It's just a part of that elusive quality that is commonly
known as chemistry. This isn't the kind of chemistry of elements
and periodic tables, or the kind of chemistry that results in
explosions when the wrong stuff is mixed together.
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of science that can have some influence on how
a sports team plays on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Chemistry was cited as a major ingredient when the Rangers won
the West in 1996. Some of those players are gone, notably
designated hitter Mickey Tettleton, center fielder Darryl Hamilton
and third baseman Dean Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   But the chemistry apparently remains with this team. And that
chemistry will be called upon as the Rangers try to battle back
into first after losing their division lead to the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different players, a different mix,'' shortstop Kevin
Elster said. ``It's like I love Mexican food, I love salsa. But you
can't find two that taste the same. It's a different mix, but it's
still good. That's like it is here. It's a different mix, but it's
the same kind of feeling we had a couple of years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Better winning through chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the going gets tough, that's what makes a team stay
together,'' Rangers infielder Luis Alicea said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think Baltimore has it?'' Elster asked. ``Do they have
talent?''
</P>
<P>
   According to Elster, the answers are no. And yes.
</P>
<P>
   And the Rangers? Yes and yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah,'' Elster said.
</P>
<P>
   Team chemistry is kind of like the wind. Few can explain what it
is, or where it comes from, but you know when it's there and can
sense when it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what team chemistry is,'' Elster said. ``I can't
put my finger on it, I can't explain it. You either have it or you
don't. It's that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Like H2O, which assumes the shape and color of what it's poured
into, chemistry takes on many forms.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, it's how well the players work together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like watching Ellie (Elster) and Mac (Mark McLemore) at
shortstop and second base,'' Wetteland said. ``There's not a verbal
definition, but if you watch Ellie and Mac at short and second
you'll understand what chemistry is.''
</P>
<P>
   Off the field, it's how well the players get along.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to a certain point on the field,'' first
baseman Will Clark said. ``It's more important off the field. It's
more important how you get along with everybody on an everyday
basis for eight months.''
</P>
<P>
   There's some debate about which aspect of team chemistry is the
most important.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees of the 1970s were perceived as a
dysfunctional team. They didn't need a chemist, they needed a
psychiatrist. The clubhouse was immortalized by reliever Sparky
Lyle as ``the Bronx Zoo.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Yankees went to the World Series in 1977 and '78.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 25 guys that maybe off the field didn't pursue it, but
when they went on the field they had it,'' said Rangers bench coach
Bucky Dent, the shortstop on those Yankee teams. ``It's having
confidence when you go out there that you know you're going to win.
The teams that I played on, it seemed like always in September it
was 2-1, 1-0. You could not afford to lose your concentration,
because at certain times it could cost you the pennant. There was
that responsibility of staying in the game and not messing up.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland played on two teams with that kind of chemistry _ the
1994 Montreal Expos that had the best record in baseball when the
players went on strike and the '96 Yankees that won the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chemistry was there because everybody was very focused on
whatever it takes to be better every day, and on whatever it takes
to win the game that day,'' he said. ``It wasn't that we all went
out together and ate together and all that jazz; it had more to do
with everybody knew that the person sitting next to them had
prepared in order to beat their opponent. That type of chemistry is
the important chemistry.''
</P>
<P>
   But also important is the chemistry of getting along well in the
clubhouse, of blending 25 players of different ages and from
different backgrounds and cultures in order to perform on the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good thing about this ballclub is everybody is well liked
and everybody gets along, on the field and off the field,'' left
fielder Rusty Greer said. ``You have 25 people put together for
seven months. You spend more time with these guys than you do your
own family. You learn to get along. That's a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't come naturally.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders such as Wetteland help make sure it happens. An example
is his complicated set of bullpen rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're everything from being impolite, and not saying thank
you and please, and not asking anyone if they'd like some water
before you get one, to a stupid question like what's the score when
you can look up at the scoreboard,'' Wetteland said. ``Yeah it's
silly, but there's a purpose to it all. When you take a head slap
for doing something stupid, the important thing is not that you got
punished. The important thing is that everybody gets a crack at
you, and everybody enjoys it. In the big picture it builds a
togetherness. After 162 games, guys have kept each other in every
ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   The rules even apply before the game. That's why, even though
the game still was a couple of hours away, Levine asked Wetteland
if he wanted a cup of coffee, and why Wetteland was so polite in
accepting.
</P>
<P>
   The rules are designed to keep each other focused. But they
wouldn't work if the players didn't get along.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise with Alicea's good-natured barbs directed at teammates
who mess up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams that win have fun out there,'' Alicea said. ``They go
out and relax and have fun and let their ability take over. You can
get the most out of guys by joking around and saying things to
encourage them to play. Guys don't take it personally, and it seems
to work. That's the chemistry that this team has. We can get on
each other a little bit, and it doesn't get personal. It's fun.''
</P>
<P>
   If the players didn't like each other, off the field it could
turn into resentment and animosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everybody's on the same page, you've got chemistry,''
center fielder Tom Goodwin said. ``If not, you've got dissension
and more than likely you're not going to win a lot of ballgames.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-98 1806EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
