<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS LOOK AT THE FOUR TOPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Mavericks seem to have a clear idea of how
Wednesday's NBA draft will transpire.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they could always get an intriguing late trade offer,
like the one last week from Milwaukee Bucks general manger Bob
Weinhauer, who was shopping former All-Star point guard Terrell
Brandon or one of two first-round picks for a move up the selection
ladder.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as with Chris Anstey last year, they could pull a foreign
player out of the hat like 6-foot-11 German ``wunderkid'' Dirk
Nowitzki.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't believe anything you hear and rule nothing out,''
Mavericks general manager Don Nelson said. ``But I really think
this thing is becoming pretty clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Barring an unexpected trade or meteoric rise from a surprise
prospect such as Michigan's Robert Traylor, the Mavericks have
targeted their Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   They are planning to select either Saint Louis guard Larry
Hughes, Kansas forward Raef LaFrentz or one of two North Carolina
teammates, forward Antawn Jamison and guard Vince Carter, with
their No. 6 pick. Nelson brought only those four players in for
private workouts and seems content to add one of them _ most likely
Carter or LaFrentz _ to a team that last season went 20-62 and
missed the playoffs for a league-high eighth consecutive time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be happy with any of those four,'' he said. ``And it
looks like we'll get to decide between two of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not bad.''
</P>
<P>
   In what is becoming a consensus scenario among NBA personnel
types, Arizona guard Mike Bibby, Pacific center Michael Olowokandi
and Kansas forward Paul Pierce are expected to go 1-2-3 in some
order. That leaves the Mavericks third in line for the four players
that round out the draft's top tier. Hughes is one of the draft's
fastest risers and Jamison is considered a top-five pick, possibly
leaving Dallas with a choice between the athletic-but-raw Carter
and the polished-but-soft LaFrentz.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks, who also have the 30th, 35th and 53rd picks,
enter the draft seeking a pace-pushing point guard and a bulky
backup center. But as for the four players who could slide to No.
6: &QL; 
VINCE CARTER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At 6-foot-7, 215 pounds and possessing an unmatched first step
and leaping ability, Carter was one of the nation's best finishers
as a junior last season. He averaged 15.6 points per game, but was
never forced to consistently knock down the open 15-footers he will
have to bury as an NBA shooting guard or small forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing on me was, can I hit a consistent jump shot?''
Carter said. ``That has become my main focus right now. Since we
lost to Utah (in the semifinals of the NCAA Tournament), I've been
back in the gym shooting the basketball, trying to get comfortable
again.''
</P>
<P>
   During workouts for Vancouver, Golden State, Denver and Dallas,
Carter impressed with his shooting form if not his results.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were going to make a film to teach youngsters how to
shoot, you'd use him as an example,'' Nuggets coach Dan Issel said.
``I would say it's real close between him and Pierce. He was that
impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Grizzlies player personnel director Larry Riley: ``When it
comes to running and jumping, Vince is probably the best in this
draft. If people were convinced that he could consistently make the
jump shot, they wouldn't be talking about four, five, six or seven,
they'd be talking about him at one, two or three.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Mavericks, Carter could play shooting guard, sliding
Michael Finley to small forward in case Nelson remains pessimistic
of re-signing free agent Cedric Ceballos. &QL; 
RAEF LaFRENTZ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 6-11, 235-pound senior is considered the best power-forward
prospect. A two-time first-team All-America selection and Big 12
player of the year, he has impressed scouts with his soft,
left-handed touch and array of low-post moves that led to 19.8
points and 11.4 rebounds last season.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't, however, considered strong enough _ or tough enough _
to immediately play center. That won't help his case with the
Mavericks, who already have ``soft'' centers in Shawn Bradley and
Chris Anstey.
</P>
<P>
   ``He runs the court, he scores, he rebounds and he blocks
shots,'' Boston Celtics general manager Chris Wallace said. ``But
he has to get stronger to meet the rigors of the NBA. His best
basketball won't come at center.''
</P>
<P>
   LaFrentz's stock has slipped recently, because scouts don't see
that something ``special'' in his game and they fear his potential
has already peaked. In addition, the Mavericks are already loaded
at power forward with Samaki Walker, Kurt Thomas and A.C. Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can play either position,'' LaFrentz said. ``I
played primarily with my back to the basket in college. I think
that is one area of my game that I can expand and become much
better. For a big man, I think that is one of my strengths to take
people out on the floor and be able to shoot it.'' &QL; 
ANTAWN JAMISON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At 6-9 and 223 pounds, Jamison was simply too quick for college
forwards and averaged 22.2 points and 10.5 rebounds as a junior at
North Carolina last season. With pogo-stick jumping ability and a
cat-quick release on his shots, he was the nation's consensus
player of the year last season, joining only Michael Jordan as the
only Tar Heel to accomplish the feat.
</P>
<P>
   While scouts rave about his aggressiveness, agility and knack
for being in the right place at the right time, they're confused as
to whether Jamison is a small forward or power forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tremendous competitor and very athletic,'' said Gary
Wortman, director of scouting for the Atlanta Hawks. ``He has a
knack of getting off shots and getting to the free-throw line. But
he's more of a three (small forward), not strong enough for four
(power forward) right now.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Mavericks, Jamison could utilize his athleticism in
Nelson's up-tempo style and allow Finley to play his more natural
shooting guard position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most guys see what I did at Carolina and think that's all I
got,'' Jamison said. ``I played mostly inside, and I didn't have to
go outside and shoot the jump shot. I was doing a great job of
playing the post and scoring. I think a lot of teams are uncertain
on whether I can shoot from the outside. I really see myself as a
three and sometimes I can play the four.'' &QL; 
LARRY HUGHES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks have long coveted the 19-year-old since watching
him average 20.9 points as a 6-5 freshman shooting guard at Saint
Louis last season. Though he averaged only 2.4 assists, took almost
17 shots per game and shot only 41 percent (29 percent on
3-pointers), scouts drool over his quick first step, ball-handling
skills, unlimited shooting range and ability to create his own shot
off the dribble.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the tools to be a tremendous weapon as his shooting
improves,'' Wallace said. ``All the traits you want are there _
size, quickness, two-way skills. He could be something special.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, who scored 30 points seven times last season, could
eventually become the fast-breaking point guard Nelson desires. In
light of Robert Pack's injury-riddled season, Hughes would seem a
perfect fit in Dallas. Nelson, however, realizes the secret is out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody sees in him what we see,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Golden State, picking No. 5, is also making no secret of its
infatuation with Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I fit in with anybody who likes to run, hit the open
court and finish,'' Hughes said. ``I'm an offensive player, but I
also enjoy shutting people down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
