<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday 6/20/98. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- June 20, 1998 -- NY-CENTENNIAL, 6-20 -- Penny
whistles and push carts helping to give Orchard Street between
Delancey and Broome Streets in Manhattan the look of an 1898
neighborhood. The street scene is part of the commemoration of the
consolidation of five boroughs into New York City. The actual
anniversary of the city's consolidation was on New Year's Day, but
organizers thought the summer's first weekend would provide a
natural opportunity to herald both history and summer weather.
(Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- June 20, 1998 -- CHINA-OPERA-STARS-2, 6-20 --
Lu Weizhi practicing a movement taught by Shi Jiehua, a Shanghai
opera star who now lives in New York. Chinese performers often have
to adjust to an austere life in the United States. Unlike many
artists from Western countries whose celebrity follows them here,
performers from China find themselves plunged into the austere
world of new Chinese immigrants, a world of menial jobs, Spartan
housing and little contact beyond the immigrant community. (Chang
W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- June 20, 1998 -- CHINA-OPERA-STARS-1, 6-20 --
Shi Jiehua, center, and her husband, Cai Qingling, left, with a
colleague, Chen Zhiping, in a video store in New York. Cai and Ms.
Shi, are both former members of Shanghai's celebrated Kunqu Theater
Troupe. For many Chinese, the sight of Shi Jiehua shelving
videotapes or Cai Qingling delivering takeout food is akin to the
notion of Luciano Pavarotti scrubbing pots at a pasta joint in
Little Italy. But virtually no Chinese opera star in this country
can survive on performing and teaching alone. (Chang W. Lee/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- June 20, 1998 -- BENNETT-BROTHERS, 6-20 --
Robert Bennett, left, and his younger brother, William, in 1948.
Today, Robert Bennett is President Clinton's personal lawyer, and
William Bennett is a conservative author of books such as ``The
Book of Virtues.'' Each brother says he respects the other's right
to make a living. The close but awfully complicated relationship
between these two prominent men, brothers who sometimes seem to
agree on little more than the appeal of a good steak, is a matter
of intense interest in Washington. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) PITTSBURGH -- June 20, 1998 -- PITTSBURGH-POLICE-2, 6-20
-- Linda Rosato-Barone, 40, is one of 14 commanders on the
Pittsburgh police force. Commander Barone and other women on the
Pittsburgh force say the skills women bring to the job add vital
components to policing. ``I think adding women to the force has
helped make the men more sensitive. They hate to hear that they are
becoming touchy-feely; they prefer the image of tough and strong. I
beg to differ,'' says Commander Barone, who joined the force in
1979. ``They're human beings like everyone else.'' (Terry Clark/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) PITTSBURGH -- June 20, 1998 -- SUB-PITTSBURGH-POLICE-1,
6-20 -- Comdr. Maurita Bryant, 45, talking with Sgt. James O'Brien,
runs a police district in Pittsburgh with the highest crime rate.
Commander Bryant joined the force, when ``the idea of having a
female supervisor was unheard of.'' Commander Bryant, who grew up
in a housing project and saw police officers as people to be
feared, concedes that old ways die hard among some officers. ``When
you have to discipline a male officer, with white guys you usually
see a level of red in their face, and with black guys, you see them
tense their jaw muscles. It's interesting to watch,'' she says.
(Terry Clark/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SPRINFILED, Pa. -- June 20, 1998 -- FINANCIAL-AID-EDUC,
6-20 -- James Doyle of Springfield, Pa., at home, has accepted an
offer to attend Princeton University, which changed its formula for
determining financial aid. Under the old formula, Princeton would
have been financially out of reach for his father, a retired
teacher. The once orderly world of financial aid, where colleges
avoided bidding against each other and standards of need were well
established, is unraveling, replaced by a more competitive
environment. (Sal Dimarco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) GAFFNEY, S.C. -- June 20, 1998 -- SUMMER-JOBS, 6-20 --
Sharai Correll, an 18-year old premed student, is working this
summer as a sales clerk at Fila, a shoe and sportswear retailer.
Ms. Correll is amazed at the leverage she and friends command this
year in the market for summer work. ``Five jobs in two days!'' she
exclaims. In many places around the country, tight job markets mean
youth unemployment is at its lowest point in a decade. (Nancy
Pierce/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
