<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: RESIDENTIAL ASSOCIATIONS GO ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Va., N.Y.)  (mk) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the pool at Hampton Commons in Hampton Township, N.J.,
opened last month, residents of the 300-unit condominium
association were reminded that only unit owners whose maintenance
charges were current would be admitted. Bathers in arrears, the
board noted, could be fined $25.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the Hamptons Common board tack up the announcement
on the bulletin board, but it also went a little further: It posted
a ``news flash'' on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web site is an extremely valuable tool for getting the
word out to our homeowners,'' said Thomas Gaines, secretary of the
condominium association. ``A lot of the people who live here
commute to somewhere else for work. That means there's not always a
lot of time or energy left for going to meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton Commons appears to be on the leading edge of a trend in
community relations _ providing residents with information and
interaction over the Internet as a supplement to the more
traditional ways of communicating with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A growing number of condominium, co-op and homeowner
associations are using the World Wide Web to communicate with
residents,'' said Donna Reichle, director of media relations for
the Community Associations Institute in Alexandria, Va., a trade
organization for co-ops and condominiums. ``And the homeowners are
really responding.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, Ms. Reichle said, her organization has maintained a
Web site that residents, board members and co-op and condominium
managers can turn to for up-to-the-minute information about
community living. The site, http://www.caionline.com, is a central
repository for publications, articles, ``how-to'' advice, court
rulings and real-life experiences of residents and board members
dealing with just about every conceivable aspect of co-op and
condominium ownership and management.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, boards are discovering that what the Community
Associations Institute Web site does for its members, individual
buildings can do on a smaller scale for their unit owners.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton Commons, for example, posts on its Web site the minutes
of every board meeting, reports prepared by committees and notices
that range from who may use the pool to when shrubs displaced by
sewer line work will be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the board also posts bylaws, rules and regulations
and other information relating to the finances of the association.
And, like most Web sites, the Hampton Commons site also provides
links to other Web sites like local schools, governmental agencies
and, of course, the Community Associations Institute which, in
turn, provides links to hundreds of other related sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've found that one of the biggest benefits for unit owners
is when the Web site is used as an online service desk,'' said Ms.
Reichle. ``Instead of having to get someone on the phone at the
management company, a resident who has access to a computer and the
Internet can send in an e-mail message any time of the day or
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Some co-ops and condominiums, Ms. Reichle said, post electronic
forms on their Web sites so that when residents want to apply, for
example, for permission to make repairs or alterations, they can
complete the forms online and file them electronically. Other
buildings, she said, use the Web site as a marketing tool for
potential purchasers _ posting pictures, financial reports and
other details about the building and its amenities. ``Buyers can
look at pictures of an apartment, check the financials and even get
a feel for the community without even leaving their desk,'' Ms.
Reichle said.
</P>
<P>
   While establishing a presence on the Internet is neither
technically difficult nor excessively costly, there are at least
two issues that must be addressed by any co-op or condominium board
contemplating such a project.
</P>
<P>
   The first is that not every unit-owner owns a computer or has
access to the Internet. And second, it takes more than just a
rudimentary understanding of computers to establish an internet
address, create a ``home page'' for the site, add content and links
to the site, and then keep that information up-to-date and
accurate.
</P>
<P>
   The first issue, it seems, is quickly taking care of itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``An estimated 28 million households have Internet access
today,'' said Ms. Reichle, adding that in addition to being able to
access the Internet from home computers, many individuals are able
to gain such access from computers at work, school and even from
public libraries.
</P>
<P>
   The second issue _ creation and maintenance of the site _ is
also becoming increasingly easy to address.
</P>
<P>
   At Hampton Commons, for example, a computer-savvy resident,
Bonnie Venable, volunteered her time and expertise to construct the
association's site and keep it current.
</P>
<P>
   And for co-ops and condominiums in New York, the Council of New
York Cooperatives recently began providing member buildings with
the ability to establish a professionally designed site at minimal
cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no longer a luxury to have a Web site,'' said Mary Ann
Rothman, executive director of the Manhattan-based co-op and
condominium organization. ``We have nearly 2,000 member
associations in New York City and its environs and this is our way
of helping our members make the transition into the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the council's Web site (http://www.cnyc.com) has had
nearly 16,000 ``hits,'' or visits by web surfers since it was
established about two years ago. In addition, she said, the council
has received an increasing number of requests from other Web sites
to share mutual links with those sites. As a result, she said, the
council last month established CNYCSites, a web site design and
maintenance service for member buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd Chrein, president of Chrein.com, the company that designed
the council's Internet site, said that buildings that sign up for
CNYCSites will have a site designed for them that will be linked
directly with the council's existing site.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to make the process as simple, painless and
inexpensive as possible,'' Chrein said, explaining that the basic
site design being offered to member buildings consists of two
``pages.'' Each page, he explained, can contain virtually any
information that can be stored and displayed on a computer.
</P>
<P>
   At present, Chrein said, the basic package being offered by
CNYCSites allows members to choose from three predesigned templates
into which individual buildings can insert whatever information
they choose.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, Chrein said, the first page _ the home page _
contains information about the building, pictures or illustrations,
and links to other Internet sites. The second page, he said,
usually contains a bulletin board for listings of meetings,
activities and events and for posting apartments for sale or
sublet.
</P>
<P>
   Additional pages can be added so that other information _
including building bylaws, proprietary leases and rules and
regulations _ can be instantly accessed by clicking on a link to
the desired page.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already gotten about 250 hits on the CNYCSites page,''
Chrein said. ``And we've sent out a few dozen application packages
to member buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   For members of the Council of New York Cooperatives, he said,
the one-time charge for designing a two-page site is $400. In
addition, Chrein said, member sites can be updated monthly for an
annual fee of $175. Additional information may be obtained by
calling CNYCSites at (212) 787-3462.
</P>
</TEXT>
