<HEADLINE>
JUST A TASTE: WHERE THERE'S SMOKE, THERE'S BARBECUE FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Did you know ...
</P>
<P>
   - Americans grill 2.3 times a week, according to the
grillmeisters at Weber. (Compare that with just three times a year
for the folks in the United Kingdom.)
</P>
<P>
   - Three out of four homes in the United States own a grill.
</P>
<P>
   - The most popular holiday weekend for grilling out is July
Fourth.
</P>
<P>
   - Most popular grilled foods: hamburger, steak, hot dogs and
chicken breast.
</P>
<P>
   - The Barbecue Industry Association found the most common
ingredient used to doctor up barbecue sauce is garlic, followed by
brown sugar.
</P>
<P>
   - Half of all marshmallows eaten in the United States have been
toasted over a barbecue grill.
</P>
<P>
   The association also includes this juicy morsel in a recent
press release: ``The Midwest is the barbecue hotbed _ if you can't
find a meat and sauce combination you like in Kansas City, you
can't find it anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, here.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of our town ...
</P>
<P>
   First it was Saveur magazine, and now the June issue of Food &AMP;
Wine magazine features a recipe for B.B's Lawnside Spicy Apple
Cider Barbecue Sauce. The article, written by cookbook author
Steven Raichlen, explores the four major styles of barbecue sauce:
Kansas City, Texas, North Carolina and Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   Not just for breakfast anymore ... Susan Moehl and Penni
Johnson, the proprietors of Southmoreland, a Mobil Four-Star
bed-and-breakfast on Kansas City's Country Club Plaza, are dishing
up a barbecue breakfast for their guests from May to October. The
women use a hand-laid limestone barbecue pit to whip up such
breakfast barbecue meats as pork chops or ribs to ham or sausage
kebabs. They also sear Texas toast on the grill.
</P>
<P>
   On the global grill ...
</P>
<P>
   Cooking teacher and cookbook author Steven Raichlen spent three
years traveling the globe exploring the wide world of barbecue
culture for his much anticipated Barbecue Bible (Workman).
</P>
<P>
   This month you can find Raichlen's Greek-inspired recipes for
Grill-Roasted Leg of Lamb with Lemon Butter, Greek-Style Garlic and
Lemon Roasted Potatoes and Swordfish Souvlaki on the Internet at
www.weberbbq.com.
</P>
<P>
   Heads up for Brazil ...
</P>
<P>
   I've noticed several trend trackers hailing Brazilian barbecue
(known in that country as churrasco) as the next hot food trend
coming down the pike. If a recent family vacation to Denver is any
indication, it's already starting to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Three Rodizio (pronounced ho-dee-zee-oh) restaurants are
thriving. On two nights I enjoyed the full-blown meal, a staggering
variety of meats from a skewer _ including picanha (a
Brazilian-style beef filet), lamb, fish and delectable nibbles of
bacon-wrapped turkey.
</P>
<P>
   A $15.95 per person price tag included gaucho-clad waiters and a
staggering self-serve salad bar with such exotic goodies as fresh
buffalo mozzarella, quail's eggs and feijoada, a black-bean stew.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-98 1859EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980620.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8808 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LILCO-SEVERANCE-57     06-20 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LILCO-SEVERANCE-575(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORDS SHOW LILCO PAYOUT WAS NO SECRET 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BRUCE LAMBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. _ When Gov. George Pataki angrily disclosed a
$42 million payment to the chairman of Long Island Lighting Co.
earlier this month, he denounced it as ``an extraordinary secret
act of greed.''
</P>
<P>
   The payment, he insisted, violated the state's agreement to take
over Lilco's electricity business.
</P>
<P>
   But formal documents show that state officials had known the
takeover would result in millions of dollars in benefits to Lilco
executives, even if the exact amount was not specified. The records
include Securities and Exchange Commission filings, Lilco's
takeover agreement, its agreement to merge with Brooklyn Union Gas
and correspondence from the Long Island Power Authority, the state
agency that negotiated the takeover.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has clouded the governor's triumph in revamping Long
Island's electricity service at long last and delivering a 20
percent cut in what, under Lilco, had been the highest bills in the
continental United States.
</P>
<P>
   The payouts, which also included $25 million to 25 other top
Lilco executives, bolstered the central argument of takeover
opponents, who contend that the $7 billion deal was a giveaway to
Lilco that burdens electricity customers with debt. The critics
charge that Pataki and his aides purposely ignored the compensation
issue for fear it would jeopardize the takeover.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did nothing, because to reveal what was taking place
would have blown the deal sky high,'' said Wayne Prospect, a
coordinator for an opposition group, the Initiative for Competitive
Energy. ``Their attempt at being outraged and shocked is totally
disingenuous.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has ordered the state attorney general and the Public
Service Commission to investigate the payouts and demanded that the
former Lilco chairman, Dr. William Catacosinos, return the money
and quit as chairman of Lilco's successor, Marketspan. The power
authority, which hired Marketspan to run the old Lilco system, is
withholding $1 million a month and imposing other penalties, and
the state Assembly has set a hearing on the matter for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki and his power authority chairman, Richard Kessel, insist
that the payouts were surreptitious and violated the takeover and
merger pacts. They contend that Lilco executives were not entitled
to severance payments because they all automatically got new jobs
at Marketspan and never lost a day's pay.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki and Kessel declined to comment directly about what the
documents disclosed about the compensation entitlements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact remains this was an extraordinary act of greed, and
Catacosinos should give it back and resign,'' reiterated the
governor's spokesman, Michael McKeon.
</P>
<P>
   Kessel said, ``The bottom line is LIPA's agreement prohibited
these payments, period, and in fact the Lilco board engaged in a
willful attempt to conceal this information from the power
authority and the state.''
</P>
<P>
   But the documents paint a different picture.
</P>
<P>
   As early as 1984, Lilco's corporate filings showed that
Catacosinos was building the framework for handsome retirement and
severance benefits. In 1994, during a Lilco takeover bid by Gov.
Mario Cuomo, the power authority's counsel, Richard P. Bonnifield,
wrote to Kessel about Catacosinos' ``golden parachute.'' That memo
said Lilco had set aside trusts to provide more than $10 million
``to fund his post-employment compensation.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On May 21, 1997, Kessel sent his agency's response to questions
about the most recent takeover plan from the chairman of the
Assembly Energy Committee, Paul Tonko. Addressing severance pay,
the letter said that Lilco officers had individual contracts
providing benefits if the company had ``a change of control.''
Those benefits included three years' salary, accelerated vesting of
supplemental retirement benefits and three years of life and health
insurance. The letter concluded, ``The transactions contemplated
with Brooklyn Union and/or LIPA will result in a change of control
as defined in the employment agreements.''
</P>
<P>
   In June 1997, the joint Lilco-Brooklyn Union proxy statement
said that the merger and takeover ``will each result in a change in
control'' of Lilco and thus ``entitle each officer to the benefits
payable under the terms of the employment agreements.''
</P>
<P>
   The registration statement that the companies filed with the
Securities and Exchange Commission that month said: ``The
transactions contemplated with Brooklyn Union and/or LIPA will
result in a change of control (as defined in these agreements) and
entitle each officer to the benefits payable under the terms of the
employment agreements.''
</P>
<P>
   The June 1997 merger agreement states Lilco's responsibility to
pay obligations ``relating to several change-of-control or similar
payments payable to executives of Lilco in connection with the
closing.'' Another section refers to the benefits to be paid ``as a
result of the termination of executive employment.''
</P>
<P>
   On March 25, 1998, opponents of the deal released Bonnifield's
1994 memo on the $10 million-plus golden parachute. In an interview
at that time, Kessel expressed no surprise about the memo. He did
not argue, as he does now, that such payments were prohibited, nor
did he indicate any plans to try to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   ``LIPA has nothing to do with this,'' Kessel said then.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen days later, in a Newsday report on the same issue, he
stressed that the power authority would never make such payments,
but he did not contest Lilco's right to do so. He was quoted
saying, ``The bottom line is, whatever compensation exists for
Lilco executives, the LIPA plan completely protects rate payers
from having to pay for it now or in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Kessel now says he does not recall why he did not take a
militant stance in March and April against the planned Lilco
payments.
</P>
<P>
   Marketspan's spokesman, Joseph McDonnell, a former Lilco
executive who received a payment, said: ``The employment contracts
were disclosed in Lilco's financial filings and its agreement with
LIPA. LIPA officials never expressed the view that anything in the
agreement prevented Lilco from making these payments, nor did it
seek to know the amount of the payments.''
</P>
<P>
   The critics have pounced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pataki and Kessel were asleep at the wheel,'' said Gordian
Raacke, director of a court-appointed Lilco watchdog group, the
Citizens Advisory Panel. ``They didn't do their due diligence. If
they claim they didn't know, they are incompetent to run our
electric system. The Catacosinos incident is only the first of a
series of abuses we can expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Shapiro, a lawyer for the New York Public Interest
Research Group, which filed suit against the takeover, said:
``While $67 million is a lot of money for normal people, it's not
even a drop in the bucket in terms of the overall $7 billion deal.
It's a drop in the ocean, and it's the entire ocean that Pataki
gave away.''
</P>
<P>
   Graef Crystal, a compensation analyst and critic of high
executive salaries, has studied documents in the case and
concluded, ``In our view, the governor had every reason to know
that these payments would be made.''
</P>
</TEXT>
