<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8813 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NORLEANS-COX     06-20 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORLEANS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Americanization of New Orleans
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS -- It seemed like an odd attachment.
</P>
<P>
   To an outsider, the K&AMP;B drugstores here were nothing but boxy
buildings with funny purple signs _ a bit of an eyesore next to the
mansions along St. Charles Avenue. But natives loved them, and when
the Pennsylvania-based national chain Rite Aid bought them out,
many vowed they would never shop there again.
</P>
<P>
   K&AMP;B operated in New Orleans for more than 90 years, and the
color of the chain's logo _ not quite violet, not quite lavender _
had entered the local vocabulary as ``K&AMP;B purple.'' They sold
things not usually found at the corner drugstore, such as bourbon
and vodka in plastic bottles with purple labels, and ice cream in
flavors such as cream cheese and eggnog.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Rite Aid, surprised by this fierce brand loyalty,
removed their peppy ``Your drugstore just got better'' banners and
slowed the process of replacing the K&AMP;B logo with their more
generic red, white and blue one. And just to show there are no hard
feelings, the Rite Aid folks held a charity auction of K&AMP;B
memorabilia _ purple shopping baskets, playing cards, and clerk
smocks. Die-hard K&AMP;B fans arrived before dawn; by noon, more than
1,000 people had shown up.
</P>
<P>
   Why all the fuss over a dying drugstore chain? Because a battle
for the soul of New Orleans is being waged, and, for the moment,
the outsiders are winning.
</P>
<P>
   At least a dozen locally owned institutions have sold out or
closed in the past three years, and national chains, once
conspicuously absent here, are arriving in droves. The likes of the
House of Blues, Pottery Barn and Starbucks _ opening this summer _
are making the city feel more ... American. To many in this
aggressively untrendy town, Americanization represents a fate worse
than hurricanes, heat waves and bad oysters.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Orleans has an incredibly unique history, and nothing can
ever take that away,'' said Dannal Perry, a museum educator with
two historic houses in the French Quarter who stocked up on K&AMP;B
purple merchandise before Rite Aid took over. ``But if we don't
take care of our local businesses, we'll be Cleveland. Why would
anyone want to come here if we lose our unique personality?''
</P>
<P>
   The fear is not unfounded. Consider:
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the House of Blues, a slick, no-expenses-spared
nightclub chain owned, in part, by Dan Aykroyd, opened in the
French Quarter. The club immediately stole big local acts such as
the Neville Brothers from the considerably less glitzy local icon
Tipitina's. The old club almost closed.
</P>
<P>
   Krauss Co., a homegrown department store in an ornate historic
building on Canal Street, closed in 1997 after 90 years.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Maison Blanche, another local department store on Canal
Street, announced it had been sold to Dillard's Inc. The Arkansas
chain probably will close the downtown store and rename the ones in
the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Starbucks, the ubiquitous Seattle coffeehouse
chain, will open in Uptown, a tony, residential area near Audubon
Park served by locally owned coffeehouses with strong followings.
Some are wondering whether Starbucks will go head to head in the
French Quarter with the famous Cafe Du Monde, home of chicory
coffee and sugary beignets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The phenomenon of national companies replacing mom-and-pop
stores has been going on for years in most cities, but New Orleans
has resisted this,'' said Tim Ryan, dean of the College of Business
at the University of New Orleans. For example, Louisiana was the
last state in the nation that had no interstate banks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We revel in our uniqueness; we're proud of our local
institutions,'' Ryan said. ``Krauss existed for years after it (no
longer) was economically viable. It's amazing it didn't go out of
business 10 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Although proud provincialism has played a role in keeping the
national chains at bay, pure economics are involved as well. After
the oil bust of the late 1970s and early 1980s, national companies
were afraid to set up shop in New Orleans. Now that the city is
enjoying a rebound, it seems as good a place as any to do business.
</P>
<P>
   The economy may have improved, but the provincialism remains.
There was even a Mardi Gras parade devoted to the battle over the
heart and soul of New Orleans, called ``Souled Down the River.''
Revelers dressed as zombies in K&AMP;B clerk uniforms, and held signs
that said, ``Your drugstore just got worse.'' A float called the
Old Absent House mourned the closing of one of the oldest bars in
the French Quarter, the Old Absinthe House. The marchers ended the
night with a party in the now-vacant Krauss building.
</P>
<P>
   People are very curious to see how Starbucks affects business at
CC's Gourmet Coffee House, Rue de la Course, and PJ's Coffee and
Tea Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a formidable foe, and I take that very seriously,''
said Phyllis Jordan, owner of PJ's. ``A lot of people say, `Oh, you
have nothing to worry about; people here are so provincial, they
won't go with a national chain.' I'm not so sure. It's up to us to
meet the competition and serve our customers better.''
</P>
<P>
   To do that, PJ's plans to emphasize its uniquely New Orleans
spirit with one-on-one service and a slower pace.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan argues that some local businesses have improved, thanks
to new competition. Tipitina's, which almost closed when the House
of Blues came to town, is thriving again by concentrating on
lesser-known, locally popular bands. They've even opened a second
location.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone agrees that competition helps.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Rochester, owner of the Funky Butt, a jazz club on the
edge of the French Quarter, said he thinks Tipitina's has ``gone
corporate'' and lost its authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these places moving in make me very, very nervous,'' he
said. ``Places like the House of Blues and Storyville (another
glitzy jazz club set to open on Bourbon Street) are so huge and
have so much money, it's going to have a major effect on a little
struggling place like the Funky Butt. They're just creating
atmosphere, whereas we have it naturally.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Terrence Fitzmorris, director of the Center
for the Study of New Orleans and the Mississippi River at Tulane
University, said he thinks people are overreacting.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Orleans is indeed an American city. It's just that our
understanding of what it is to be an American city has changed in
the last 50 years,'' he said. ``Atlanta is now considered an
American city, and New Orleans is not because it has held on to
much of its ethnicity and showcases its heritage. But New Orleans
reinvents itself just like any other city. I don't think Rite Aid
replacing K&AMP;B takes the heart out of New Orleans.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he said, some of the outsiders were invited in. State
and local leaders OK'd plans for a huge, land-based casino near the
French Quarter. After a two-year battle, Harrah's Jazz Co., which
went bankrupt operating a temporary casino while building a
permanent one, has been given the go-ahead to finish construction
on the new casino and open for business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Rite Aid any worse than placing a monstrosity in the middle
of Canal Street?'' Fitzmorris said. ``Because New Orleans has an
exotic history of being French and Spanish, people assume it will
act in an exotic fashion. But New Orleans fits the American mold.
It just has added layers.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
