<HEADER>
A8814 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PBP-FIRES21-COX     06-20 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PBP-FIRES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Firefighters clean up after the fire
 &HT;    By Scott McCabe
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE _ Mop-up duty doesn't lead to firefighting glory,
but someone has to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Kinkaid was chomping at the chance.
</P>
<P>
   Mop up means bulldozing street-wide paths through dense forest
to separate the charred land from the green, hosing down dry edges
and extinguishing sudden flares.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the glamour work, but I don't want to lose this
thing,'' Kinkaid said of the subdued fire that earlier this week
burned more than 300 square acres at Brannan Field Park, south of
Interstate 10 and just east of the Naval Air Station at
Jacksonville. ``We worked too hard to contain it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kinkaid, a state forest firefighter, was joined Friday by five
firefighters from South Florida who pulled into their hotels at 2
a.m yesterday morning.
</P>
<P>
   All told, 12 firefighters from South Florida _ three from Palm
Beach County _ have traveled north to help battle the raging brush
fires. They join crews from other states that are are monitoring
more than 7,000 square acres here.
</P>
<P>
   Three volunteers from the Martin County Red Cross left Friday
for Northeast Florida to help feed fire victims.
</P>
<P>
   South Florida firefighters awoke at 5 a.m. Friday to begin
mop-up duty.
</P>
<P>
   The team split into day and night shifts. The first hooked up
around noon with crews from as far away as South Carolina and
Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Despite temperatures striking 103 Friday, a record high for
Jacksonville, firefighters spent the day preventing rather than
putting out flames. Thanks to little wind, the few fires that
popped up were quickly checked, and no new fires began.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Brad Havrilla of Palm Beach County spent most of the day
fighting through forest to water down smoldering pine. He
concentrated on the perimeter of a 12-acre area that caught fire
two days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out here, there are more things to anticipate,'' he said. ``If
things start coming on you, you might have to just run while in a
structure fire you might be able to bunker down.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday morning, Jacksonville firefighters warned the men
about an unexpected danger if the area had to be evacuted:
Uncooperative homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   A man whose Alachua home was in the path of a wildfire Wednesday
wouldn't leave. He had greeted firefighters with an M-16, according
to a firefighter who talked the man into letting his wife leave the
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's the case, get out of there,'' District Chief R.E.
Garmon of Jacksonville told the men Friday morning. ``Let it
burn.''
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters kept that home and othes safe. No arrests were
made.
</P>
<P>
   No evacuations were ordered Friday in Duvall County, where the
crew of South Florida firefighters is expected to remain until
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But until a good rain comes, crews will work around the clock
preparing for the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we don't have rain, whether it's for days or for
months, the smoke will continue to burn,'' Kinkaid said, pointing
to small flames erupting from the ashes. ``That's why we have to do
the dirty work and stay on top of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
