<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News service for Sunday, June 21. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
QUEST _ The death of Professor Jonathon William Faulkner was
accompanied by a curious inheritance left to his students: $1
million for the one who could solve a mystery hidden in his 10-room
mansion. With that fictional premise, a Scottsdale company lured
thousands of computer sleuths into buying a $50 game _ and
competing in an arduous contest that promised $1 million to the
real-life winner. But, two years later, Sirius Publishing Inc. has
transformed its software conundrum into a mystery by refusing to
fully identify the winner. By DENNIS WAGNER. Story will move in the
``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BULLET _ Lynn Andrews was 14 last summer when he was shot in his
throwing arm by a 14-year-old girl. She was angry, Lynn says,
because he would not loan her a rap CD. Like most other shootings
in Arizona in 1997, the attack didn't even make the news. But the
shot from the .44 Magnum changed the lives of Lynn and nearly
everyone around him, showing just how devastating one bullet can
be. By KARINA BLAND. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
VICTIM _ C. Hermanex is a Chandler, Ariz., resident who originally
wrote of her experiences as a victim of domestic violence for her
church newsletter. This is an edited version of the account
Hermanex agreed to share with Republic readers: It could happen to
someone you know. It happened to me. Government statistics say
domestic violence is undereported by 10 to 1. Having experienced
over 40 physical assaults, with only four resulting in arrest and
conviction of the batterer, I guess I fit the statistic. But I am
not a statistic. I am a woman, with a name, a life, a family. Story
will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Phoenix) _ On occasion, Rev. Jack Spaulding of St.
Thomas the Apostle Catholic Church has delivered messages during
prayer services in a monotone voice, in the first person, as if
Jesus or Mary were speaking directly through him. A parishoner from
St. Thomas mentioned this to me recently, adding, ``I wonder if it
was the Lord who told Father Jack to throw the nuns out of their
convent.'' By E.J.MONTINI. Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K''
categories. &QL;
