<HEADLINE>
IT'S POLITICALLY INCORRECT, BUT LET'S HEAR IT FOR `TEAM SATAN!'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the night of Feb. 22, 1980, millions of unsuspecting
Americans were transformed into hockey fans.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them didn't know a blue line from a stretch mark. They
didn't know if Mike Eruzione was the team captain or the kid who
delivered the pizza.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, when a team of overachieving U.S. college kids upset the
mighty Soviet Union in the Olympics semifinals in Lake Placid,
N.Y., people across America cheered and hugged one another with
pride. Hockey had a golden page to add to its memory book.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, today in Lyon, France, the World Cup soccer match between
the United States and Iran will kindle interest, but it lacks the
relative drama of that night in Lake Placid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just concerned with getting the three points'' for
winning, American Ernie Stewart said, echoing the U.S. team's
weekend theme.
</P>
<P>
   From a Biblical standpoint _ certainly, from this corner of the
globe _ the match is not like David and Goliath. It's more like
cold-shouldered Cains and Abels.
</P>
<P>
   From a World Cup standpoint, they make odd bedfellows, paired on
a political rostrum called Group F.
</P>
<P>
   These players were about 10 years old _ most of them _ in 1979
when Iranian militants stormed the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took
52 hostages. The Embassy is now a police training center, and on
its brick walls outside, the spray-painted message, ``Death to
America,'' is said to be faded and hard to read.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, to ask this team of U.S. soccer players, who fight a daily
battle for recognition on their own, to shoulder the country's
political pride seems grossly unkind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I haven't talked to Bill lately,'' U.S. midfielder Tab
Ramos told reporters in France. ``Does Bill Clinton know we're
playing Iran?''
</P>
<P>
   Ramos' sarcasm is more than called for, of course.
</P>
<P>
   The president's videotaped message set for today, in which he
says he hopes the match can be ``another step toward ending the
estrangement between our nations,'' is the sporting equivalent of a
guy who runs up in the airport and says, ``Here _ deliver this
package.''
</P>
<P>
   Gee, thanks. Can we sell you some D.C. United tickets?
</P>
<P>
   The greater prize remains a place in the World Cup's second
round. The U.S. strikers look labored enough without the extra
baggage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to make this a political game,'' U.S. coach Steve
Sampson told the news media after practice Friday. ``At some point,
we're just going to have to put the other stuff aside.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be no banners, Lyon's gendarmes have decreed.
Security has been stepped up around town. Effigies of Jimmy Carter,
we also assume, will not be gassed and burned.
</P>
<P>
   The coach of the Iran team _ gasp _ even lives in California. He
said he plans a ``surprise'' gesture of good will for the
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   I know _ two tickets to Six Flags Over Tehran.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it's a joke. We're trying our best to deal with this.
</P>
<P>
   If the Olympics has taught us anything in 2,000 years, it's that
sports and politics have always been intermingled. Jesse Owens and
Hitler in Berlin. The bloody Hungary and Soviet Union water polo
match in Melbourne. The boycott in Moscow, and again in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In a perfect world, the only storyline today would be whether
Stewart or surfer-dude teammate Frankie Hejduk can muster scoring
chances against Iran's Ahmad Reza Abedzadeh.
</P>
<P>
   But we know better. In Tehran, they're praying for an Iran
victory. Defeating the United States, the nation that Iranians
openly call ``The Great Satan,'' will launch a national holiday, if
not holy day.
</P>
<P>
   Although the newly elected leader of Iran, the Mohammad Khatami,
talked about the match being ``a prelude to a new path,'' hardline
newspapers in Tehran reiterated their stands against ``injustices
perpetrated by World Arrogance.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be us, neighbors. Arrogance United, in the Tehran box
scores.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, though, most Americans don't get it. Most Americans
wouldn't recognize the World Cup trophy if UPS left it on their
doorsteps.
</P>
<P>
   There is refreshing naivete, therefore, when U.S. goalkeeper
Kasey Keller said, ``It's nice to get some recognition from the
government. We understand there's a lot of pride at stake in this
game.''
</P>
<P>
   The greater good, Keller knows, is the baggage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it brings more fans to the TV and more exposure to the
sport of soccer, that will be great,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of Americans will be watching today. To them, Team
Satan has a score to settle.
</P>
<P>
   It might be boorish. It might be immensely politically
incorrect. But for U.S. soccer, it's a captive audience. And
there's no 10-run rule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-98 1927EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
