r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-BURN-TEX     06-20 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-BURN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURN SEEKS REDEMPTION VS. MUTINY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By TROY PHILLIPS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With most soccer eyes on the World Cup, the Dallas Burn quietly
has been trying to revive its pedestrian Major League Soccer
season.
</P>
<P>
   A rematch with Tampa Bay at the Cotton Bowl tonight offers the
Burn a chance to prove it can win when expected. The game will also
give the Burn an opportunity to avenge an earlier loss to the
Mutiny, and a victory would allow Dallas to start closing the gap
in the MLS' Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Burn is 10 points behind second-place Chicago (10-5, 28
points) and well in back of conference leader Los Angeles (12-2, 37
points).
</P>
<P>
   Two goals by U.S. national teamer Frankie Hejduk helped the
Mutiny (3-12) defeat Dallas, 3-1, on April 11. John Kowalski has
since resigned as Tampa Bay's coach, and Hejduk is starting for
Team USA against Iran in today's World Cup match.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas (8-6) has its own problems and could have up to six
players miss today's match. Alain Sutter, Eric Dade, Jorge Flores,
Richard Farrer and Gerell Elliot could be sidelined by injuries,
and Leonel Alvarez will not play because of an accumulation of
yellow cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy when you don't know who's going to be there each
week,'' forward Dante Washington said. ``You can't blame that,
because we have a bunch of guys capable of starting. But
chemistry-wise, different players bring different things to the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   The Burn's last home game marked the league's most lopsided
match ever, an 8-1 loss to Los Angeles. Disappointing road games at
D.C. United and Chicago followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The D.C. game was tough, in that we were winning late,'' said
Washington, referring to the Burn's 5-4 shootout victory after
leading 4-3 in the final two minutes. ``It was a great outcome,
considering we were coming off the 8-1 loss. The most important
thing was how we reacted to that loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago defeated Dallas on a penalty kick after saving 10 Burn
shots. Dallas also had 11 corner kicks, but the expansion Fire won
its eighth consecutive game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight games in a row, I guess you take it when you can get
it,'' Washington said. ``We were all over them, and they got a gift
of a penalty kick. From the way we dominated them, I don't think
we're in that bad of sorts.''
</P>
<P>
   In two-plus seasons, the Burn has strung together no better than
a five-game winning streak, once last season and in 1996. This
year, Dallas started 3-0 but has yet to match that streak.
</P>
<P>
   The Burn has been unable to project any fear factor like that
associated with Los Angeles or D.C. United, Washington said. In
1996, LA started 12-0 and began 9-0 this season. Two-time MLS
champion D.C. has consecutive 13-4 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does a lot for you mentally to get on a streak,''
Washington said. ``You feel invincible. We haven't been able to get
that snowball rolling to where other teams are afraid of us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-98 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
