<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8837 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOODWARD-ELTON-BOS &LR;      06-20 1409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODWARD-ELTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODWARD WILL GET PRIVACY _ FOR A WHILE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOREEN IUDICA VIGUE AND RIC KAHN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELTON, England _ As the army of journalists and fleet of
satellite trucks withdraw for now from this quiet village, Louise
Woodward will soon make her way to the local pub and market without
the world watching.
</P>
<P>
   But even those who campaigned to bring home the town's most
infamous daughter admitted that they could never again see her in
the same way, that just below the surface of daily routine and
pleasantries will exist a longing for answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things will be back to normal, but there is always talk and
there will be stares,'' said Marion Barlow, stocking the shelves of
her packed hardware store in the town center Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all want to treat her and the family like normal people,
although we all want to ask questions. She won't ever really have
her own life now.''
</P>
<P>
   The young woman who dreamed of becoming an actress is destined
for a life less ordinary, some specialists say. Made famous by a
trial observed around the globe and forever tainted by her
manslaughter conviction in the death of Matthew Eappen, an infant,
Woodward now walks the same path as others who became known for
their misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once a person has a label put on them _ such as `the nanny
killer' _ it's very difficult for people's perceptions to change,''
said Northeastern University's Jane Bybee, an assistant professor
of psychology who has written about shame and shunning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if she's exonerated, people will still call her, `the
suspected nanny killer,''' said Bybee. ``The label will follow her
to the end of her day.''
</P>
<P>
   Bybee compared Woodward to celebrity athlete O.J. Simpson,
accused and acquitted of murdering his wife and her friend.
Afterward, Simpson was dumped by his girlfriend, heckled on the
golf course, and snubbed by neighbors. Shutterbugs waited at every
corner, and he contemplated fleeing the country.
</P>
<P>
   While channel-surfing at home last fall, Simpson called Court TV
during its broadcast of Woodward's trial. The fallen football
legend wanted to express his support for the frightened British au
pair _ one outcast to another.
</P>
<P>
   As a convicted felon in a baby's death, Woodward should not
expect that those among the throngs which rallied for her during
the trial will welcome her with open arms if she tries to get close
to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is she going to have a life after this?'' Bybee asked. ``O.J.
is the walking dead. He's still ostracized.
</P>
<P>
   ``People use different standards when considering whether
(Woodward) should be convicted in a court of law than being friends
with somebody and accepting them socially,'' Bybee said. ``Would
you want your children babysat by her or your brother to marry
her?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Like Woodward, Cheryl Amirault LeFave had been just another
ordinary person leading an unobserved life. Then, she, her mother,
Violet Amirault, and her brother, Gerald ``Tooky'' Amirault, were
branded child molesters during the mid-1980s, charged with abusing
children at their Malden day care center.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Her 14-year ordeal then became a roller-coaster ride of
headline-grabbing trials, convictions, and a series of appeals.
Earlier this month, a Superior Court judge overturned LeFave's
conviction, finding that the testimony of child witnesses had been
tainted by faulty interviewing. The state has appealed; if
prosecutors win, she returns to prison.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  LeFave said she lost a lot: eight years of her life in a
prison cell, her mother to cancer, her married life to stress _ and
her good name. She has never fully recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Though she's technically an innocent woman and has been free for
nearly three years, LeFave said she sometimes lies awake all night,
her nerves worn raw by the experience. She said Woodward may have
the same anxieties.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``If it's an unjust conviction'' as Woodward
contends, &UR;  &LR; ``there's never going to be a moment where she's at
peace,'' said LeFave. ``It's a constant haunt ... It's the scarlet
letter.''
</P>
<P>
   LeFave, 40, has said she lives a closeted existence, rarely
leaving her Ashmont apartment, fearful of being recognized.  &UR;  &LR; At a
recent Elton John concert, she realized the joy had been torn from
her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried the entire night,'' she said. ``To think I watched all
those people tap their feet and clap their hands and I have been
stripped of that for the rest of my life ... The drum doesn't beat
in me anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodward says she wants to attend college and then get a job.
LeFave said she'd been there, too. She had a steady job as an
airline reservations clerk two years ago _ until a supervisor saw
her on the 6 o'clock news. LeFave was immediately escorted from the
premises.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always become a prisoner of people's perceptions,'' said
LeFave, who is awaiting word on whether the Supreme Judicial Court
will take back her freedom. ``She's going to feel the stares, the
doubts in people's faces. It's crippling. There's not a moment when
you're carefree.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Then again, some say that like a fading athlete grown addicted
to glory, Woodward &UR;  &LR; may miss the constant media attention: cameras
flashing and reporters jostling to get closer to her.
</P>
<P>
   British journalists said last week that although they will soon
leave town, they will return to document Woodward's most personal
milestones: her start in college, her first job, her love
relationships _ and, especially, the birth of a first child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether she likes it or not, she is a famous person,'' said
Martin Dillon, a journalist with the Liverpool Echo, a tabloid
daily. ``The media chase will die down somewhat, but once she gets
a boyfriend, once she gets married and has a baby, the press will
be back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conviction will hang over her forever and will follow her
at each milestone in her life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, minutes after she left Marblehead for Logan Airport
and the flight home to Elton, media trucks and journalists
descended on the English town. Some villagers complained, and
others even crossed the street to avoid reporters. But Barlow noted
that &UR;  &LR; still others have come to realize how vital publicity has
been a help to Woodward, at least financially.
</P>
<P>
   ``She got more support from everywhere because of the publicity
and the cameras in court,'' said Barlow. ``Without it, I am sure
the family would have had to sell their house. The publicity
allowed them to pay for the best defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Left alone, Woodward will probably suffer internal conflicts
between her belief that she's innocent and her court conviction,
British psychologists say.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Sidney Crown, a London psychotherapist, believes the
Woodward family should undergo counseling as Louise tries to regain
her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she becomes Saturday's news _ and that's going to happen
very rapidly _ she's then going to suddenly realize that she's not
famous anymore, she's not notorious, and she's just her.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodward's challenge to adjust will be complicated by the fickle
press, said Dr. Richard Howells, a communications instructor at the
University of Leeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, we were struck by her innocence in the whole
thing and now she doesn't look so innocent,'' Howells said. He
believes Woodward is a victim of the media tendency to ``build
celebrities up and then shoot them down.''
</P>
<P>
   In November, when Judge Hiller Zobel reduced Woodward's
second-degree murder conviction to manslaughter and sentenced her
to the 279 days she had already served, the village of Elton
toasted Woodward with champagne, hailing her as a folk hero who'd
survived rough treatment in a foreign land.
</P>
<P>
   But as she finally arrived here last week _ traveling like
royalty despite unresolved allegations that her family misused her
defense fund _ public opinion on British soil had already shifted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``First Class Child Killer,'' screamed the front page of the
tabloid The Mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Howell said Woodward's upcoming interview with the BBC's Martin
Bashir may swing the public pendulum back to Woodward, if all goes
well &UR;  &LR; _ and, experts added, as long as she doesn't get paid for her
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've grown up an awful lot,'' Woodward said to the world press
on Thursday. ``I hope it changed me for the better, but only time
will tell.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jordana Hart of the Globe staff and Globe correspodent Peggy
Hernandez helped prepare this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
