<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8839 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-CHANGE-BOS &LR;      06-20 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CHANGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG BIRD'S ARRIVAL ONLY ONE EXAMPLE OF CHINA'S CHANGES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill Clinton, get ready to meet Da Niao.
</P>
<P>
   Da Niao, as millions of children in China know, is Big Bird's
cousin. In a modern Shanghai television studio, ``Sesame Street''
has just finished producing 130 half-hour shows in Mandarin. The
show will soon be syndicated across China, sponsored by General
Electric.
</P>
<P>
   This is not your father's Red China. In fact, the country that
President Clinton will see this week barely resembles the country
that hosted George Bush for the last American presidential visit
nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Bush visit, China has developed commodities markets
and stock exchanges. Satellite dishes are everywhere. So are
personal agendas, personal computers, personal trainers, and almost
anything that stresses individual, not communal, growth.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky Fried Chicken _ KFC, that is _ is a popular lunch
joint. Chinese cities have private clubs, night clubs, strip clubs,
and book clubs, but the books are all about amassing capital, not
honoring Chairman Mao's dictums.
</P>
<P>
   In China, the ultimate sign of status may be a Bloomberg
terminal, spewing out streams of data about the world markets 24
hours a day. A new book, ``Big Dragon: China's Future _ What it
Means for Business, the Economy and the Global Order,'' says that a
fast-selling magazine, Strategy and Management, aims to be China's
equivalent of the Harvard Business Review. That's not surprising,
except that some of the magazine's investors apparently are
associated with the People's Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush saw China, most of the population had been shaped by
Mao, who had died 13 years earlier. But today's Chinese have
distant memories, if any at all, of Mao and the Cultural
Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Burstein, an investment banker from Weston, Conn., and
co-author of ``Big Dragon,'' recently visited a family in Shanghai
for dinner. When he asked the 16-year-old daughter about her
ambitions, she responded ``Stanford,'' the university she hopes to
attend.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few years ago, that conversation would have been
unimaginable. Instead, as Burstein puts it, a teenage girl would
have said, ``My goal is to integrate with the workers, soldiers,
and peasants and build the revolutionary China.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Dragon'' itself is an example of the change. Next month it
will be published in China, after a bidding war among several
Chinese publishers. The book calls for good relations between
Washington and Beijing, but it does include a few criticisms of
China's leaders. In the 1980s, such a work would have been banned
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   No, this isn't Communist China. But what is it?
</P>
<P>
   Burstein calls the system ``market socialism'' or ``state
capitalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake: President Jiang Zemin, the army, and security
services ensure that the newfound freedoms go only so far.
</P>
<P>
   While China has loosened some restrictions on speech, there is
strong evidence that the ``re-education through labor'' camps are
expanding.
</P>
<P>
   And to prepare for Clinton's nine-day, five-city visit, China
has conducted extensive sweeps of dissidents, jailing some,
threatening many, and shipping others far away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been all too common for them to send people on vacation
before a visit by a president or American officials,'' said Stanley
Roth, the State Department's top Asia expert.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Roth insists that economic openings in China are leading
to some political openings. China blocks dozens of sites on the
Web, but plenty of information from exiles still comes through.
There are fledgling environmental groups. China holds relatively
free local elections.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Big Bird's gangly cousin. Five years ago, the
producers of ``Sesame Street'' went to China _ home to 200 million
children _ for exploratory talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had this feeling that everything would be very closed, but
that lasted about 30 seconds,'' said David Jacobs, a vice president
of Children's Television Workshop in New York.
</P>
<P>
   During those meetings, Jacobs said, Chinese television
executives and educators quickly launched into frank discussions
about what they liked and disliked about their society. ``Sesame
Street,'' called ``Zhima Jie,'' was soon up and taping.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese had a few special requests. They wanted to give
preschoolers an early appreciation of Chinese opera and art. And
because China's one-child policy has created a country full of sons
and daughters who are often spoiled, Big Bird's cousin and several
newly minted Muppet characters put extra emphasis on learning to
share.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone agreed that ``Zhima Jie'' should emphasize education
and avoid becoming too commercial. Nevertheless, commercials will
be shown before and after the show when it airs across the country.
</P>
<P>
   And because this is the new, consumer-driven China, store
shelves will soon offer books, videos, and toys featuring the
6-foot-tall yellow bird and his Mandarin-speaking pals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-98 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980620.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8840 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-MEXICO-H     06-20 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD </SLUG>
 CUP-MEXICO-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Mexico gladly accepts draw after trailing Belgium 2-0
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BORDEAUX, France _ Most of the time, ending a game with a tie is
like kissing your sister.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, it was like kissing the sky.
</P>
<P>
   This time, after one of the more remarkable comebacks of the
World Cup thus far and a tying goal that was nothing if not
spectacular, it was like the entire Mexican team ascending the
Azteca pyramids, sweaty and exhausted, and thanking the heavens for
a divine effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where there is hope, there is a chance,'' said Mexican forward
Cuahtemoc Blanco, whose diving, awkward 63rd-minute chip-in
provided the 2-2 tie with Belgium. ``Even if hope looks like it is
lost.''
</P>
<P>
   All hope definitely seemed gone for Mexico at steamy-hot Stade
Lescure on Saturday. Belgium stormed to a 2-0 lead, the Mexicans
were playing a man short because of a questionable red card and
every legitimate Mexican opportunity was being kicked away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked dead,'' Mexico's Claudio Suarez said.
</P>
<P>
   But the heat kept rising. The vocal Mexican fans kept yelling _
``Mexico, Mexico, rah-rah-rah.''
</P>
<P>
   And Mexico's attacking game ultimately took over, with a
well-earned penalty kick by Alberto Garcia-Aspe and Blanco's
highlight-reel goal setting off another wild celebration by Mexican
fans.
</P>
<P>
   The tie clouded Mexico's hopes of advancing out of the tough
Group E, which includes the favored Dutch, who defeated Korea on
Saturday. A win would have assured a trip to the single-elimination
second round.
</P>
<P>
   Now tied with the Dutch with four points, while Belgium has two
(with a pair of ties) and South Korea none, Mexico must earn at
least a tie with the Dutch in order to keep its chances of
advancing since Belgium likely will beat South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   But considering how things began Saturday
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy,'' Mexican coach Manuel Lapuente said. ``It was
very difficult for us today from the beginning. We were playing
very well, but getting the red card I thought it would be
impossible to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   The red card came against Mexico defender Pavel Pardo in the
29th minute, and by most accounts it was a questionable
interpretation of the back-tackle rule, which FIFA president Sepp
Blatter ruled should be an automatic red card and disqualification
from the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was called,'' Pardo said. ``I don't know how right it was,
but it was called.''
</P>
<P>
   The call clearly devastated Mexico. Only minutes later Belgium's
Marc Wilmots put his team ahead with an easy boot into the back of
the net off a corner kick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were forced to change our tactics,'' Lapuente said. ``With
11 on 11, against anyone we attack. But 10 on 11, we had to be
careful.''
</P>
<P>
   At halftime, Blanco said he told teammates to quit playing so
tentatively. But only three minutes into the second half it looked
as if Belgium would walk away with the victory when Wilmots got his
second goal on a nice individual effort to get clear in the Mexican
box and unleash the untouchable shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, we should have won this game,'' Belgian coach Georges
Leekens said. ``When Belgium is up 2-0, Belgium should win.''
</P>
<P>
   But Belgium didn't, thanks to a terrific effort by Ramon Ramirez
in the 55th minute that ignited his team.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez tried to take a pass in front of the Belgian goal and
work the ball past goalie Filip De Wilde. But as DeWilde tried to
converge on the ball before Ramirez could get off a shot, Belgium's
Gert Verheyen also crashed into Ramirez, clipping his heel from
behind.
</P>
<P>
   Verheyen then received a red card from referee Hugh Dallas of
Scotland and Garcia-Aspe whipped in the penalty kick to make it
2-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``From that point, we could be Mexico again,'' Mexico's Luis
Hernandez said. ``We kept going and going forward. It was
tremendous to show that we had character and we had spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   From the 56th minute on, Mexico dominated control of the ball
and took several legitimate shots.
</P>
<P>
   The game-tying goal by Blanco was a thing of beauty, with
Ramirez taking the ball on a big run directly at the Belgian
defense, then chipping the ball across to Blanco.
</P>
<P>
   The pass went long, well over Blanco, but Blanco dove feet-first
and whacked the ball with his left foot in front of De Wilde and,
well, then it was the raucous Mexican fans who went wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very good game for us, even though we wanted the
win,'' Blanco said. ``It looked like we were going to have an
unlucky day, but we turned it around. We were in trouble, but we
got out of it. It looked like we were not going to get anything,
but we got a point. That was great.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
