<HEADLINE>
SHORT HOLE STYMIES BROOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Fort Worth resident Mark Brooks watched his
chance to move into contention during the third round disappear
with a triple bogey at the 288-yard seventh hole, the shortest
par-4 at the Olympic Club.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks pulled his drive into a bush, forcing him to take an
unplayable lie. His recovery shot kicked into the rough and Brooks
eventually three-putted for a seven. After playing the first six
holes at even par, Brooks was 6 over on the final 12, dropping to
12 over for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played the short holes poorly. That really hurt,'' said
Brooks, who also took one of only five bogeys recorded at No. 1, a
533-yard par-5 that played to a tournament-low scoring average of
4.58. Another bogey came at No. 10, a 422-yard par-4.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks' third-round highlight proved to be an 18-foot chip-in
for birdie from the rough surrounding the 13th green.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a tough week,'' said Brooks, who survived the cut at
his first major championship since winning the 1996 PGA. ``I didn't
have a lot of confidence coming in. But even if you did, you were
still going to have problems here.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks agreed with fellow pros who have criticized the U.S. Golf
Association's course set-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``About every third year, they miss the boat in trying to make
the winner shoot around par,'' Brooks said. ``If you're in the
rough, more than half the lies here are total luck around the
greens. There's not much skill involved. You just make a slash and
go at it.''
Nicklaus, Woods fade Jack Nicklaus, who survived the cut in his
42nd Open with a 40-foot birdie putt on the 18th hole of Friday's
round, ran out of magic yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I visualized a 65. That was in my mind until I passed it on
the 17th fairway,'' said Nicklaus, who shot a 73 and dropped to 10
over.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, meanwhile, opened with a birdie and did not take
another in his final 17 holes. He registered consecutive bogeys at
Nos. 3 and 4, then parred in to shoot 71 and drop to 7 over.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those weeks where I can't keep anything
going,'' Woods said. ``Everything will go perfect for four holes,
then my swing goes away. Or I'll make everything for a few holes
and then I'll four-putt.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who did not three-putt during his victory at the 1997
Masters, has two four-putts and three three-putts on his card at
the 1998 Open.
Rolling with Casey Perhaps appropriately, disabled golfer Casey
Martin played the third round with the only player in the field who
might have an inkling of what his physical condition would be like:
Spain's Jose Maria Olazabal.
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal's career was presumed over in 1996, when he was unable
to walk 18 holes without severe pain because of what was initially
diagnosed as severe arthritis. Eventually, Olazabal's condition
improved and he returned to the European Tour in 1987 after an
18-month absence.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who suffers from a rare circulatory disorder that makes
it difficult for him to walk, was granted a federal court order in
February allowing him to use a cart in competition at professional
events.
</P>
<P>
   Before the round, Olazabal joked with Martin about letting him
ride in the passenger's seat. Although he said he ``feels
sympathy'' for Martin, Olazabal made it clear that he disagrees
with the U.S. court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a chance to play and was told that I would be able to
use a buggy,'' Olazabal said. ``I declined the invitation. I think
that walking is part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin termed the pairing ``ironic'' and said the two exchanged
nothing but pleasantries throughout 18 holes that ended with
Olazabal shooting 71 and Martin fashioning a 74.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew about his foot problems, so I thought it was ironic
that we played together,'' Martin said. ``But we're in totally
different situations. He's almost 100 percent and I never will
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Told about Olazabal's anti-cart stance, Martin shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't seem bitter at all,'' Martin said. ``He was very
congenial.''
Briefly After omitting the driver from his bag in the first two
rounds, John Daly unleashed it yesterday on six holes. He hit a
390-yard drive on No. 6, setting up a birdie, and drove the green
at the 288-yard seventh hole. Off the seventh tee, Daly used a
3-wood.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Perry recorded the first hole-in-one of the tournament by
knocking a 6-iron into the cup at the 176-yard 13th hole. It marked
his third career ace in tournament competition but his first at the
Open.
</P>
</TEXT>
