<HEADER>
A8862 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAN-SOCCER-BOS &LR;      06-20 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-SOCCER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR AMERICANS, A GAME; FOR IRANIANS, A CAUSE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LYON, France _ Iran's soccer coach carries a green card from the
Great Satan. Jalal Talebi's family has lived in California for
nearly two decades. His youngest son just graduated from Palo Alto
High and is bound for UCLA. His wife has a skin care business and a
vegetarian restaurant near Stanford. Talebi used to coach at a
local junior college. He likes America and Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But all week long, people have been bringing up 1979 to him.
America Held Hostage. Iran, the outlaw state. Revolution, war,
terrorism, embargos, fractured relations between Washington and
Tehran. It all comes back because somebody pulled two balls out of
a bowl last December and matched the US and Iran in a World Cup
soccer match here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please don't make it too big,'' Talebi pleaded with
journalists last week. ``This is a game. A game of football.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, for many of Talebi's countrymen back home, it is much
more. Though the two governments have been edging closer to
normalcy, nudged last week by Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, Uncle Sam is still widely regarded with hatred and
mistrust in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   America propped up the Shah for years, opposed the Islamic
revolution, sabotaged the country's economy, and is thought by some
in Iran to have provoked the war with Iraq. Wall murals in Tehran
still say ``Down with the USA'' and show the American flag with
skulls instead of stars.
</P>
<P>
   So an Iranian victory in the Stade Gerland Sunday (it's a night
game here in France) would all but knock the US out of the world's
most important sporting event and be a coup of enormous symbolic
and emotional significance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is imperative that we win against the USA,'' says Khodadad
Azizi, the team's star player. ``For historical reasons, our
country is a lot more sensitive to this meeting. Iran has been
disappointed by American politics in recent years. This is the most
important match of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   For the American players, most of whom were young children
during the hostage crisis, Sunday's match has little political
significance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't talked about it,'' says playmaker Claudio Reyna,
who was 6 when the US embassy was stormed. ``We've talked about
Iran the soccer team and not Iran the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   US coach Steve Sampson, who was in graduate school in 1979,
remembers the ``America Held Hostage'' drama vividly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can relate to it more than our players,'' he says. ``I
watched it every night on television. Certainly, what happened to
those hostages was devastating to them. Our hearts went out to
them. At some point, though, you have to put those issues aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's match, the first ever between the US and Iran, is being
touted as a bit of political serendipity, bringing two together
countries that have had no diplomatic relations for nearly two
decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media are calling this the mother of all soccer matches,''
says Talebi. ``They are making it too big, but we accept it. We are
happy to be playing a game that the world is watching.''
</P>
<P>
   After 20 years away from soccer's global stage, the Iranians are
delighted merely to be here. Iran was Asia's dominant team in the
'70s, winning three continental championships and qualifying for
the 1976 Olympics and the 1978 World Cup. Then the revolution and
the Iraq war brought soccer in Iran to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a holy war for us,'' says Talebi, who was national
coach then. ``Our basic thought was to get rid of the enemy and
finish the war. During those eight years, not only soccer but all
of sport fell behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Iran didn't even try to qualify for the 1982 and 1986 Cups.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no real game of football in Iran,'' Talebi says.
``So I had to go overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   He became a coaching gypsy, taking jobs in the United Arab
Emirates, in Singapore, in the US.
</P>
<P>
   Talebi settled his family in San Jose, opened a supermarket and
took a coaching job at De Anza community college. While the Islamic
government back home railed against the Great Satan, Talebi felt
welcome as an Iranian in the States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was treated as everyone else,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Talebi still carried an Iranian passport, still went home for
several months every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born in Iran,'' he says. ``Iran is my country. Everyone
loves their country and wants to die for their country.''
</P>
<P>
   For Talebi, the serendipity is not that his country is playing
America but that his country is playing in the Cup at all.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranians are here by a near-miracle. They did not win their
qualifying group last year. They could not beat Japan in the Asian
playoff. They could not beat Australia at home in the first match
of their last-chance playoff and trailed, 2-0, with 14 minutes left
in the return match at Melbourne. Somehow, the Iranians pulled off
a draw and got a ticket to France because they had scored more road
goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 20 years, we are here,'' says Talebi, who was brought in
last month to coach after the squad lost by six goals to Rome's
club team. ``This is a victory for us. We are here to get more
experience, to show everyone we can play, that we are one of the
best countries in Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing Uncle Sam, though, adds undeniable spice to the quest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can hardly imagine what's going to happen in Tehran if we
win,'' says Mohammad Khakpour, the squad's top defender.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens inside the Stade Gerland Sunday, the Iranians
plan to shake hands with the Americans after the final whistle and
exchange jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no problems with the American people,'' says Ali Daei,
their star forward. ``The people are not the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the international noise over the match hasn't reached
the players. The Iranian team has been secluded in a bakery school
in Yssingeaux, a 90-minute drive southwest of the city. The
American team is quartered in an ivy-covered chateau in the wine
country an hour's drive north.
</P>
<P>
   The players know each other by reputation and by jersey number.
They're vaguely aware of the recent diplomatic dance steps between
their governments. But for most of them, what happened in 1979 is
hazy history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Great Satan? What's that?'' US midfielder/-surfer Frankie
Hejduk wondered last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a board wax,'' he was told.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
