<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8878 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-U.S.-HNS     06-20 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD </SLUG>
 CUP-U.S.-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
U.S.-Iran: Ultimate in political football
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BORDEAUX, France _ The lingering image is of American citizens
being put on display on the streets of Teheran, handcuffed and
blindfolded, the American flag burning at their feet and chants of
``Death to Satan'' ringing through their ears.
</P>
<P>
   Some 20 years later, 22 men from the United States and Iran will
march onto a small patch of grass in France, many of them hardly
able to remember the details of the 1979 international crisis.
</P>
<P>
   They pledge to try and offer the world another image.
</P>
<P>
   They will arrive to an entirely different corner of the world, a
snug little French city called Lyon, which is known for tempting
wines and quaint sidewalk cafes.
</P>
<P>
   Their flags will be waving above plazas, parks and the charming
35,000-seat Stade Gerland. Their fans will be wearing only their
colors.
</P>
<P>
   They will be bound only by their nation's political pasts and
the ramifications tied to this day for more than six months.
</P>
<P>
   And the only thing at their feet will be a soccer ball, which
they all know is in the same shape as the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are sportsmen, not politicians,'' said Iranian coach Jalel
Talebi, who in an ironic twist in this soccer showdown is a coach
who has lived in Southern California the past 17 years. ``We want
to play football and show everybody that we have no problem with
the American people. But there are political things involved, I
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Players and coaches from both sides have known the factors
involved in today's game for months. Only recently has the game
become even more pertinent in a World Cup sense _ both teams need a
victory to keep hopes alive for advancing in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize both governments are looking at this game and would
like to get one over on each other,'' U.S. goalkeeper Kasey Keller
said. ``If they beat us, they've had a successful World Cup. I
expect the first 10 or 15 minutes will be an emotional situation
for everybody. I wish all the attention we're getting would be just
about soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is not.
</P>
<P>
   For 90 minutes today in Lyon, the world will watch the United
States and Iran battle on a soccer field not just because of things
like the Group F standings, the opportunity of earning points in
the round-robin and putting on a display of terrific soccer.
</P>
<P>
   The world surely will watch as much because of what was put on
display nearly 20 years ago in Tehran, the 444 terroristic days,
the tense history and lingering ill feelings by people of both
nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can relate to that period of time a lot better than the
players can,'' U.S. coach Steve Sampson said. ``I was glued to the
television every night watching the news.''
</P>
<P>
   Said U.S. defender Alexi Lalas, 28: ``What I remember is, U.S.
good; Iran bad. Of course, the fact that we are playing together
will be symbolic. It makes for a good picture. But whether you can
change deep-rooted feelings between the governments is a different
question.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the painful and bitter feelings between the nations
hardly have tempered over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomatic relations between the nations remain severed and it
was not until last week, perhaps in an effort to ease pressures for
today's game, that U.S. government officials even hinted at
relaxing its strong stance against Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Both President Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
addressed the U.S.-Iran game last week, using the opportunity to
mention the possible resumption of diplomatic relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton also reportedly taped a special message that
will be broadcast during today's game.
</P>
<P>
   Still, last month the U.S. State Department called Iran the
world's most active sponsor of terrorism and the Iranian government
has made no secret of its involvement in the game. National
officials will be present in the stadium today and all business
activity is expected to be suspended in Iran during the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranian government also condemned a French television
station's showing of the movie Not Without My Daughter, which it
said depicts Iranians in a negative light. The government even
briefly hinted at pulling its team from the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Iranian players realize the stakes involved today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to win'' Iranian forward Khodadad Azizi said. ``For
historical reasons, our country is a lot more sensitive to this
meeting. Iran has been disappointed by American politics in recent
years. We have to win. This is the most important match of my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   The game has received such attention that the international
soccer federation has banned fans from bringing banners or signs
into the stadium. It also has increased security for the game and
admitted that it has received threats of ``unknown'' factions
saying they would disrupt the game.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team has made public their hotel headquarters while in
Lyon.
</P>
<P>
   And FIFA president Sepp Blatter has admitted that it was ``no
accident'' that chosen to call the game was a referee from
Switzerland, a noted neutral nation with good relations with the
United States and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the middle of it all are the players and coaches,
the majority of whom have announced that they will try to spurn
FIFA's World Cup edict of immediately leaving the field in favor of
an age-old soccer tradition _ trading jerseys at the final whistle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Win or lose, I am going to try and trade jerseys,'' U.S.
forward Eric Wynalda said. ``Before the game we are going to shake
hands and at the end I would like to trade jerseys. It's a great
example of how the World Cup and soccer brings nations together.''
</P>
<P>
   Said U.S. midfielder Ernie Stewart: ``It could be a great symbol
to both nations of how things can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course. But today the world will watch these nations play
soccer because of the way things were from 1979-1981 and what it
has done to these political nemeses since.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to keep the politics out of it completely,''
Sampson said. ``But it is hard to ignore history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
