<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Still aiming high: Shank's aim still steady after injury
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- A quarter thrown into the crowd at a high school
football game struck Luke Shank's right eye like a BB hitting
glass, shattering the lens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a thunk, and I'm on the ground,'' Shank said.
</P>
<P>
   How does Shank know it was a quarter if he never saw it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because my friend has it,'' the 18-year-old from Fort Wayne,
Ind., said with a smile. ``My dad was going to put it in the stock
of my rifle. ... Maybe my new rifle.''
</P>
<P>
   His new left-handed rifle. A shooter depends on his eye the way
a kicker does his leg. But the freak accident forced Shank to
switch the eye he uses to sight the target and, by extension, shoot
from the left side of his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just awkward; it's not harder,'' said Shank, who will
compete Monday and Tuesday in air rifle at the USA Shooting
National Championships at Wolf Creek Olympic Shooting Complex.
``It's ingrained in your head one way, and you have to turn it
around.''
</P>
<P>
   After a 10-month layoff, Shank returned to the sport a year ago
and placed fourth at the Junior Olympics three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   His cousin, JP O'Connor of Marietta, helps coach him, often by
phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He spent an awful lot of time standing at home, holding the
gun and pointing at a pencil dot on the wall,'' O'Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   Just as he had to switch from right to left, Shank also
transferred his longtime wish of attending West Point to the
reality of entering the Naval Academy, which recruited him for its
rifle team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coach caught wind of his story,'' O'Connor, 43, said. ``I
look at him and think, `Why couldn't I be like that when I was 18?'
He's got the drive, the ambition and the brains.''
</P>
<P>
   For three months after the accident, Shank couldn't see at all.
He spent the first two weeks on the couch deep in thought, but not
self-pity, even though he knew if he'd worn his glasses and not his
contacts, he would've been fine.
</P>
<P>
   Things had been going so well, Shank told himself. ``I was
making good grades, had the highest rank in ROTC and was shooting
well,'' he said. ``I got self-confident, and then it humbles you
and makes you appreciate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Shank never doubted he'd be able to see again. Looking at his
brown eyes, there's no way for an outsider to tell which one has
the implanted lens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of led to believe, because I think people wanted to
cheer me up, that I'd be able to see all right again,'' Shank said,
``so I was kind of waiting on that. The doctor essentially told me
I'd never see better than 20-60. He's still amazed that I can see.
Beyond 10 feet on a normal eye chart, I can read the 20-20 line
with corrected vision.''
</P>
<P>
   The glasses he wears have ``bulletproof'' lenses, he said, which
protect his good eye with 20-15 vision, as well as the one, he
said, ``that's like it's 70 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Shank, who got his first gun at age 6 and shot at GI Joes, golf
balls and pop cans, will report to Annapolis next month with a
medical waiver. He jokes that he won't be a fighter pilot, but
that's OK, because he's more interested in engineering and physics.
</P>
<P>
   Shank has worked long hours with O'Connor this week to make up
for a month spent getting into shape for the academy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be physically training and shooting,'' Shank said.
``If you build coarse muscle, it causes jitters.''
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to score 590 out of 600 during the 1 hour and 45
minutes he has to record 60 shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole reason someone shoots is it's virtually impossible
to shoot perfect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he won't stop trying.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
