<DOCNO> NYT19980620.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9056 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USOPEN-KUCHAR-COX     06-20 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USOPEN-KUCHAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Father's day at the open
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's a story that Boys' Life would not publish.
It's fiction so far-fetched, you'd send the Hardy Boys into
gut-breaking laughter. Surely, the schmaltz police would surround
you.
</P>
<P>
   OK, just for laughs, can you run that by me again? You say the
kid, a gangly golfer who grins more than a guilty politician, turns
20 on Father's Day while he's playing in a U.S. Open as an amateur
and beating many of the world's best players? Are you serious?
</P>
<P>
   Granted, he's the U.S. Amateur champion from Georgia Tech and
arguably the best college player in the nation, but what's that? A
final round on Father's Day, with his father, Peter, on his bag?
</P>
<P>
   Well, as Matt Kuchar's smiling mug will attest, it's not only
``way cool,'' it's way true. Just when it seemed as though Kuchar's
1998 highlight footage could not upstage finishing 21st at the
Masters winning over every mother in the nation and earning a
return trip to Augusta, here he was Saturday only two shots off the
lead in the 98th U.S. Open before sliding to a 6-over 76 finish,
and falling eight strokes behind leader Payne Stewart with an
overall 5-over 215. Kuchar made the early surge displaying all the
nervousness of somebody hitting range balls at Druid Hills.
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, Kuchar had been following double-bogeys with birdies,
and staying cooler than the ocean breeze. As a matter of fact,
after playing two days with Kuchar, defending champion Ernie Els
was ready to say the kid would be right there today, with a
mind-boggling reason to remember a 20th birthday and Father's Day,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he's playing, the way he's controlling his emotions,''
said Els, ``he's got a real good chance. I said to him, `After this
week, you might want to turn pro. You might have a 10-year
exemption.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Asked Friday if he seriously can contend, Kuchar said quickly,
``I don't think so.'' At the time it was midafternoon and he
trailed Payne Stewart by five shots. As the day wore on, however,
and The Olympic Club found some victims because of a putt-putt pin
placement on the 18th, Stewart regressed. Kuchar went to bed a mere
two shots off the lead.
</P>
<P>
   More nervous than his demeanor would imply _ he starts his grin
nearly before the ball has found the cup _ Kuchar said, ``There is
the experience factor. We'll see how I handle the final two days
here, see how well I stack up against these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise that Kuchar proudly defends his father. Peter,
the insurance and investment man from Lake Mary, Fla., is living
every dad's dream, having caddied for his son during an Amateur
victory and now in two majors. While Kuchar obviously draws
inspiration and finds a calm from his presence, it's Dad who gets
so demonstrative by cheering, jumping and college-type high-fives
that he occasionally disturbs fellow caddies and players.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Riefke, who caddies for Justin Leonard and has spent two
days watching the act, spoke with Peter earlier in the week about
``being more aware of his surroundings.'' On the 12th green Friday,
Riefke said he fixed a heel print that was a result of Father
Kuchar's jumping around after Matt's birdie. At the 18th green
Friday, Leonard, already irked with his own game, motioned Peter to
move out of his peripheral vision while lining up a putt. When the
ESPN cameras caught Leonard, he was shaking his head, obviously
perturbed.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Peter upset him, Leonard said, ``Next question.''
Then he added, ``It does me no good to answer that question,
understand?''
</P>
<P>
   Els admitted, ``His father gets quite excited. Matt's very calm,
but his father's the other side of the coin.''
</P>
<P>
   Walking toward a car shuttle to the media center Friday, Matt
said, ``I think any dad would react the same way in the same
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked flatly whether his father is a distraction, Kuchar even
smiled then.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I think Dad does a good job _ very good golf etiquette,''
Matt said. ``He gets excited after I make a putt or hit a shot, but
the players have time to calm down themselves and let the crowd
subside. ... He's great for me. I don't know if it would be an
advantage for another guy to have my dad, but he keeps me calm. He
keeps me relaxed. Seeing him excited is just a lot of fun for of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   That a son doesn't care to rob his father of a lifetime thrill,
regardless that he gets carried away, only adds to the son's
character.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hitting every shot with him,'' said Peter, a 6-handicap
player. ``Trust me. Every shot. The kid's got a flair for the
dramatic. He never ceases to amaze me.''
</P>
<P>
   Fun is the optimum word for both Matt and his Dad. It is costing
Peter about $30,000 to play around the world this summer _ they are
in Scotland for the Loch Lomond Invitational in two weeks, followed
by the British Open in England _ but surely it will return to the
family kitty in the near future. How near is the real question. For
the first time, Matt is waffling a bit when asked about the pro
issue. College is fun, yes, and he has two years remaining. But a
lot has happened lately. It's obvious he can play with these guys,
or outplay them. He began the third round seven shots ahead of
Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if money can persuade me to leave,'' Kuchar said.
``I haven't even thought about it. I'm not sure what will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he dare think about, gasp, winning a U.S. Open as a
20-year-old amateur?
</P>
<P>
   No way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember in junior tournaments, I was always thinking, `What
am I going to say in my acceptance speech?' '' Kuchar said. ``I
would be playing in the last group on the last day and I'm
thinking, `What am I going to say when I get the trophy?' ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I never won a single junior event.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
