<SLUG> BC-USOPEN-NOTEBOOK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Montgomerie hears it from fans
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Colin Montgomerie is about to complete another
forgettable U.S. Open, a Saturday 77 having placed him at
11-over-par 221. And that's the less troublesome part.
</P>
<P>
   After being showered by jeers and catcalls from Olympic Club
fans Friday, Montgomerie was given extra security for Saturday's
third round. The United States Golf Association put a security
force around the Scotsman that included two San Francisco policemen
and a Daly County cop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's regrettable,'' David Fay, the USGA executive director,
told European reporters. ``We're just hoping verbal abuse doesn't
turn into physical abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Favorites fizzle big-time
</P>
<P>
   So much for the U.S. Open pre-tournament favorites. Tom Watson
missed the cut. Justin Leonard faded further out of view Saturday
with a 77. Jim Furyk finally awoke Saturday with 68 and is at five
over. PGA Tour leading moneywinner Fred Couples ballooned to 18
over with a 79.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play very well the first two days and I got behind
the 8-ball,'' said Furyk, who lost a playoff to J.P. Hayes at
Westchester a week ago. ``I still think par or just under par will
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, not really a favorite but a man familiar with
Olympic from his college days, kept saying all week that he was
playing well, but hasn't showed it. He's at 7-over 217 following a
71 Saturday that included 14 straight pars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't made many putts,'' Woods said. ``I haven't hit the
ball solidly. I haven't hit the ball below the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Distance, however, typically has not been a problem. Woods hit
driver, wedge (148) yards on the 533-yard, par-5 first hole and
two-putted for birdie.
</P>
<P>
   Woods and Jack Nicklaus were among those players complaining
about sand-filled divots causing soggy lies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfair,'' Woods said. ``It's one thing to be in the
middle of the fairway. It's another thing to end up in a bunker in
the middle of the fairway.:''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus called the 18th fairway a ``mine field.'' Said the
58-year-old, four-time champion, who shot a 73 and is at 10 over,
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know if you have a chip or a bunker shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry aces 13th hole
</P>
<P>
   Chris Perry made a hole-in-one on the par-3, 13th hole with a
6-iron from 176 yards, during a 2-over 72, moving to seven over for
the tournament. His respect for the course did not diminish,
though. ``This course doesn't turn men into boys; it turns men into
children,'' said Perry. ``It makes us pros, who are the best in the
game _ the top 1 percent of people who play golf _ look like
15-handicappers.'' ... What does Matt Kuchar, the Georgia Tech
phenom, say when he's angry at a shot on the course? ``Cornbread!''
... Kuchar's ball says ``Kooch'' on it. Lee Janzen's carries the
number 93, denoting his 1993 Open win. ... The 60 players to make
the cut was the lowest since 1977, when 60 also advanced to the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
