<SLUG> BC-QUEST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER GAME'S PHANTOM MILLION-DOLLAR WINNER LEAVES PLAYERS
SKEPTICAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DENNIS WAGNER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The death of Professor Jonathon William Faulkner was accompanied
by a curious inheritance left to his students: $1 million for the
one who could solve a mystery hidden in his 10-room mansion.
</P>
<P>
   With that fictional premise, a Scottsdale company lured
thousands of computer sleuths into buying a $50 game _ and
competing in an arduous contest that promised $1 million to the
real-life winner.
</P>
<P>
   But, two years later, Sirius Publishing Inc. has transformed its
software conundrum into a mystery by refusing to fully identify the
winner.
</P>
<P>
   The twist has sent angry players of the Treasure Quest software
game on a new mission _ trying to find out whether the
award-winning games is as bogus as Professor Faulkner's will.
</P>
<P>
   ``My gut feeling is that it's a scam,'' said Paul Wigowsky, an
Oregon schoolteacher who this week filed a consumer fraud complaint
with the Arizona Attorney General's Office. ``Unless we see the
winner with our own eyes, we won't believe it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Karie Dozer, a spokeswoman for Attorney General Grant Woods,
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   But Sirius President Richard Gnant insisted that the Treasure
Quest winner is a real person, the prize money will be paid as
advertised and that game rules were followed ``impeccably.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're miffed because they didn't win,'' Gnant said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've maintained the integrity of this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Treasure Quest began April 10, 1996, with a flurry of fanfare as
the world's first million-dollar software contest and, Gnant said,
sold 225,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   The game is based on the mystery left behind by Professor
Faulkner, as revealed in a series of computer screens. Players face
a labyrinth of about 1,200 clues involving word and number riddles
tapping everything from ancient Hebrew letters to Morse code to
literary quotations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to solving the puzzle, winners were required to
submit an essay of at least 1,000 words explaining their answer.
</P>
<P>
   Wigowsky and others said they spent thousands of hours
deciphering codes, doing library research and trading ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, when the winner was announced May 17, there was no press
release, photo session or celebration _ just a note on the Treasure
Quest Web site identifying the $1 million answer as ``The Tree of
Life.''
</P>
<P>
   That revelation came with a cryptic identification of the
winner: ``P. Dreizen of San Francisco, California.''
</P>
<P>
   Telephone operators list only one Dreizen in San Francisco _
Pamela. She did not respond to a phone message, and computer
searches under that name lead nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Gnant said P. Dreizen asked not to be identified further. He
added that game rules don't require the winner to go public, and he
is morally bound to respect Dreizen's request.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Treasure Quest rules specifically waive a player's right to
privacy: ``Entry constitutes permission (except where prohibitted)
to use winner's name, likeness, hometown, biographical information
and any comments about the contest for publicity purposes without
compensation.''
</P>
<P>
   Gnant said he didn't release the winning essay because Dreizen
asked him not to, and because it contains personal information.
</P>
<P>
   He said the essay was required only as a tie-breaker, in case
two winning entries were submitted the same day. &QL; 
WEB SITE CLOSED &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the winner was announced, Gnant closed the
Treasure Quest Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was so much untruth in there,'' he said, referring to
postings from disgruntled players. ``I watched these people trash
my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gnant refused to answer basic questions such as: How many
people were on the winning team? Is Dreizen male or female? When
was the winning entry submitted?
</P>
<P>
   That date is critical to players who say they came up with the
mystery answer more than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Gnant acknowledged that Wigowsky solved the riddle
before Dreizen, but was disqualified because he did not place a
contest registration number in the appropriate place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy didn't follow the rules, so he didn't win Treasure
Quest. I'm sorry,'' Gnant added. ``Maybe I should have told him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gnant, the brother of state Rep. Randall Gnant, R-Scottsdale,
blamed the controversy on ``extremists'' and said most contestants
loved the game. He stressed that judging was verified by a renowned
New York company that has overseen contests by Coca Cola and other
major companies. A letter from the firm, Ventura Associates Inc.,
confirms the selection of Dreizen as winner.
</P>
<P>
   Gnant said he sympathizes with losers, adding, ``These people
poured their hearts and souls into this contest for two years. It
was an addicting game. I spent two weeks playing it and almost went
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   He said there was no celebration of the final results because
his company has switched from computer games to CD-ROM movies, and
he didn't want to spend money on a victory bash. &QL; 
SKEPTICS UNSATISFIED &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But those answers don't satisfy the sleuthing skeptics, who even
discovered that P. Dreizen can be reconstructed into a provocative
anagram: ``End Prize.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Boucher, a Colchester, Vt., postal supervisor who spent
vacations working the puzzle, said Treasure Quest is so complex
that no one could solve it alone, yet the winner's name never
surfaced during two years of chat room exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   ``For people to take this on blind faith is just stupid,''
Boucher added. ``I'm not a sore loser. If I lost, I lost. But until
these questions are answered, I'm not going to accept the fact that
this P. Dreizen won.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he is one of several players who shifted their
attention from the game mystery to Sirius business.
</P>
<P>
   Among their discoveries, confirmed by Gnant: The publishing
company has cut its staff from 80 employees to 25, closed its
headquarters and moved operations into a warehouse. Gnant said
those moves reflect Sirius' new direction, not financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   James Beckett, a 62-year-old retiree from Corning, N.Y., found a
1991 commercial bankruptcy involving another Gnant business,
Express Technologies Inc., and lawsuits against Sirius alleging
unpaid debts. Gnant said the complaints arose from disputes with
suppliers over unsatisfactory products.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER SUSPICIONS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Suspicion about the winner also stems from a dispute over key
literary quotes used in solving the riddle. Wigowsky and others say
the phrases contain errors. Gnant denies there are mistakes and
complains that every bit of information he gives out gets twisted:
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say the grass is green and the sky is blue without
someone saying there's an ulterior motive.''
</P>
<P>
   Disgruntled players plastered Web sites and discussion rooms
with questions, conspiracy theories and a mock game called Treasure
Quash. At least one man logged a complaint with Internet Fraud
Watch.
</P>
<P>
   Beckett said he assumed the game was legitimate because of the
accolades and media hoopla. But problems soon emerged when the
Treasure Quest mastermind, Cerise Casper of Washington, sued Sirius
Publishing over a contract dispute. Before that case was settled
for an undisclosed sum, Casper reportedly made computer contact
with Treasure Quest participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``No sooner do we get into this than Cerise pops up in the chat
rooms, warning us to contact the attorney general,'' Beckett said.
</P>
<P>
   Gnant would not say whether the prize money _ to be paid in
increments of $50,000 a year _ has been set aside in a trust, but
said the funds are ``secure.''
</P>
<P>
   As for whether Sirius profited from selling the software and
related items, he said, ``I think financially it was about a push.
It might have made a couple hundred thousand dollars.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
