<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBA-HARPRING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Draft passe as way to forge a dynasty
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Barring great fortune, the draft no longer is the way
to build a strong team in the NBA, and the next edition on
Wednesday bears testimony to that.
</P>
<P>
   Sending a warning to fans of the Clippers, Grizzlies and
Nuggets, Detroit vice president for basketball Rick Sund says,
``Anybody who thinks that this draft, even if you do have one of
the first three picks, is going to catapult some team over the hump
is greatly mistaken.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawks general manager Pete Babcock notes, ``The way you build a
team in today's NBA is through trades and free agency.''
</P>
<P>
   What's happened to a cherished institution that still serves the
NFL well? The rules have changed.
</P>
<P>
   Sund's Pistons have the 11th pick Wednesday night. ``Basically,
we expect to be drafting somebody who we might be able to develop
into a player that will help us three or four years down the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, under current rules, a player drafted Wednesday can
become a free agent after three seasons, or about the time he
starts to blossom as a player. That's one of the changes the NBA
wants in its working agreement with the players association. Teams
are asking for options that will add two or three more seasons to a
rookie contract. That would serve to hold down salaries of young
players and also protect the investments of teams that are
building.
</P>
<P>
   Sund recalls that in his years as player personnel chief in
Dallas, the Mavs thrived on the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``The year we made it to the (Western) conference finals (in
1987), 11 of our 12 players were guys we drafted. Those days are
over. You build teams in thirds now _ one-third draft, one-third
free agents and one-third trades.''
</P>
<P>
   A glance at the top prospects in this draft shows the dilemma
that bad teams face:
</P>
<P>
   Among the projected top players in the draft, guards Mike Bibby,
Paul Pierce, Vince Carter and Larry Hughes, forwards Robert Traylor
and Antawn Jamison and center Nazr Mohammed are all underclassmen.
German Dirk Nowitzki and Houston high-schooler Rashard Lewis did
not go to college. And there are three others also making the jump
from high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to get a read on young players,'' Babcock said.
``It's a huge gamble, and the problem we have is that, the more
young players you have in the draft, the fewer remain to become top
senior talent. Right now, you hope you can find a serviceable
player who can develop.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Tim Duncan of San Antonio and Keith Van Horn of New
Jersey both stayed in college four years, few are induced to follow
their example.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the draft shows this sorry record:
</P>
<P>
   Over the last six years, only a handful of players took the
teams that drafted them from the lottery to the playoffs. The
number includes Kevin Garnett and Stephon Marbury (Minnesota),
Grant Hill (Detroit), Shaquille O'Neal and Penny Hardaway (Orlando)
and Alonzo Mourning (Charlotte).
</P>
<P>
   Is that pattern likely to change soon?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Babcock said. ``Under the current rules, the league is
very different.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
