<HEADER>
A9065 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YANKS-LEDE-COX     06-20 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YANKS-LEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two for the show
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- George Steinbrenner, the ``Boss'' of the New York
Yankees, is sitting in his office, thinking ahead to this week's
four-game series against Atlanta and chuckling about his
counterpart with the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Ted Turner) probably said I am a preppy, prep-school,
blue-blazer-type guy. Which I am,'' said Steinbrenner, who also
owns a shipbuilding operation. ``Ted Turner is a free-spirit
dresser, and he is a free-spirit human being, which I love about
him. I think it's great.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Turner also is laughing. He's sitting in the CNN Center in
downtown Atlanta, remembering the first time he met Steinbrenner.
``It was like a rookie looking up at Hank Aaron,'' said Turner,
vice chairman of Time Warner and owner of the Atlanta Braves.
``When they made George, they definitely broke the mold. He's
definitely one of a kind.''
</P>
<P>
   If baseball ever needed an odd couple among its ownership, it
got it in Turner and Steinbrenner, two of the richest and most
powerful men in sports. Ted and George. George and Ted. Instead of
well-worn adjectives to describe the two, just recall that Turner
has gone to great financial lengths to save the world, and
Steinbrenner has gone to great lengths to control it.
</P>
<P>
   George's main concern at the moment is whether he can force the
city of New York to tear down Yankee Stadium and build him a new
ballpark. Ted's main concern is about nuclear testing in India and
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   That makes the upcoming series between the owners' baseball
teams more than a brief recreational respite from a mundane summer
schedule that has both teams threatening to lead their respective
divisions by double figures. In June.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun in 1996, and it is going to be fun again,''
Steinbrenner said, referring to the Yankees' victory over the
Braves in the '96 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a really hard one,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   But Turner and Atlanta have persevered. And Steinbrenner and New
York have persevered. In fact, that's why George and Ted are fond
of each other.
</P>
<P>
   Sort of. George says the two don't exchange Christmas gifts, but
if they did, he'd get Ted something special. ``I wouldn't buy him a
present; I would give him something I value very much, something
that was very valuable to me that I had achieved, hoping that he
understands I was parting with it for a person I think the world
of.''
</P>
<P>
   And Turner? ``What would I buy George? ... I don't know _ a
power hitter?''
</P>
<P>
   Ted says he hasn't talked with George lately, but he is aware
that a character portraying George was a big hit on the
``Seinfeld'' television show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I have watched it; it's (Time Warner's) show,''
Turner said. But he admitted he hasn't seen many of the episodes.
``I've watched three or four, and there are 200 or something I
haven't seen. I'm more interested in trying to get the nuclear
situation back on the agenda, now that India and Pakistan exploded
bombs.''
</P>
<P>
   When the series begins in New York on Monday, the smartly
dressed Steinbrenner will be sitting in his club-level box, rocking
away in his leather recliner. And when the series shifts back to
Atlanta on Wednesday, Turner, in his best free-spirit attire, will
be watching from his seat near the field, jabbering away.
</P>
<P>
   Turner will have his hands on a soft drink; Steinbrenner will
have his hands on the controls.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Steinbrenner has never been more involved with the
operations of the Yankees. He's making personnel decisions for the
team, and some people contend that he's even calling the clubhouse
to make moves during the game. George says it's not so. ``I never
called the dugout on what to do in a game,'' he said. ``Never.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner, on the other hand, has never been so far removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss being more hands-on now that the team has had so much
success ever since I got my hands off,'' Turner says. ``I'd love to
be (team president) Stan Kasten. I'd love to be more involved.
Remember my slogan: `Lead, follow or get out of the way.' And I
have gotten out of the way with my sports teams. It's worked out
better that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner, 60, paid $10 million for the Braves in 1976 and became
the proud owner of one of the worst franchises in sports.
Steinbrenner, 67, bought the Yankees in 1973 for $8.8 million and
had one of the best.
</P>
<P>
   From the very first meeting, Steinbrenner recalls that Turner
seemed preoccupied with bigger things.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sitting at a bar talking after a meeting of
baseball,'' Steinbrenner said. ``He was complaining that he was
going up to his room to watch the news. It was 6 (p.m.), and he was
going to excuse himself from us. He was complaining about how bad
it was, the only time you could find out what was going on in the
world was at 6 and noon, and in between you are in a blank. He was
saying he thought he would do something about it. I swear to God, I
can remember the story like it was yesterday. And a year or so
later, he founded CNN.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner also liked Steinbrenner from the start. ``I guess George
was considered sort of a rebel among the baseball establishment, so
we had a natural affinity,'' he said. ``We were both considered bad
boys.''
</P>
<P>
   With good reason. Both men pushed baseball's envelope. Turner
once rolled a ball around the bases with his nose and rode an
ostrich in an on-field race. He was suspended by commissioner Bowie
Kuhn for taking over as manager for one Braves game.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner, just as outrageous, once dropped his pants for a
skit on ``Saturday Night Live'' and agreed to be photographed in a
Napoleon costume for Sports Illustrated. He was suspended twice,
once by Kuhn for illegal contributions to Richard Nixon's political
campaign and once by commissioner Faye Vincent for hiring a private
investigator to follow Dave Winfield, a Yankees player.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Ted and I) weren't Bowie Kuhn's types,'' Steinbrenner said.
``We dressed as we wished, and we didn't wear the black silk
stockings. (Kuhn) kind of had us targeted, the two of us. When Ted
was suspended for going into the dugout, I went and argued on his
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came into baseball, you walked in your first
(owners) meeting, and the American League sat on one side of the
room and the National League on the other. And the sanctimonious
group in front. It was like Appomattox Courthouse, the North vs.
the South. There was no togetherness. Ted was like a breath of
fresh air in there. Few of them realized it at the time. Geez, we
needed something to make it more exciting, and Ted made it more
exciting for fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner credits Turner with changing the complexion of the
sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason baseball has the television contract it does today
is because of Ted Turner,'' Steinbrenner said. ``He stood up in the
meeting and talked about television, and Bowie paid no attention to
him and kind of wrote him off.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner hasn't been written off since.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner said he and Turner did not make a bet during the
1996 World Series, and he doesn't expect to do it this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had won, I couldn't have paid him,'' Steinbrenner said.
But there's another side to that story: Steinbrenner knows Turner.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much money do I think Ted is carrying in his pocket right
now?'' Steinbrenner asked. ``Not enough to buy us lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
