<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What they're saying
 &HT;    By .J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Fifteen of the nation's foremost baseball writers
provide their thoughts on which team is better _ Yankees or Braves:
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY CHASS, New York Times:
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I have to say the Yankees, because they can't do
anything wrong. (Monday) is a perfect example of it. They were
playing Baltimore, down 3-0, and Ricky Ledee, who is replacing
Bernie Williams, comes up and hits a three-run homer. No matter who
is injured, somebody fills in. As good as the Braves starters are,
the Yankees have six. None of them might be Greg Maddux, but they
are deeper.''
</P>
<P>
   JERRY CRASNICK, Bloomberg Sports:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Yankees are the best, because I really have a lot
of concern about the Braves bullpen. They seem to be very
vulnerable in the late innings. The Yankees just seem to have a
certain something that few teams have. They seem to have a certain
intangible; they have a lot of guys who know how to win.''
</P>
<P>
   HAL BODLEY, USA Today:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that probably for this year the Yankees are a better
team. But if you factor in the experience and pitching staff of the
Braves, they would have to get the edge. What I am saying is
everything is going right for the Yankees right now, but over the
long haul I think the Braves have the better team.''
</P>
<P>
   TOM KEEGAN, New York Post:
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say the Yankees, because they can beat you more ways.
They have speed, power, a real high on-base percentages and a deep
rotation like the Braves, a deeper bullpen than the Braves and a
deeper bench. And when you get to the postseason, I think it tends
to be low-scoring games, and not as many mistakes are made. So you
have to be able to win games other than hitting home runs, and I
think the Yankees have more ways to win games than the Braves.''
</P>
<P>
   LARRY STONE, Seattle Times:
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I would give the edge to the Yankees based on the
overall depth and bullpen. The Yankees have a guy go down, and they
have an All-Star caliber player to step in. They also have the best
bullpen in baseball. But the Braves aren't far behind.''
</P>
<P>
   MARC TOPKIN, St. Petersburg Times:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yankees are better. They have more ways to beat you. Right
now it is an easy pick.''
</P>
<P>
   BILL MADDEN, New York Daily News:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yankees are better for a number of reasons. No. 1 is the
bullpen. Obviously, the Braves bullpen has been their Achilles'
heel, and the Yankees have a deep bullpen. Another strength that
the Yankees have big-time over the Braves is their depth. The
Braves bench is very shallow compared to the Yankees. Braves. Both
are solid managers, and I don't think you could give either one the
edge. (Bobby) Cox's biggest problem is when he has to take out his
starters and go to that bullpen. When you take out Greg Maddux, and
the bullpen blows the game, any manager looks bad.''
</P>
<P>
   ROSS NEWHAN, Los Angeles Times:
</P>
<P>
   ``Right the Yankees slightly. I think they have better bullpen
depth, better bench depth and (are) stronger right now at second
and shortstop.''
</P>
<P>
   BOB ELLIOTT, Toronto Sun:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Yankees are the best. Atlanta is the home of the
WCW, and New York is closer to WWF headquarters. You know, the big
wrestling argument. And I think a lot of people argue about whether
the Braves are better or the Yankees. I think the difference is
Bernie Williams.''
</P>
<P>
   TOM VERDUCCI, Sports Illustrated:
</P>
<P>
   ``I give the edge to the Yankees. They have better depth,
especially in the bullpen. I do think these two teams are extremely
close, but I give the Yankees a very slight edge.''
</P>
<P>
   PAUL NEWBERRY, Associated Press, Atlanta:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Yankees are the better team right now. They seem
to have all facets of their game in order. That could change if the
Braves get their bullpen in order. I don't think there is a big
difference, but there is this uncertainty to the Braves bullpen
which gives the Yankees the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   STEVE MARANTZ, The Sporting News:
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a tough one. I would say the Yankees are better
because of their bench and bullpen. I think they maybe are better
offensively, top to bottom. The Braves clearly have the better
three starters. John Smoltz is a big element for the Braves and is
a question mark for this season. They seem less formidable without
him.''
</P>
<P>
   PETE WILLIAMS, USA Baseball Weekly:
</P>
<P>
   ``I will say until the Braves resolve their bullpen situation,
the Yankees look like the better team. I would say also on the
bench, and the Yankees don't have Chili Davis. I know bullpen and
bench are two areas that John Schuerholz traditionally addresses
around the trading deadline. But going into this series, I think
the Yankees clearly have a better team.''
</P>
<P>
   JON HEYMAN, Newsday:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Yankees are slightly better, because they have a
little more balance in their lineup and a little more depth on the
bench. I think top to bottom, the Yankee lineup is more difficult
to pitch to. Everybody is a threat in the Yankee lineup, while the
Braves rely more on a few great players.''
</P>
<P>
   PETER SCHMUCK, Baltimore Sun:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to go with the Braves. I just think that the Braves
starting rotation is more proven. It is no secret that it is the
best in baseball, and the Yankees are probably second-best. The
thing with the Yankees, they are depending on guys without knowing
if they can go the distance. Who knows what (Hideki) Irabu is going
to do in the second half? Offensively, I would have to give the
Yankees the advantage. The Braves pitching outweighs an offensive
advantage for the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
