<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LABOR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA LABOR NEGOTIATIONS GOING NOWHERE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The lasting image of Michael Jordan's epic,
title-clinching shot in Game 6 of the NBA Finals may have to last a
long time.
</P>
<P>
   By all appearances, the NBA is about to go into protracted
hibernation, and nightly SportsCenter images of Jordan and Pippen
will soon be replaced by Italian-suited attorneys muttering
something about ``base-year compensation.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA and the players association have nine days to break a
three-month stalemate on a new labor pact or face another
owners-imposed lockout of the players _ the league's second labor
stoppage in four years.
</P>
<P>
   Free agents will be frozen out. There will be no trades, no
player signings, no summer pro leagues, no NBA stars in the World
Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the two sides are so entrenched that the NBA faces the
very real possibility of tarnishing its record as the only U.S.
professional sports league never to lose regular-season games to a
labor stoppage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it certainly doesn't look good right now. We've got
less than two weeks left, and we really haven't made much
progress,'' said Russ Granik, NBA deputy commissioner and the
league's chief negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides are far apart right now,'' said Dan Wasserman,
spokesman for the players association.
</P>
<P>
   That's about as much as the two sides agree on, and that's bad
news for the league and for fans. Come July 1 _ the day free agents
are eligible to negotiate new contracts _ the owners will almost
certainly impose a lockout, leaving teams and players in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   The owners voted earlier this year to reopen the collective
bargaining agreement signed in 1995. Granik and Billy Hunter,
executive director of the players association, have met 10 times
since April 1, and are no closer to reaching agreement on the
fundamental issue _ the clause that allows teams to ignore the
salary cap when re-signing their free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Granik and Hunter will meet again Monday in what could be a
make-or-break negotiating session.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not optimistic right now about getting much done before
July 1,'' Granik said.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   At least a half-dozen issues _ including the length of rookie
contracts and testing players for marijuana use _ are on the table,
but there is only one deal-breaker: the so-called ``Larry Bird''
exception to the salary cap. It's the Bird clause that allows, for
example, the Chicago Bulls to sign Jordan to a $35 million annual
salary despite a leaguewide salary cap of $26.9 million per team.
</P>
<P>
   This ``soft cap'' has, according to Granik, thrown the league's
entire economy out of whack. Revenues are growing, but expenses _
i.e. player salaries _ are far outpacing that growth, according to
the league.
</P>
<P>
   When the players and owners signed the current pact and salary
structure in 1995, they agreed players would receive at least 48
percent of NBA revenues. This season the players' salaries totaled
57 percent, far exceeding the 51.8 percent trigger that allowed the
owners to reopen the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Granik said the NBA paid $1 billion in salaries and benefits
this year, $165 million more than projected.
</P>
<P>
   The league claims 14 to 15 teams will finish in the red this
year. The union claims the number is closer to four or five, and
the players association also notes that major-league baseball and
the NFL pay players 60 to 70 percent of revenues.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the NBA has not strayed from its insistence on a
``hard'' cap, meaning a phase-out of the Bird exception and an end
to the brief era of $100 million contracts. The hard cap is
anathema to the players, who view the Bird exception as an
untouchable issue.
</P>
<P>
   It may take the threat of canceling games this November to move
anyone toward center court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
