u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-OPEN-MAGGERT-HNS &LR;      06-20 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-MAGGERT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Maggert haunted by 3-putts
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JAYNE CUSTRED &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ It was the putter that betrayed Jeff Maggert on
Saturday during the third round of the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Three three-putts for bogeys on the treacherous Olympic Club
Lake Course tract was the difference between a very acceptable
2-over-par round of 72 and Maggert's disappointing 75. It also was
the difference between trailing leader Payne Stewart by three shots
or the six that Maggert will face going in today's final round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those three putts were the icing on the cake,'' Maggert said.
``Today was more putting than anything else. Those three were the
key holes for the round. Under conditions like these, you've got to
two-putt those holes. You can't give shots away like that.''
</P>
<P>
   And still expect to win the U.S. Open Golf Championship. That
was what was most discouraging of all. Maggert has finished fourth
in the Open in two of the last four years, and his back-to-back 69s
in the first two rounds of this tournament had put him in a great
position to finally get his first major victory.
</P>
<P>
   Now he faces an uphill battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take perfect golf tomorrow,'' Maggert said. ``So far,
4 under has been the low round this week. I'll probably need 5
under to have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Maggert's day ended up even more frustrating because he started
out so well. He opened with a birdie that helped him stay close to
playing partner Stewart, who made eagle on No. 1. Even the bogey 4
on No. 3 and the double-bogey 6 on No. 5 weren't too devastating
because Stewart had stumbled as well and there was plenty of golf
to be played.
</P>
<P>
   ``The turning point was No. 9,'' Maggert said. ``I drove it into
the light rough, and I had a good lie. I hit the front edge of the
green, on the fringe, and three-putted for bogey. Then I
three-putted for bogey on Nos. 11 and 12. And all of those were bad
first putts. They were all about 10-footers for par.''
</P>
<P>
   Maggert did manage to sink a nice 12-footer for birdie on No. 16
that got him back to 2 over for the tournament But the 17th hole
dealt him what might have been the fatal blow. Maggert hit what he
thought was a solid approach shot to the green, only to have the
ball catch the edge of the heavy greenside rough. He recovered with
a nice chip to within five feet but missed the par putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one I really needed to get in,'' Maggert said. ``But
that's the way it was today. Sometimes the ball doesn't do what you
want. I didn't feel like I struck the ball too poorly. I drove the
ball OK. It seemed like I'd get awkward bounces _ one or two feet
in one direction when I needed them to go in the other direction.''
</P>
<P>
   That has been the case too often for Maggert, who has 11
second-place finishes on tour. He has a solid record in major
championships _ in 22 major appearances since 1992, he has finished
in the top 10 eight times. But he still is seeking that big
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Maggert came close last year. He spent a good portion of the
final round locked in a battle for the title with eventual champion
Ernie Els, Tom Lehman and Colin Montgomerie. But a couple of bogeys
midway through the day forced him to play aggressively. And he
closed with back-to-back double bogeys and finished fourth.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Maggert was hoping for the chance to redeem himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought my game was good for the Open,'' Maggert
said. ``I think you learn it is the patience that you have to learn
to play the Open well. I think that is what I have done well the
last four, five years. This is not a golf tournament where you are
going to go out and expect to shoot 65s and 64s.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Maggert, that is so true. And it's unlikely
Maggert will be able to change that today. But he still intends to
try.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to get off to a good start,'' Maggert said. ``If I can
get a couple under on the front nine If I'm back to even par at the
turn, I've got a chance. Payne's in a tough position. He knows he
needs another round like today.''
</P>
<P>
   But Maggert needs even more than that. The Olympic Club is one
of the most difficult courses the pros have faced in recent years.
Even Maggert was surprised at what the course threw at the golfers
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough,'' Maggert said. ``I needed some good breaks, and
I just didn't get many. I was really trying to have fun. I kept my
head in it well. But 75 was just the best I could have done today.
I played and played and played, and that's just how many shots it
took.''
</P>
<P>
   Too many shots one more year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
